<FIRST>r a PM-DisneyStunts     10-18 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disney Stunts,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Inspect Stunt at Disney Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Safety complaints from stunt
workers at the new Disney-MGM Studios are being investigated by
federal inspectors for possible safety violations
   The tourist attraction says it is cooperating in the review, and
a company spokesman said Walt Disney World does not expect to be
cited by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration.
   Inspectors from OSHA's Atlanta office were called in after a
performer was involved in an accident last month during an outdoor
show that recreates scenes from Indiana Jones adventure movies.
   The stunt worker fell from a moving ladder and OSHA said the
complaints indicated the man suffered injuries to his head, neck,
back and right elbow.
   DUring the show, a cast of stuntpeople escape from exploding
jeeps, jump from buildings and re-enact other daring escapades that
Indiana Jones manages on celluloid. The show is performed several
times daily.
   Some workers complained that broken equipment was causing falls,
and smoke machines were irritating the workers' noses and throats.
They also complained of slippery footing and improperly placed
padding, used to cushion falls.
   ``I don't know of anything other than some minor falls,'' said
Disney's publicity director, Charlie Ridgway. ``I know that in the
training process and the whole business there are lots of sore
muscles, but there haven't been any serious accidents.''
   He said Disney has tried to ensure the safety of its workers,
and the company would be willing to accept any OSHA recommendations
for improvements.
   To assess the show's safety, OSHA's advisers will review the
procedures.
   ``This is really something new for us, so it may take several
weeks to complete,'' said Rafael Rodriguez, an OSHA industrial
hygienist.
</TEXT>
