<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle-Facts     10-18 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle-Facts,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Facts and Figures About Galileo</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Facts about the Galileo spacecraft,
its probe and its mission:
   ORBITER
   Height: 15 feet (30 feet with antenna extended)
   Mass: 5,870 pounds
   Payload: 227 pounds
   Instrument packages: 11
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PROBE
   Height: 34 inches
   Mass: 737 pounds
   Payload: 62 pounds
   Instrument packages: 6
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SCHEDULE:
   Oct. 18, 1989 _ Carried into Earth orbit by the space shuttle
Atlantis.
   Feb. 9, 1990 _ Galileo passes 9,300 miles from Venus, where it
will look for lightning and photograph the planet's cloud
circulation.
   Dec. 8, 1990 _ Passes within 620 miles of Earth, examines
composition of moon's far side and maps Earth's atmospheric
hydrogen.
   Oct. 29, 1991 _ Caps 10-month journey through the asteroid belt
by passing within 600 miles of 10-mile-wide asteroid Gaspra,
examines geology and composition.
   Dec. 8, 1992 _ Flies by Earth a second time, within 200 miles,
photographs moon's north pole to determine if ice exists, makes
time-lapse ``movie'' of Earth-moon system.
   Aug. 28, 1993 _ Second trip through asteroid belt, comes within
600 miles of 20-mile-wide asteroid Ida.
   July 1995 _ Probe separates from Galileo orbiter to achieve
better angle for later entry into Jupiter's atmosphere.
   Dec. 7, 1995 _ Orbiter and probe arrive at Jupiter, with orbiter
passing 620 miles from the moon Io to brake it into orbit. Probe
parachutes directly toward Jupiter's surface, sending atmospheric
data back to orbiter for 75 minutes before pressure destroys it.
   December 1995 to October 1997 _ Galileo's orbiter continues
circling Jupiter, relaying data to Earth for 22 months. It will
receive aid from Jupiter's moon in shaping its wide orbits.
</TEXT>
