<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 2345EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle-Means     10-18 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle-Means,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>What We Will Learn from Galileo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists hope the Galileo space
probe, carried into Earth orbit aboard the space shuttle Atlantis,
will find clues to the origin of the universe when it reaches
Jupiter in six years.
   The mission also will look for organic chemicals in the gasses
covering the largest planet, chemicals that could also have been
the basis for life on Earth.
   ``The Jupiter system is so full of exciting phenomenon that we
hardly know what's going on there,'' said Torrence Johnson, the
Galileo project's chief scientist. ``What we're trying to do is
learn fundamental things about how the universe was formed, how it
ticks and where we came from.''
   The planet Jupiter and its moons are in effect a mini-solar
system, and Jupiter itself is often called a star that never caught
fire. Its hydrogen-rich atmosphere should be a window into the
conditions that existed when the Sun and its planets formed.
   The small probe will radio back readings during its 75-minute
plunge into the fifth planet's atmosphere, but Galileo itself will
continue a wide orbit around Jupiter for 22 months, keeping track
of changes in its weather for the first long-term study of an outer
planet.
   While Jupiter is the main target, Galileo will first circle
Venus to learn how its clouds circulate and look for lightning.
Then the craft will fly twice by Earth, mapping hydrogen in the
home planet's atmosphere and photographing the moon's north pole to
look for ice.
   Galileo will also povide the first close-up data about
asteroids, passing within 600 miles of Gaspra and Ida on its way to
Jupiter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
