<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0517EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d i PM-Spain-Wife     10-18 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spain-Wife,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidacy of Prime Minister's Wife Raises Hackles</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report; an accompanying story is PM-Spain-Elections.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When word got out that the Socialist Party
was running Maria del Carmen Romero Lopez, a 42-year-old former
schoolteacher, for Parliament, the opposition cried foul and
likened her to Eva Peron and Imelda Marcos.
   Carmen Romero happens to be Mrs. Felipe Gonzalez, wife of
Spain's two-time prime minister who is running for re-election.
   Mrs. Romero, who uses her maiden name, was given the No. 3 spot
on her party's list for Cadiz, where seven of the current nine
deputies from the southern province are Socialists.
   Because of the system of proportioning parliamentary seats to
parties on the basis of their provincial votes, she is certain to
be elected.
   Mrs. Romero, mother of children aged 17, 16 and 10, has shunned
the limelight during her husband's seven years in office and rarely
accompanies him on official trips. She has not adopted any causes
or become involved in charitable work. She says Spain has only one
first lady, Queen Sofia, wife of King Juan Carlos.
   At the Socialist Party congress last year, she tossed red roses
at the Executive Committee that had just approved a 25 percent
minimum quota for women in party and government positions.
   Gonzalez has been noticably neutral about his wife's candidacy,
limiting himself to remarks about the ``lack of democratic
sentiment'' on the part of those who liken her to the wife of the
late Argentine leader Juan D. Peron. Although she never ran for
office, Eva Peron, also known as Evita, played a dominant political
role in Argentina in the 1940s until her death in 1952.
   Imelda Marcos also had an influential role in the Philippines
before her husband, the late Ferdinand E. Marcos, was ousted in
1986.
   Mrs. Romero says that as a member of Parliament she would
concentrate on issues related to women, education and youth
unemployment.
   Press response to her first campaign appearance Oct. 1 in the
town of Chiclana was less than enthusiastic.
   Jose Luis Guitierrez, a commentator for Diario 16, called her
political discourse ``outdated'' and her speaking voice ``not
exactly good.''
   In spite of her party's decision to promote women, Gutierrez
wrote, ``Carmen Romero is not just another woman and, for obvious
reasons, does not have the same rights and duties as other Spanish
women.''
   The feminist Lidia Falcon questioned Mrs. Romero's record and
says the invitation from the Cadiz branch of the Socialist Party to
run there seems more like ``an offer of an honorary presidency made
to queens and aristocrats than a recognition for past services.''
   But Cristina Almeida, a human rights attorney who is running for
Parliament on the opposition United Left ticket in Madrid, welcomed
Mrs. Romero's candidacy, saying she had ``all the right in the
world'' to seek office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0000EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Farley     10-18 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Farley,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Author of `Black Station' Books Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter L. Farley, whose ``Black Stallion''
books stirred the imaginations of millions of young readers and was
the basis of an Academy Award-winning movie, died after suffering a
heart attack. He was 73.
   Farley, who was admitted to Sarasota Memorial Hospital on
Sunday, died Monday evening.
   Farley, whose books have been translated into 20 languages and
have sold more than 12 million copies, recently completed his 21st
novel in the ``Black Stallion'' series, said Jenny Fanelli, a
Random House editor who worked with Farley on two of his books.
   The author's last novel, ``The Young Black Stallion,'' written
with his son, Steven, is set for release in December, Fanneli said
Tuesday.
   ``My great love was, and still is, horses,'' Farley said in an
interview last year. ``I wanted a pony as much as any boy or girl
could possibly want anything, but I never owned one.''
   Farley, who had lived in Venice, Fla. since 1946, was born in
Syracuse, N.Y. He started writing ``The Black Stallion'' as a
child, using his experiences with an uncle who was a famed horse
trainer.
   The final manuscript of the novel was delivered to Random House
in 1941, when Farley was still a high school student in New York
City and about the same age as his 17-year-old hero, Alec Ramsay.
   Farley's romantic tale about a young boy stranded on a desert
island with a spirited horse brought him $1,000.
   After Army service, he attended Columbia University, then
returned to writing and horses. He produced 20 more books in the
``Black Stallion'' series and wrote 11 other books, including
shorter workers for younger children.
   ``What he captured best is a child's love for a horse,'' Fanelli
said. ``His own love of horses shines through his books.''
   ``The Black Stallion'' was made into a movie produced by Francis
Ford Coppola in 1979. Farley had refused dozens of previous movie
offers, fearing the story would be lost in the translation to film.
   The movie received two Academy Award nominations, and was
followed by a sequel, ``The Black Stallion Returns.''
   Farley's success enabled him to own many horses. He and his
wife, Rosemary, spent their summers in the hills of central
Pennsylvania, where they owned a farm at Earlville.
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by a daughter, two sons
and a brother.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0001EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e PM-APArts:Hoffman     10-18 0837</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Hoffman,0859</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dustin Hoffman's Shylock Prepares for Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dustin Hoffman's Shylock on the London stage is
now a memory, leaving a legacy of mixed reviews, packed houses and
great expectations for Broadway, where he opens in December.
   Sir Peter Hall's production of Shakespeare's ``The Merchant of
Venice'' was the lone smash hit in an otherwise lackluster summer
for British drama. It opened June 1 at the Phoenix Theater for a
13-week run that was extended through Sept. 23.
   Hoffman as Shylock was a risky venture. It wasn't just a
question of ironing the New York inflections out of Hoffman's
voice, but of how the fastidious British theater-going public would
take to a Hollywood star attempting Shakespeare.
   ``I didn't quite know what it would be like. All I knew is I
would learn something,'' Hoffman said.
   Explaining the mixed reviews, he blamed the speed with which the
production was rushed onto the stage, due to his father's illness,
which forced him to spend time at his bedside in the United States.
   ``We opened in this play after 10 public performances, and my
performance for me was like those incisions you see from people
who've been operated on,'' he said in an August interview.
   ``You still see their fresh wounds and their stitches; now I'm
at a point where you can barely see the scars.''
   Shylock is the Jewish moneylender whose thirst for revenge
against Antonio (Leigh Lawson), the Venetian merchant of the title,
finds its match in the exactingly legalistic heiress, Portia
(Geraldine James).
   Hall, who directed the play, said that as an authentically
Jewish actor, Hoffman ``changed the part historically.''
   ```Merchant' seemed to me particularly right for him,'' Hall
said in an interview. ``Shylock is about the outsider, the man
coming into the society which he is foreign to, which was very much
Dustin's situation coming into an English theater company.''
   Assessing Hoffman's achievement toward the end of the London
run, Hall said: ``Shylock is wheeling and dealing and surviving,
and that's what Dustin seizes hold of. To me, he answers the
question, is Shylock comic or tragic, by saying he's both; he's a
man.''
   The Shylock character traditionally provokes the accusation that
Shakespeare was anti-Semitic, and anyone involved in staging ``The
Merchant of Venice'' knows how sensitively it must be handled.
   ``To have a Jewish actor play Shylock is mandatory in our age,''
said Hall. ``If you're going to talk about Jewishness, you'd better
do it from a position of integrity and knowledge, not ham acting.''
   Some of the play's success may have been due to renewed
enthusiasm for Shakespeare. But the real draw undoubtedly was
Hoffman, fresh from his second Academy Award for ``Rain Man,'' in a
play that marked both his British and his Shakespearean stage debut.
   Hoffman, who grew a beard for the show and shaved it off after
the last performance, eschewed above-the-title billing and appeared
half way down the cast list.
   But despite such modesty, the mixed reviews and a top ticket
price of 17.50 pounds ($28), expensive by London standards, the
play quickly sold out. Only the London mega-musicals such as
``Phantom of the Opera'' and ``Aspects of Love'' sold as many
tickets.
   The play starts New York performances Dec. 4 at the 46th St.
Theater, with an opening on Dec. 19.
   Hall recalled that Hoffman first thought of playing Hamlet, but
was judged too old at 52. Malvolio in ``Twelfth Night,'' another
possibility, was shelved for want of a suitable Viola. The two then
hit on Shylock, one of Shakespeare's most controversial parts and
also surprisingly small in light of its importance. Shylock appears
in only five scenes.
   A planned out-of-town tryout in Bath was canceled because of
Hoffman's father's illness, and Hoffman's performance had to evolve
during the run. The opening, said co-star Geraldine James, was
``very rushed.''
   ``Dustin hit his peak in the middle of the run,'' she said in an
interview. ``He hadn't got the confidence at the beginning ... and
I think he might have gone too much the other way (towards the
end), playing too much into the audience.''
   She said she found his attitude anything but starry. ``He was so
generous, spiritually and literally; he wouldn't have his name over
the title and insisted on me having the last curtain call.''
   Julia Wilson-Dickson, the production's dialogue coach, admired
Hoffman as ``a fanatical worker, a seeker after the truth ... but
perhaps a little more free in his enthusiasm'' than most British
actors.
   It fell to her to turn his ``dawg'' into ``dog,'' and ``bawnd''
into ``bond,'' and his performance over time got ``simpler, more
straightforward, and physically stronger vocally,'' she said in an
interview.
   ``The actual conception of it is exactly the same, but the
practical delivery has been honed greatly.''
   Could Hoffman tackle other Shakespeare parts? ``Absolutely,''
Wilson-Dickson said. ``I've told him so about 50 times _ and he's
definitely humble enough to ask.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0002EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-PinocchioCampaign Bjt   10-18 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pinocchio Campaign, Bjt,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Jersey Governor Hopefuls Air Dueling Pinocchio Ads</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a campaign that's given new meaning to
``stretching the truth,'' both candidates for New Jersey governor
are running TV ads that portray their opponents as Pinocchio, whose
nose gets longer with every lie.
   ``It has not exactly been an intellectual tea party,'' Kenneth
Connolly, campaign manager for Republican James Courter, said this
week.
   The name-calling between Courter and Democrat James Florio has
been denounced by popular two-term Republican Gov. Thomas H. Kean
and by newspaper editorials.
   Florio hit the huge New York and Philadelphia television markets
this month with commercials featuring Courter's nose getting longer
and longer as a narrator ticks off a series of his supposed lies
and misleading statements.
   Courter and his advisers liked the idea so much that they, too,
employed the wooden character from C. Collodi's ``The Adventures of
Pinocchio.''
   Courter's commercial showed millions of viewers the faces of
both congressmen. Florio's regular nose grows longer and longer,
while Courter's enlarged proboscis simultaneously shrinks back to
its regular shape.
   ``The reason we ran the Pinnochio spot is that Jim Florio on TV
called Jim Courter a liar. You simply cannot let that charge go
unanswered. We were forced to respond,'' Connolly said.
   Richard Sinding, president of the Center for Analysis of Public
Issues at Princeton University, called the campaign for governor
the dirtiest he has seen.
   Kean, who is barred by state law from seeking a third
consecutive four-year term, predicted the negative campaigning will
``depress the electorate. People will say neither of them are any
good.''
   Jon Shure, a Florio spokesman, defended the opening Pinocchio
ad, which blasted Courter's record in civil rights and
environmental protection.
   ``What's negative in this campaign is Jim Courter's record,''
Shure said. ``That's what our ad shows. That was an
attention-getting advice, a somewhat humorous way to make a serious
point.''
   The Courter campaign apparently did not enjoy it.
   ``Florio lied,'' the narrator says in the Republican's return
volley.
   ``Poor Jim Florio,'' the narrator concludes as Florio's nose
stretches into Pinocchian proportions. ``Even the newspapers say he
has an ethical cloud hanging over his head.''
   Courter is running an uphill battle against Florio in November's
election. Recent polls indicate he is trailing by between 14 and 23
points.
   At the end of the classic children's tale, Pinocchio turned into
a real boy.
   ``It's not clear at what stage in his adult life he moved to New
Jersey and decided to run for governor,'' said Adrian Heffern, a
political columnist for The Asbury Park Press. ``There are
suspicions that his consultants are the Fox and the Cat who led him
astray the first time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0016 </DOCNO>
