<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Quake 5thLd-Writethru   10-18 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Quake, 5th Ld-Writethru,a0853,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: National Guard Mobilizes; new material in grafs 3, 9 and 10.
Congressional reax. Editing to update.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Tuesday night he would
provide federal assistance to earthquake victims in California and
a spokesman said Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner would
``land as close as he can get'' to assess the damage.
   The president was informed of the earthquake after addressing a
Republican governors' dinner. He paused outside his limousine and
told reporters at a distance that ``the federal government will do
everything it can to help.''
   Skinner was flying overnight to California. Military officials
mobilized two National Guard units to aid California rescue
efforts. The Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) established
a command center at its headquarters in Washington. White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said ``they will coordinate all the
information and dispatch of whatever support they can provide.''
   White House Chief of Staff John Sununu said he had contacted the
office of California Gov. George Deukmejian. The governor was in
Frankfort, West Germany and Sununu authorized a U.S. Air Force
plane to fly Deukmejian immediately back to California.
   Sununu also phoned Vice President Dan Quayle, who was visiting
San Diego. ``The vice president was aware of the earthquake. There
was no experience of it that far south, however,'' Fitzwater said.
   Quayle was to return to Washington ``at about midnight,'' said
Fitzwater. ``He wanted to return, was scheduled to return, and we
saw no reason to suggest a change of plans.'' An hour later,
however, the White House said Quayle would remain overnight in
California and confer with Skinner on Wednesday.
   Skinner was being flown aboard a special military aircraft and
was to ``land as close as he can get,'' according to Fitzwater. He
said Marilyn Quayle was accompanying Skinner and was ``going out to
be part of the assessment team.'' She has made disaster relief a
special interest as the vice president's wife.
   Several Bay-area members of Congress also were aboard the flight
after calls from their home districts. ``There is extensive
damage,'' said Rep. Norman Mineta ``People are frightened out
there,'' said Rep. Don Edwards.
   National Guard spokesman Dan Donohue said two California Air
National Guard units were being activated.
   Donohue said the 129th Air Rescue and Recovery Group from
Moffett Naval Air Station and the 146th Tactical Airlift Wing at
Van Nuys and Channel Island would send helicopters, rescue and
recovery aircraft and cargo planes to the San Francisco area.
   ``It's a given they will get whatever disaster aid is called
for,'' he said.
   Fitzwater said Sununu had ``talked to officials at Department of
Defense, and they will be prepared to help in any way they can,
coordinating again through FEMA.''
   Fitzwater said FEMA would keep Sununu informed. No top officials
planned to stay at the White House throughout the night, Fitzwater
said, and the president got his final briefing of the evening from
Sununu at 10:45 p.m.
   Reporters learned of the earthquake while Bush was just
beginning his address at the ballroom in the Capital Hilton, a few
blocks from the White House.
   Fitzwater described how Bush was informed after he finished his
speech: ``We handed him the note just as he was coming off and he
read it and just said _ mentioned something to Barbara, `Look at
this. It looks like a very serious problem. Do we know anything
more about it?'...
   Said Bush: ``John (Sununu) called the governor's office and got
some information there. The governor's out of the country but we're
beginning to get a lot of information back here and obviously the
federal government will do everything that it possibly can to help.
But at this point we're just assessing _ ''
   White House domestic adviser Roger Porter, informed by ABC-TV
correspondent Brit Hume, darted out of the room to gather
information. Sununu, who was also at the dinner along with Skinner,
five other Cabinet members and numerous other top administration
officials, also left the ballroom to try to contact the governor's
office in California.
</TEXT>
