<FIRST>u w AM-SFEarthquake-Phones     10-18 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Earthquake-Phones,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T Lines Flooded to Bay Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Corp. appealed
to the nation Thursday night not to try telephoning
earthquake-wracked San Francisco.
   The company said it blocked part of a flood of calls into the
area so San Franciscans could call out.
   AT&amp;T spokesman Herb Linnen said 1 million attempted long
distance calls were recorded on the AT&amp;T network at 9 p.m., roughly
2{ times the normal volume.
   He said network managers in 12 locations applied controls to
block calls into the San Francisco area so there would be circuits
for people to call out.
   Those controls were still in place late Tuesday night. ``We'll
play it by ear'' in deciding when to remove them, Linnen said.
   ``We are urging people elsewhere to not call into that area so
we can devote more of our circuits to what we're trying to do _
give priority to calls coming out of that affected area,'' he said,
and this request will apply until further notice.
   ``The veterans up there in Bedminister N.J. (AT&amp;T's control
center for its long-distance network) tell me they have never seen
anything like they have seen tonight in monitoring the nationwide
network,'' Linnen said.
   Some callers from elsewhere in the nation could not place calls
to countries on the Pacific Rim because the AT&amp;T switching center
at Sacramento, Calif., which handles those calls, was jammed with
calls fro San Francisco.
   ``We have asked the foreign telephone administrations in Pacific
Rim countries to block calls coming into the Bay area in order to
take some of the load off,'' said Linnen.
   AT&amp;T handles about 70 percent of the nation's long-distance
calls.
</TEXT>
