<FIRST>u p AM-MississippiEln 4thLd-Writethru a0836 10-18 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mississippi Eln, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0836,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key GOP Seat Up For Grabs in 5th Mspi District</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with final results, Anderson quote, other
details, background; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Sen. Gene Taylor won an overwhelming
victory over Republican Tom Anderson in a special congressional
election Tuesday, giving the Democrats all five of Mississippi's
U.S. House seats for the first time in 17 years.
   With all 372 precincts reporting in the race to pick a successor
to the late U.S. Rep. Larkin Smith, Taylor had 83,093 votes, or 65
percent, to 44,430, or 35 percent for Anderson, a veteran
Washington aide.
   The GOP, which holds both of Mississippi's U.S. Senate seats,
lost its only House seat, which it had held since 1972. Smith, a
Republican, died in a small plane crash in August.
   Taylor carried all but one of the 12 counties in the 5th
District in Mississippi's southeastern corner, which includes the
Gulf Coast and the cities of Biloxi, Gulfport and Hattiesburg.
   ``I'm kind of bewildered by the numbers,'' Taylor, 36, said in a
telephone interview from Biloxi on Tuesday night. ``We hoped to
win, but we're overwhelmed.''
   Taylor, a conservative, said residents of the district ``can
expect someone who is going to go to bat. Above all, I hope they
come to expect honest government.'' He said he would ask to be
sworn in next Tuesday.
   Anderson conceded defeat around 8:30 p.m., saying he hadn't had
enough time to build a successful campaign.
   ``We came from nowhere, we worked hard,'' he said. ``It's been
the longest 50 days of my life.''
   Taylor represented Bay St. Louis in the state Senate. Anderson,
43, was a longtime chief of staff to U.S. Sen. Trent Lott, who held
the seat for the Republicans for 16 years before going on to the
Senate. Smith defeated Taylor for the post last year.
   The GOP showed the importance they place on the seat in the
amount of money Anderson spent, a campaign appearance by President
Bush and Lott's visibility. Anderson spent about $500,000, roughly
five times Taylor's spending.
   ``That district is important to us not because it has been in
Republican hands for so long,'' said state Democratic Chairman Ed
Cole. ``That's one of the reasons.
   ``But that district represents the best of what Mississippi has
to offer in that it has the strongest economy, the highest per
capita income, the highest technology base and the greatest
population growth in the last 10 years.''
   In the primary Oct. 3, Taylor got 42 percent of the vote and
Anderson 37 percent. Attorney General Mike Moore, a Democrat, got
21 percent of the vote and was eliminated.
   Authorities found Smith and his pilot Aug. 14 in wreckage of
their single-engine plane. Smith, a popular law enforcement
official on the coast, was returning from opening ceremonies at the
Dixie World Series in Hattiesburg.
   Tuesday's election was the seventh special congressional
election this year. Of the previous six, Democrats won four,
Republicans two.
   There is an eighth such election scheduled for Nov. 7, in Texas
to fill the seat of the late Mickey Leland, who also died in a
plane crash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
