<DOCNO> AP891018-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0517EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--`Sinful'Shopping     10-18 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--`Sinful' Shopping,0143</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town-Sponsored Shopping Excursion Irks Merchants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRISTOL, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OK, downtown Bristol isn't Fifth Avenue.
But merchants were still plenty miffed when they found out the city
was organizing a shopping trip to take residents to Massachusetts.
   ``I am totally outraged,'' fumed Frank Johnson, president of the
Bristol Chamber of Commerce. ``I cannot express my outrage.''
   Now, Fall River isn't exactly Rodeo Drive, either. But the
southeastern Massachusetts city boasts more than 100 outlet stores,
enough to persuade Bristol's parks and recreation department to
organize a bus excursion for Nov. 4.
   For City Council member William Stortz, the trip transcended bad
politics.
   ``It is sinful to encourage and assist local people to shop
out-of-town,'' Stortz said.
   Mayor John J. Leone said it is too late to cancel the trip _ the
bus is already full.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
