<FIRST>r a PM-NoriegaPenPal     10-18 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Noriega Pen Pal,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega's Pen Pal Returns to United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schoolgirl Sarah York says her pen pal, Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, told her during her vacation in Panama that
he ``wants peace'' with the United States.
   The seventh-grader from Negaunee arrived in Miami on Tuesday
where U.S. Customs officials seized some candy she was bringing
back, said her mother, Pauline York. Sarah and her father, Michael,
then traveled on to Michigan.
   Sarah, 11, and her father went to the Central American country
days after Noriega's defense forces quashed a coup.
   ``I wanted to go to see for myself,'' she said in Miami. ``I see
a country that really wants peace with the U.S.''
   She said she visited Noriega on Oct. 11.
   ``He told me he wanted peace, and the U.S. to be friends without
one country trying to manipulate the other ... without making
Panama another U.S.,'' Sarah said.
   ``I've heard he's a Buddhist, a bigot, a bisexual,'' her father
said of the Panamanian leader. ``I've heard everything from you
people (the media), and he's not.''
   Sarah said she also spent time fishing and swimming with other
Panamanian friends she met last October when she visited the
country as Noriega's guest.
   Sarah began writing Noriega in March 1988, shortly after he was
indicted in the United States on drug-trafficking charges.
   Editorials condemning the trip and her friendship with Noriega
appeared during her visit. Rep. Bob Davis, R-Mich., said Sarah's
red-carpet treatment in Panama was embarrassing for the United
States.
</TEXT>
