<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--HistoricLandmark     10-18 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Historic Landmark,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steel Plant Designated National Historic Landmark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHNSTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cambria Iron Co., the country's
leading producer of steel rails 120 years ago, was designated a
national historic landmark.
   Federal, state and local government officials and
representatives of Bethlehem Steel Corp., which is a successor of
Cambria Iron, gathered in Bethlehem's lower works Tuesday to
dedicate the remaining iron company buildings and the entire
Johnstown Plant.
   Cambria Iron was renowned for its technological innovations and
the manufacture of iron and steel rail.
   ``We draw only the most significant historic sites to consider
as national historic landmarks,'' said Jerry Rogers, an associate
director for the National Park Service.
   Officials for the park service and Bethlehem stressed that
Cambria's impact extended beyond such technical innovations as the
three-high rolling mill and first steel-rail production in the
United States. The company also trained a generation of steel
innovators and helped to shape late-19th century industrial society.
</TEXT>
