<DOCNO> AP891018-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0208EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-YellowstoneTimber Bjt   10-18 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yellowstone Timber, Bjt,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Oppose Proposed Timber Traffic Through Yellowstone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New National Park Service Director James
Ridenour faces his first big test among environmentalists as he
ponders whether to allow about 20,000 truckloads of timber to go to
mill through Yellowstone Park.
   ``If he does the wrong thing, he'll see us in court,'' said
Steve Whitney of the Wilderness Society.
   Federal law prohibits commercial operations in the parks, except
in emergencies, Whitney said.
   National parks spokesman George Berklacy said Interior
Department lawyers are reviewing the matter. Yellowstone Park
Superintendent Robert Barbee is due in Washington on Thursday to
discuss the problem with Ridenour.
   The timber, in national forests bordering Yellowstone, amounts
to about 40 million board feet from trees that were partially
burned when fire blazed out of control in the park last year.
   Anxious to get rid of the wood to speed new tree growth, the
U.S. Forest Service sold the timber to Brand-S Lumber Co. in
Livingston, Mont., for about $1 per 1,000 board feet.
   Brand-S, the closest lumber mill to the burned forests, is about
100 miles away _ if you drive through Yellowstone.
   ``We could go around the park, but it would cost more money,''
said Doug Crandall, Brand-S manager.
   It's about 75 miles farther to drive around the park, Crandall
said, adding that that route is a more difficult pass through the
mountains and is not cleared during the winter.
   Hoping for approval soon from the National Parks, Brand-S is
cutting down trees and piling up timber.
   ``We have about half a million board feet cut,'' said Crandall.
Leaving a dead tree standing diminishes its value because of
deterioration, he said.
   ``I know the Wilderness Society is concerned about a bad
precedent, but these circumstances are unusual and abnormal _ a
once in a lifetime occurrence,'' Crandall said.
   Crandall said his company has promised to repair any damage
caused by the trucks, but that doesn't satisfy the Wilderness
Society.
   ``We will challenge any effort to haul through the national
parks,'' said Michael Scott, Northern Rockies regional director for
the society.
   The trucks would go through an important grizzly bear habitat,
he said, adding that the potential damage to the bears and other
wildlife could not be repaired with dollars.
   ``A park is supposed to be a place apart from the normal
commerce of the world,'' said Scott. ``It is not designed to be a
throughway from commercial operations.''
   Berklacy said Ridenour will rely heavily on Barbee's
recommendation, which a spokeswoman at Yellowstone said has not yet
been made. Barbee was not available for comment.
   ``If he (Ridenour) errs he will err on the side of environmental
concerns,'' said Berklacy. ``At this point, there is some question
about legality. He has questions about impacts on the roads and
visitor activity and the wildlife.''
   Both Whitney and his assistant at the Wilderness Society, Brian
Culhane, say ``a new breeze is blowing at Interior'' since the
Reagan administration appointees left office, but they are
withholding judgment on Ridenour to see whether his actions match
his words.
   ``The rhetoric is good,'' said Culhane, citing a recent Ridenour
speech in which the director told park officials to more actively
protect the parks against external threats.
   Culhane said Ridenour's decision on hauling timber in
Yellowstone will be the first major test.
   ``We're talking about the world's first national park,'' he
said. ``If we don't start with Yellowstone, where are we going to?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0209EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lottery-Schools     10-18 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lottery-Schools,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Facing Constricted Budget, School Board Takes Chance at Lottery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLYOKE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most folks buying tickets for a shot at a
$40 million lottery daydream about mansions and yachts, but nine
Holyoke residents have a different hope _ ending their school
district's financial crisis.
   The nine members of the city's school committee anted up $1 each
to play this week's Mass Millions game.
   ``We thought it was an excellent idea,'' member Bill Collamore
said Tuesday. ``It got a lot of people worked up and we're very
happy.''
   The idea surfaced at Monday night's school committee meeting. A
member who works for the Massachusetts Lottery Commission, and
therefore cannot play it, suggested that the board buy a few
tickets and then have them notarized so that winnings would go to
Holyoke schools.
   Members immediately started digging into their pockets to come
up with the money for the $1 tickets.
   Odds against winning are more than 9 million to one, but
Collamore said Holyoke schools need any help they can get.
   ``You know the city of Holyoke is in dire straits for money. Our
school system is in really bad shape,'' he said.
   Because of state budget cuts, the School Department had to trim
$10 million from its budget request this year, getting $29 million.
That meant laying off 107 people and cutting some programs, such as
music, Collamore said.
   The school committee joins millions of people hoping for the big
prize. Last week, the lottery commission did $11.5 million in
sales, spokesman Dave Ellis said Tuesday. There was no winner
Friday and sales are expected to be about $15 million this week.
   If the School Committee should win in Friday's drawing, the
expected jackpot would be $1 million more than the original budget
request, Collamore noted.
   He said he does not think that committee members would have any
problems seeing the fortune go to school coffers.
   ``We would be very very happy to have this money and to help out
the students,'' Collamore said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
