<FIRST>r a PM-PhiladelphiaFire     10-18 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philadelphia Fire,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Row House Fire Kills Seven in Philadelphia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that swept through a three-story row
house, killing five children and two adults, appears to have been
accidental, fire officials said.
   However, Fire Commissioner Roger Ulshafer stressed that the
cause of Tuesday morning's blaze _ the worst in the city in more
than three years _ had not been determined.
   Ulshafer said the house apparently had no smoke alarms, which
are not required in older, private homes. Three of the dead were
found near a window, he said.
   The victims were the father, son and five grandchildren of June
Scott, who escaped unharmed with a 5-year-old grandchild.
   ``It's a very great, great, great tragedy,'' Mrs. Scott said.
``You don't know how I feel about losing my father and my baby boy
and five little babies that couldn't even help themselves.''
   Ray Belikoff, an investigator with the city Medical Examiner's
Office, identified the victims as Clyde Staples, 66; Emerson Lee,
19; Joseph Lee, 7; Jamal Lee, 3; Jeffrey Lee, 3; Andrell McCoy, 5,
and Shanta McCoy, 3.
   Ian Baldwin, who lives across the street, said he and other
neighbors tried to enter the burning house from the rear. ``There
was too much smoke,'' he said.
   The fire was the city's deadliest since May 1986, when an
arsonist killed nine people in an apartment complex in northeast
Philadelphia.
</TEXT>
