<DOCNO> AP891018-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0218EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HomelessNewlyweds     10-18 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Homeless Newlyweds,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Holds Wedding Reception On Mean Streets Where They Live</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newlyweds Tammy McZeal and Albert Franco
staged their wedding reception on a sidewalk in downtown's Skid Row
_ because they are homeless and the sidewalk is their home.
   ``We live in the area. Why should we pretend to be something
that we're not?'' the 35-year-old Franco said as he sat at the pink
and white wedding table across the street from the St. Vincent de
Paul Men's Center.
   The couple fled from TV cameras Sunday into the county
courthouse to exchange wedding vows, then had the sidewalk
reception. Plastic plates and cups and a bouquet of cloth flowers
were set out next to a busy food line.
   ``I figure, why have something you can't afford and be away from
the people that you know?'' said the new Mrs. Franco, 18, who wore
a lacy white dress and bridal veil provided by a church group.
   Women from the West Angeles Church of God and Christ also
provided wedding gifts, the cake, and even money for the marriage
license.
   The Rev. James Shaw, who ministers to Skid Row residents, met
the couple in his ministry's food line and persuaded them to
legalize their union after he found out they were living together.
   Franco said he and his bride will not stay on Skid Row much
longer.
   ``You have to crawl before you walk,'' he said. ``Now it's time
for us to walk.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
