<FIRST>r w PM-BlindDiplomat     10-18 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blind Diplomat,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Service Candidate Wants Equal Treatment as Diplomat</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman trying to become the first blind
person in the U.S. Foreign Service says he wants to become a true
diplomat and not be swept into a sheltered corner reserved for the
handicapped.
   ``Any attempt to categorize blind people means separation, and
separation is a denial of equality,'' 47-year-old Avraham Rabby
told a joint meeting of House Foreign Affairs and Civil Service
subcommittees on Tuesday.
   The Oxford-educated Rabby is near his goal of joining the
Foreign Service after a 15-year effort following the State
Department's announcement last week that it would no longer bar
candidates just because of their blindness.
   Rabby, who lives in New York City, said he hopes he and blind
diplomats who may follow him will have their handicap considered
``as merely one characteristic in a normal individual who, like any
sighted Foreign Service officer, brings to the service a wide
variety of strengths and weaknesses.''
   ``Blind people are as different from one another as sighted
people,'' Rabby said. ``There is no such thing as a category
labled, ``The Blind.''
   He objected to what he called the State Department's past
assumption that ``if one is blind, one is necessarily slow,
inattentive to one's environment, and hopelessly vulnerable to any
international terrorist who may be intent on doing harm.''
   Describing his long battle to become a member of the Foreign
Service, Rabby noted his honors degree from Oxford University in
Spanish and French, his master's degree in business administration
from the University of Chicago and his success leading a business
aimed at helping the handicapped begin careers.
   Although he passed the Foreign Service entrance examination
several times, Rabby said his candidacy was always rejected because
of his blindness, with officials offering one explanation after
another of why that was a disqualification.
   But last week the State Department announced it was reversing
its policy.
   Rabby, in what he called ``that welcome telephone call,'' was
told he could meet with department officials to discuss the terms
and conditions of his employment as a diplomat.
   ``It's historic, and it's one of those occasions when you can be
joyful,'' said Rep. Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn., who fought for Rabby's
appointment.
   Ambassador Edward J. Perkins, the new director general of the
Foreign Service, told the panel the agency had decided it could
make accomodations for blind people ``just as we do for sighted
people, based on what they can accomplish.''
   Sikorski and other panel members advised Rabby not to settle for
an inferior Foreign Service post.
   Some said they would not object if he were named as an
ambassador.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0225EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru a0470 10-18 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalist, Judge Slain; Judicial Workers Strike Over Protection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to CLARIFY that Vargas Escobar eighth news
industry worker, not journalist, killed since crackdown began. Picks up
7th, `The journalist ...' ^By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's judges went on strike to
protest a colleague's assassination and gunmen killed yet another
journalist, the eighth news industry worker slain since the
government launched its all-out war on cocaine barons.
   An anonymous caller claiming to speak for drug traffickers took
responsibility for Tuesday's killing of Hector Jimenez Rodriguez, a
federal appeals court judge in the cocaine trafficking center of
Medellin.
   Hours later in Medellin, assassins gunned down radio journalist
Diego Vargas Escobar in similar fashion, police said.
   The slaying of Jimenez, 55, sparked a three-day strike by about
17,000 judicial workers, including most of Colombia's judges, to
demand more protection from drug gangs.
   Traffickers seek through murder, bombings and threats to force
an end to the government's crackdown on Colombia's cocaine cartels,
which was launched after the Aug. 18 slaying of presidential
candidate Luis Carlos Galan, an anti-drug crusader.
   Vargas Escobar, 54, was the eighth news industry worker slain
since the crackdown began. A radio journalist said Vargas Escobar,
who worked for the Medellin station La Voz de las Americas, had
recently received death threats.
   The journalist, who did not want to be identified for security
reasons, said he did not know who made the threats.
   In anonymous calls to radio stations last week, The
Extraditables _ alleged traffickers wanted in the United States _
claimed responsiblity for the slayings of two journalists in
Medellin.
   Police said Jimenez was about to step into the car of a
colleague outside his home when two men pulled up on a motorcycle
and one strolled over and shot the judge six times.
   An anonymous caller told a radio station in Medellin that The
Extraditables killed him in retaliation for the extradition of
Colombian drug suspects to the United States.
   Colombia has extradited four suspects since President Virgilio
Barco initiated the crackdown, and The Extraditables have promised
that they would kill 10 judges for every drug dealer extradited.
   None of the 12 alleged top Colombian drug bosses wanted by the
United States have been captured, but the government has seized
millions of dollars in their alleged assets.
   Jimenez was a federal appeals court judge for 20 years in
Medellin. All federal judges in the city have handled drug matters,
but it was not known whether Jimenez had any cases recently.
   The court workers' union declared a 72-hour strike to demand
more protection for the judicial branch.
   Various figures are given on the number of judges slain in
Colombia. The court workers' union says 221 court employees,
including 42 judges, have been killed during the past 12 years,
many of them by drug traffickers.
   Union officials said Colombia's 4,600 judges are still waiting
to receive bullet-proof vests as part of a $19 million U.S. aid
program to protect them.
   ``The justice ministry told us some time ago that it had
received just 15 bullet-proof vests and would distribute them
soon,'' said Yolanda Parra, an administrator at the court worker's
union. ``But judges have still not gotten anything.''
   The union's president, Antonio Suarez, met late Tuesday with the
country's justice minister, Roberto Salazar Manrique, to repeat
judges' demands for more government protection.
   Ms. Parra said judicial officials had sent numerous messages
expressing their security concerns but had received no response
from the ministry.
   ``Part of the problem has been the instablity at the ministry,''
she said, referring to the recent resignation of Monica de Greiff,
who became justice minister July 16 and quit 70 days later.
   Former Communications Minister Carlos Lemos Simmonds took on the
duties of justice minister until Oct. 8, when Roberto Salazar
Manrique was named to the post.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
