<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0251EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     10-18 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Sees French Market Changing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Take a look at the potatoes in France if you
want to learn something about the local lifestyle.
   ``Four years ago it was usual to see sacks of unwashed potatoes
on supermarket shelves, but such presentation is no longer
acceptable,'' says an Agriculture Department report.
   Today is is usual for raw potatoes, sacked or loose, to be
washed before they are presented to shoppers, the report said. And
many French food buyers are opting for frozen, precooked potatoes.
   The department's Foreign Agricultural Service said the
coming-of-age of France's baby boomers, along with fewer
adolescents and a rapid increase in senior citizens, has meant a
rise in demand for more conveniently packaged or prepared foods.
   ``Over two-fifths of French women are now in the workforce,''
the report said. ``They want foods that require less preparation
time, stimulating a rise of ready-to-eat and microwaveable foods.''
   A similar trend developed in the United States in the 1970s and
1980s, the agency said in a forthcoming issue of AgExporter
magazine. The study of French grocery habits was undertaken to help
give U.S. exporters a better understanding of the changing French
market.
   ``The increasing number of senior citizens also is creating a
market for products and packaging adapted to the special needs of
older consumers,'' the report said.
   And the leisurely French lunch is fading into memory. As the
typical French work week is becoming shorter, the midday meal is
more hurried, increasing the demand for meals at fast-food
restaurants and cafeterias.
   ``More and more French consumers prefer to make a weekly trip to
the supermarket rather than frequent and time-consuming trips to
butchers, bakers, produce markets and other small specialty
shops,'' the report said.
   The preference for supermarket or ``hypermarket'' shopping is
especially evident among single-person and two-income households,
where time for shopping is limited.
   Another result of the changes has been the domination of big
supermarkets in the French retail grocery industry. They accounted
for 46 percent of grocery purchases in 1987, compared with 37
percent in 1983, the report said.
   This year, for the first time, French shoppers are estimated to
buy more than 50 percent of their food in the big hypermarkets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says private
exporters have sold China additional U.S. wheat under a price
subsidy program.
   F. Paul Dickerson, general sales manager for the department's
Foreign Agricultural Service, said Tuesday that three private
exporting companies made the deals for a total of 300,000 metric
tons under the department's Export Enhancement Program, or EEP.
   The sales were part of 2 million tons authorized China under EEP
last Feb. 27. With the latest EEP approvals, China has 340,000 tons
remaining to be used under the current authorization.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat. The latest sales would be about 11 million bushels. At
current prices estimated by USDA at $3.85 per bushel, the wheat
would have a farm value of around $42 million.
   Under EEP arrangements, private exporters can sell U.S.
commodities at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in
selected overseas markets and then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
   Dickerson said the latest subsidies averaged $12.81 per ton, or
about 35 cents per bushel.
   The subsidized sales were handled by the Peavey Co., 210,000
tons; Cargill Inc., 50,000; and Bunge Corp., 40,000.
   With the latest sales, China has bought about 4.3 million tons
of U.S. wheat for delivery in the 1989-90 marketing year that began
on June 1, most of it without subsidies. In 1988-89, China bought
more than 8 million tons of U.S. wheat, all of it under the EEP
program.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dry weather last week helped farmers take a
big bite out of field work, including rapid progress in the fall
harvests of corn and soybeans, says the government's Joint
Agricultural Weather Facility.
   ``Rain was needed in the Great Plains to promote winter wheat
emergence and development,'' the facility said Tuesday. ``Soil
moisture was short to adequate in the Great Plains and most of the
West, and adequate in the East. Soil moisture was adequate to short
in the Delta.''
   The facility, operated by the Agriculture and Commerce
departments, reported that by the end of the Oct. 9-15 week an
estimated 81 percent of the winter wheat had been planted, nine
percentage points ahead of normal.
   About 46 percent of the corn had been harvested, two points
ahead of normal, and 55 percent of the soybeans, eight points ahead.
   The cotton harvest, however, was only 23 percent completed, nine
points behind the normal pace.
</TEXT>
