<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0245EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a BC-Quake-OaklandScene     10-18 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Quake-Oakland Scene,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Oakland, Shock as Quake Toll Rose</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brick walls and stairwells collapsed and
cheers for the home team turned to horror as thousands of Oakland
residents struggled through the killer earthquake that rocked the
Bay Area.
   As workers frantically tried to reach victims trapped in their
vehicles between two concrete slabs on Interstate 880, Dr. Carter
Clements, assistant chief of the emergency department at Oakland's
Highland Hospital, prepared for the worst.
   ``I expect a lot of people unfortunately are going to die at the
scene of their injuries because of the difficulty of getting them
out,'' Clements said.
   ``You can't drop that much concrete on a car and get out of it.
... I'm afraid a lot of people will be dead.''
   At least 200 people were killed in their cars when a mile-long
section of the upper level of Interstate 880 collapsed onto the
lower level, said Marty Boyer, the Alameda County public
information officer. County Sheriff Charles Plummer confirmed the
death toll of 200 people.
   Clements said that more injuries were likely as the hours passed.
   ``My guess is that we're going to see, over the next 12 to 24
hours, injuries related to the quake but not severe injuries,'' he
said.
   At Jack London Square, a crowd gathered to watch the World
Series game between the A's and San Francisco Giants on a giant
television screen. At first, the fans thought the quake was not
severe, and even applauded. But when the screen flashed to a
collapsed Bay Bridge, there was horrified silence.
   ``They tell you this is going to happen but I never believed
it,'' one shaken fan told The Tribune of Oakland.
   Caroline Thomas was at work in a brick building at 13th Street
and Broadway when the earthquake struck. When the shaking stopped,
she ran for the stairwell.
   It wasn't there.
   ``My God, it collapsed just like that,'' she said after a
terrifying walk down an eight-story fire department ladder.
   Just a few doors away, Anita Williams stood shaking, clutching
her chest and trying to regain control.
   ``The buildings swayed, the walls jerked and cracked,'' she
said, adding that she ran from her building and discovered part of
its facade littering the street with rubble.
   As a BART train jerked on its track, Robert Steller thought,
``This is what it feels like to die.''
   In Oakland's Chinatown, people gathered on the sidewalks,
comparing notes in rapid-fire Cantonese.
   And throughout the city, neighbors and shop owners opened their
homes to strangers, allowing them to make frantic calls home.
   On streets littered with glass and plaster, people lined up 10
deep at pay phones to say they were OK. Some of the city's grandest
old buildings showed the effects of the quake, their windows
shattered.
</TEXT>
