<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-18 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Rise, Dollar Inches Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
moderately Wednesday, while the dollar inched down against the
Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 111.48 points, or 0.32
percent, to 35,107.56. It had gained 527.39 points Tuesday, the
second-largest one-day gain this year. The largest rise was a
793.96 gain on Mar. 28.
   The dollar ended at 142.10 yen, down 0.15 yen from Tuesday's
142.25-yen close. It started higher at 142.55 yen and moved between
142.05 yen and 142.63 yen during the day.
   Earlier trading was mixed, and prices hit a plateau when some
investors sold issues for arbitrage deals to make profits, but the
Nikkei index rose quickly as participants picked up steel,
construction and food issues, said Tomoyuki Morimoto, a dealer with
New Japan Securities, Co., Ltd. in Tokyo.
   He said the Tokyo market did not react negatively to news
reports shortly after the market's opening about a severe
earthquake in the San Francisco area, measuring 6.9 on the Richter
scale.
   In currency dealings, the dollar remained higher following its
strength in New York despite a larger-than-expected U.S. trade
deficit reported Tuesday, traders said.
   The deficit rose to $10.77 billion in August, up from a revised
$8.24 billion in July.
   ``The exchange rates moved little as market players had no idea
why the dollar remained strong despite negative news to the
dollar,'' including Friday's stock plunge and a widened trade
deficit, said a trader with the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``Because market players were inclined to avoid making major
moves, the currency fluctuation remained small,'' he said.
   The trader said the news about the earthquake in San Francisco
had only a small effect although some American speculative
investors sold the dollar because of the disaster.
 
</TEXT>
