<DOCNO> AP891018-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0306EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-LincolnS&amp;L     10-18 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lincoln S&amp;L,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDIC Investigating Contributions to Five Senators</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal bank regulators are investigating the
legality of large political contributions from a Phoenix
millionaire to five senators who intervened on behalf of his failed
savings and loan association.
   ``We will be looking at every piece of evidence we can find to
determine whether or not laws were violated with respect to
political contributions'' by Charles H. Keating, Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. Chairman L. William Seidman said Tuesday in sworn
testimony before the House Banking Committee.
   Keating, chairman of American Continental Corp., the parent
company of Lincoln Savings and Loan Association of Irvine, Calif.,
gave money to the campaigns of Sens. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.;
Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.; John McCain, R-Ariz.; John Glenn,
D-Ohio, and Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich.
   In April 1987, the five met with regulators on Keating's behalf.
   DeConcini and Riegle have since returned Keating's
contributions, but the citizens' group Common Cause last week asked
the Senate Ethics Committee to investigate the matter.
   Common Cause also asked the Justice Department to determine
whether the contributions violated the law, but Seidman's statement
is the first sign that a federal agency is actively pursuing the
matter.
   Meanwhile, Seidman suggested strongly that the government waited
three years too long before trying to contain the Lincoln failure,
expected to be the nation's costliest.
   The FDIC chief said if his agency had been regulating Lincoln it
would have sought in 1986 to take it over or issue an order
stopping abuses.
   That would have prevented some of what Seidman estimates will be
a $1.5 billion to $2 billion loss to taxpayers. The government took
control of the thrift in April.
   ``We're looking at the biggest bank heist in history,'' said
Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, at the first of four scheduled hearings on
Lincoln.
   Seidman refrained from directly criticizing M. Danny Wall, the
top U.S. thrift regulator. But his assessment raised questions
about Wall's decision to delay action against Lincoln from
mid-1987, when he took office, until April 14 of this year.
   Lincoln was seized by Wall's agency, the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board, and turned over the FDIC, which insures bank and S&amp;L
deposits. Last month the government filed a $1.1 billion civil
fraud and racketeering suit charging that Keating, his family and
associates diverted Lincoln's deposits for their personal use.
   A March 12, 1986, examination by the San Francisco branch of the
bank board found that Lincoln had violated rules limiting risky
direct investments in commercial ventures, was not in compliance
with accounting standards, had substantial loan losses, had
inadequate and missing records and was speculating in junk bonds.
   ``My staff indicated that had we made such findings in one of
our own institutions, we would have sought an immediate
cease-and-desist order to stop the hazardous operations,'' Seidman
said.
   The focus of the House panel's probe is Wall's decision, after
meeting with Keating, to order a second examination by
Washington-based regulators to confirm the findings of the San
Francisco office, delaying action against the thrift.
   However, committee chairman Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas,
said he has not ruled out asking the senators to appear before the
panel if later testimony shows their intervention caused the delay.
   Gonzalez said Cranston offered about a month ago to appear
before the committee. Riegle issued a statement saying he was
providing information to the Senate ethics panel and was prepared
to share the same information with the House.
   Seidman also testified it was ``fairly clear'' Keating was
tipped off to the April 14 seizure because a day earlier American
Continental filed for bankruptcy, complicating government efforts
to recover part of the cost of the S&amp;L failure.
   Additional hearings are scheduled Oct. 24, Oct. 31 and Nov. 7.
Keating and Wall are not scheduled to appear until the last session.
</TEXT>
