<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0309EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpillPlans     10-18 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill Plans,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Tankers Without Spill Plans to be Barred From Valdez</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tanker operators will have to have
state-approved plans outlining how they would respond to oil spills
in Prince William Sound or they will be barred from loading oil in
Valdez, officials said.
   Alyeska Pipeline Service Co., a consortium of oil companies that
operates the trans-Alaska pipeline terminal in Valdez, has been
ordered not to load tankers without approved plans after Nov. 13,
said Dennis Kelso, commissioner of the state Department of
Environmental Conservation.
   ``Be ready to contain and clean up a spill and demonstrate it
with an approved plan _ that is the message,'' Kelso said in a
statement Monday.
   Letters warning of the new policy were sent last week to those
chartering, owning or operating tankers in the sound, where the
tanker Exxon Valdez spilled nearly 11 million gallons of oil March
24, creating the nation's largest oil spill.
   A response plan must show details including how workers and
equipment will be deployed to a spill, the methods of cleanup,
disposal and communications and response times, Kelso said.
   Officials previously assumed that tankers going in and out of
Valdez _ the southern end of the pipeline _ were covered by
Alyeska's spill-response plan, said Larry Dietrick, director of the
department's Division of Environmental Quality in Juneau.
   But there were problems in the early days of the Exxon Valdez
cleanup, and since then, Alyeska has said its obligation is limited
to the initial response after the spill, not the long-term efforts.
   In the future, if a tanker is claimed to be covered under
Alyeska's response plan, its owners must show evidence that Alyeska
will respond fully to its spills, Kelso said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
