<FIRST>r w PM-US-ChemicalWeapons     10-18 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Chemical Weapons,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Will Continue to Produce Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top U.S. arms control official says the Bush
administration is ``looking after the national security of the
United States'' by deciding to make new chemical weapons while it
seeks an international ban on the deadly weapons.
   ``It is not good to cut programs in anticipation of negotiations
_ that undercuts your negotiation leverage, it undercuts your
security,'' Ronald Lehman, head of the Arms Control and Disarmament
Agency, told reporters.
   Lehman said the key to U.S. elimination of its older chemical
weapons is to get other nations have to eliminate theirs, ``and
until they are committed to such a thing, we will have a stock,
albeit a very small stock.''
   ``So we will be continuing our production program. The president
has asked us to look at how we would structure the program, how we
would implement this in the context of the overall negotiations,''
Lehman said.
   ``You don't have to be born yesterday to understand ... we have
taken a big step here, but we're also looking after the national
security of the United States,'' Lehman said.
   Recent news reports, citing unnamed administration officials,
said President Bush has signed an order allowing the continued
production of a new generation of chemical weapons for an
unspecified period of time.
   Bush told the United Nations last month the United States and
the Soviet Union should cut their existing chemical weapons
stockpiles by 80 percent as an impetus to the negotiations in
Geneva on curbing chemical weapons.
   The president did not mention his decision on production in his
U.N. speech.
   In 1984, Bush _ as vice president _ carried a draft text to the
Geneva negotiations proposing that nations signing a chemical
weapons ban cease producing such arms right away and destroy their
stockpiles over a 10-year period. The international talks, in which
40 nations are taking part, resume next month.
   A draft of the international treaty calls for the immediate end
to the production of such weapons.
   Senate Democratic Leader George Mitchell of Maine on Monday
criticized Bush's stance on producing new chemical weapons, calling
it ``a major step backwards'' that threatens the international
negotiations.
   Lehman said the threat of chemical weapons ``needs to be
addressed and our policy has been to seek a total ban on the
production and storage and use of these weapons.''
   But he stressed the administration also has been ``quite clear''
and told Congress it intends ``to maintain our binary program.''
   Binary chemical weapons consist of two non-lethal chemicals that
become deadly when mixed.
   Lehman said the administration made progress on the issue during
the recent U.S.-Soviet talks in Wyoming and as a result of that
session the two superpowers will begin exchanging data on the
location and types of stocks and amounts that the two sides have
before the end of this year.
   But Soviets diplomats, speaking privately, have said the Kremlin
is concerned about Bush's decision to continue production of the
new generation of chemical weapons.
   Under Bush's U.N. proposal, the two superpowers would reduce
their stockpiles to a level equivalent to 20 percent of the current
U.S. level.
   Only the United States, the Soviet Union and Iraq acknowledge
having chemical weapons, but more than 20 nations are believed to
have them or have the capability to produce them.
</TEXT>
