<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Psychiatry     10-18 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Psychiatry,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Psychiatric Association Votes To Readmit Soviets Conditionally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLAIRE SPRINGETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Psychiatric Association today
conditionally readmitted the Soviet Union after a Soviet official
acknowledged that pyschiatry had been abused in his homeland for
political reasons.
   But the body said the official Soviet organization could be
ousted if an investigation finds that the Soviets still use
psychiatry as a political weapon against dissidents.
   Delegates at the eighth World Psychiatric Congress in Athens
voted 291-45 with 19 abstentions early today to conditionally
readmit the Soviet All-Union Society of Psychiatrists and
Narcologists.
   The psychiatric congress also admitted a second Soviet group,
the Independent Psychiatric Association, which was set up several
months ago by psychiatrists who wanted to distance themselves from
alleged abuses by the official All-Union Society.
   The independent association was admitted unanimously with no
conditions.
   No members of the independent group attended the congress
because they were unable to get visas in time, congress sources
said.
   The All-Union Society withdrew from the World Psychiatric
Congress in 1983 to avoid expulsion because of allegations
dissidents were being certified as insane.
   Wednesday's decision empowers a world congress delegation to
visit the Soviet Union within the next year to investigate whether
the political use of psychiatry has ended.
   If the delegation finds abuses, a special meeting of the
congress would be convened to consider suspending the All-Union
Society.
   ``I think ... the conditions will allow us to assess whether or
not there has been an amelioration in the political use of
psychiatry in the Soviet Union,'' said Dr. Melvin Sabshin, medical
director of the American Psychiatric Association.
   The move to admit the Soviet Union came after Peter Morozov, the
Soviet representative, acknowledged that psychiatry had been used
for political purposes.
   His group ``acknowledges that previous political conditions
created an environment in which psychiatric abuse occurred,
including political,'' Morozov told the congress before his
delegation left the hall for the vote.
   The Soviet Union publicly admitted the political abuse of
psychiatry had previously referred to breaches of professional
ethics and the law as ``non-medical use'' of psychiatry.
   Morozov told The Associated Press on Monday: ``It is clear we
regret our past, not only (political) abuses but the whole system.''
   There was heated debate over whether to readmit the Soviet group.
   The most strident opposition came from Dr. James Birley,
president of the British Royal College of Physicians, who said
``the Soviet group is run by the (Soviet) Foreign Office. ... I
have only been given contact with Foreign Office officials in my
attempts to have talks with Soviet psychiatrists.''
   A U.S. delegation of psychiatrists led by a State Department
official visited the Soviet Union in February to investigate Soviet
claims that psychiatry was no longer being abused.
   The group noted in a report that despite some progress, more
legal safeguards were needed to prevent the hospitalization of
dissidents.
   A Soviet official told a U.S. congressional panel earlier this
month that an eight-member commission had been set up to prevent
the use of psychiatry for ``non-medical reasons.''
   But on Monday a Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman told a news
conference in Athens that the authorities were ``still looking''
for professionals to become members of the commission, which he
said was not a part of any government department or organization.
   The Netherlands-based International Association on the Political
Use of Psychiatry, which campaigned against the Soviets'
readmission, claims to have evidence that 40 dissidents are still
being held in Soviet psychiatric institutions.
   And Amnesty International said in a report released today that
an Amnesty delegation that visited the Soviet Union in March found
100 cases in which people were in psychiatric institutions for
political reasons.
   It said more such cases had emerged since.
</TEXT>
