<HEAD>Physicians, Dentists Honored For AIDS Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Health and Human Services
today honored five dentists and six physicians, one posthumously,
as heroes in the fight against the AIDS epidemic.
   Dr. James Mason, assistant secretary for health at HHS, praised
the eleven for their ``selfless dedication, compassionate service
and outstanding leadership'' in caring for people infected with the
human immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, that causes AIDS.
   They were selected from more than 70 who were nominated to
receive the Assistant Secretary for Health awards.
   As part of HIV and AIDS Awareness Month, Mason also gave awards
to 10 nurses earlier this month.
   The physicians honored were: Elizabeth Harrison of Sacramento,
Calif.; Karen Hein of New York City; Richard Keeling of
Charlottesville, Va.; Neil Schram of San Francisco; Robert Yarchoan
of Bethesda, Md.; and, posthumously, Barry Gingell of New York City.
   The dentists honored were Mario Andriolo Jr. of New York City;
James A. Cottone of San Antonio; Deborah Greenspan of San
Francisco; Cynthia E. Hodge of Nashville, Tenn.; and Frank M.
Lucatorto of Los Angeles.
