<FIRST>r w PM-Budget 1stLd-Writethru a0488 10-18 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0488,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Government Starts Belt-Tightening Under Budget Cuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 7th graf to clarify money, not cuts would be restored to
budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Medicare patients and college students are
among those who will take a financial hit because the White House
and Congress don't agree on how to cut the federal budget deficit,
officials say.
   The automatic federal spending cuts _ which took effect Tuesday
in place of a budget agreement _ will have substantial effects
elsewhere in the government if the reductions stand. However, most
agencies report it would take a while for the cuts to trickle down
even if efforts to resolve the impasse fail.
   ``Other than general restraint on spending, nothing's on hold,''
a Commerce Department official said Tuesday, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   The Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law orders spending cuts
totaling $16.1 billion in the 1990 fiscal year that began on Oct. 1.
   ``We are waiting to see what Congress does,'' said spokesman
Pete Williams of the Defense Department, which was hit with half
the reductions.
   Labor Department spokesman Tracy Dennison said the department is
studying ways to trim $465 million ``but it will probably be
sometime down the road before we can say exactly what we'll be
doing.''
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater raised the
prospect that President Bush might not accept legislation restoring
the money to the budget.
   ``There is some feeling here that they are the way to go,'' he
told reporters. ``It will reduce spending in a very effective
fashion.''
   House and Senate leaders, meanwhile, looked for a way out of the
dilemma.
   The Senate has passed a deficit-reduction bill with almost
nothing else attached to it. But the House version includes a horde
of controversial provisions ranging from child care assistance to
the Fairness Doctrine in broadcasting.
   If Congress and Bush fail to agree soon, federal employees and
many taxpayers would feel the effects of the cuts.
   For example, the Labor Department would delay employee transfers
unless absolutely necessary and some new programs could be
postponed.
   The Internal Revenue Service, the FBI and other agencies with
personnel-oriented budgets would have to furlough workers because
the deficit-reduction law prohibits cutting employee salaries.
   ``As a practical matter ... we probably don't have to consider
that for 30 to 45 days,'' said Pentagon spokesman Williams.
   At the Department of Health and Human Services, Dennis Williams,
deputy assistant secretary for budget, said the most immediate
effect of the cuts will be on Medicare.
   ``For everybody else, it will be a cumulative impact over
time,'' Williams said.
   Doctors and hospitals that participate in the Medicare program
will see a reduction of 2.092 percent in their payments, he said.
In addition, some people who submit their bills directly to
Medicare will have to cover the 2.092 percent themselves.
   Medicare is taking a total $1.7 billion cut, while defense
spending accounted for a $8.1 billion reduction.
   Medicaid payments to states are exempt from the budget cuts, as
are Social Security, Supplemental Security Income and Aid to
Families with Dependent Children.
   Sally Christensen, director of Budget Service for the Education
Department, said the student loan program is the only education
program immediately affected by the budget cuts.
   The law raises the loan origination fee from 5 percent to 5.5
percent and cuts the special allowance payment to lending
institutions from 3.25 percent to 3 percent, Ms. Christensen said.
With these changes, banks will make less of a profit and students
will pay more for taking out a loan.
   Dennis Kaplan, chief of budget control and analysis for the
Agriculture Department, said it is widely believed there that
Congress will soon work out a budget agreement to replace the
automatic cuts.
   If not, he said, the Food Safety and Inspection Service ``will
probably furlough a lot of their employees, but that won't occur
until August or September'' of next year.
   The same would be true of the Forest Service and Farmers Home
Administration, he said.
   Much of the Agriculture Department's spending is exempt from the
cuts, including food stamps, school lunches and other child
nutrition programs.
   At the Federal Aviation Administration, which oversees 16,800
air traffic controllers, spokesman John Leyden said there would be
no immediate impact other than pulling back on hirings,
procurements and changes of status for personnel.
   The White House Office of Management and Budget said a prolonged
impasse might force the layoff of air traffic controllers for three
days a month and a reduction in military forces by 160,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
