<DOCNO> AP891018-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0418EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AIDSSpread     10-18 0784</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Spread,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Think Tank Says 14.5 Million US AIDS Cases Possible by 2002</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There may be 14.5 million Americans infected
with the AIDS virus by the year 2002 unless stronger measures are
taken to combat a growing epidemic, the Hudson Institute predicts
in what it calls ``a dark view of the future.''
   Hudson, a conservative think tank, released a report Tuesday
based on a 2{-year study of the progress of the nation's fight
against AIDS and warned ``a catastrophe is sweeping over America.''
   The study warns: ``If the nation shrinks from taking responsible
action now to contain the ... epidemic, it tacitly will be
accepting a disaster of immense proportions.
   ``Unchecked, AIDS will kill more Americans in the next decade
than have died in combat in all of the nation's wars since our
founding,'' the study said. ``Already AIDS has claimed the lives of
as many Americans as did the Vietnam War.''
   The Centers for Disease Control reports AIDS has been diagnosed
in more than 100,000 Americans and almost 60,000 have died. These
numbers do not include Americans who are only infected with the
AIDS virus and not experiencing symptoms that would classify the
case as AIDS. The Hudson study estimates are based on all people
who are infected with human immuniodeficiency virus, or HIV, which
causes AIDS.
   William B. Johnston, co-author of the study and vice president
of Hudson, said the report studied three possible scenarios and
drew up mathematical models to project possible consequences.
   In the worst case, the report said there would be some 1.4
million new HIV infections annually in the United States.
   This worst case, said Johnston, assumes no vaccine is developed
and there are no major changes in current social-sexual behavior.
   Even with the best case, which Johnston said would include a
vaccine by the middle of the 1990s and ``remarkable behavioral
changes throughout society,'' the report predicts there will be
30,000 new HIV infections annually by 2002. There would be about
1.6 million Americans with the disease that year under this
scenario, the report said.
   ``The middle case, which is the most reasonable,'' said
Johnston, ``gives us about 6 million'' cases of HIV infection.
   That case assumes some changes in social-sexual behavior with a
vaccine available by the year 2002.
   Johnston said widespread, voluntary, free HIV tests for all
people between the 15 and 65 would be the primary factor in
controlling the epidemic. This will help establish the ``HIV
status'' of all sexually active people, he said.
   ``By encouraging massive, routine, voluntary testing, we can
enable society voluntarily to segregate itself sexually into two
groups: those who carry the virus and those who do not,'' the
report said. ``No other means is likely to alter the course of the
HIV epidemic.''
   Because of the ``biological dynamics'' of HIV, the report said,
the disease can be controlled ``in a society that is not
universally monogamous'' only by limiting sexual contact between
the infected and the uninfected.
   ``The only safe sex is sex between uninfected partners,'' the
study said.
   The study said it is ``equally important,'' however, to protect
the rights and privacy of all people in society.
   In all three scenarios, the AIDS epidemic would be most
disastrous to black Americans, the study said.
   Under the worst case, the researchers forecast by the year 2002
almost 42 percent of the black population aged 15 to 50 would be
infected with HIV. Under the best case, infection among that same
group would be 1.5 percent, while the rate in the middle case would
be 15.5 percent.
   For Hispanics of the same age, the infection rate would be 9.2
percent for the worst case; 3.3 percent for the middle case, and 1
percent in the best case.
   The same numbers for the white population would be 2.9 percent,
worst case; 0.8 percent, middle case, and 0.1 percent, best case.
   Currently, the study estimated that there are 1.1 million
Americans infected with HIV. This is about 0.9 percent of the total
population.
   Comment on the report was requested from officials at the
National Institute of Allergies and Infectious Disease, the lead
agency in the National Institutes of Health in the battle against
AIDS, and from the National Cancer Institute, where the virus was
first isolated in this country. Officials, however, did not return
the calls.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is an incurable
contagious disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering
it incapable of resisting other diseases and infections. It is
spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes
shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from
infected pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0428EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-Illinois     10-18 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Illinois,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Opponents Set Back in Illinois</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DOWLING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A committee of the Illinois House
blocked a bill to restrict abortions in the state in a vote that
pro-choice legislators said would kill the issue for this year.
   Abortion opponents in the General Assembly, however, said they
would ask for a vote in the full House.
   In Pennsylvania, legislation to impose more restrictions on
abortions passed a committee Tuesday on a 16-7 vote, clearing the
way for full debate by that state's House.
   Tuesday's vote by the Illinois House's Rules Committee blocked a
bill similar to the Missouri legislature's restrictions on
abortion, which were upheld in July by the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Democratic Rep. Barbara Flynn Currie, a leading abortion-rights
lawmaker, predicted the panel's vote would hold.
   ``This looked to me like a pretty solid, pretty strong, pretty
clear signal that (the bill) will not be considered in the
Legislature during the fall veto session,'' Flynn said.
   But Republican Rep. Penny Pullen, a leader of anti-abortion
forces in the assembly, said it was ``wrong for a single committee
to hold (the bill) without having any opportunity for the members
of the House and Senate to express their opinions.''
   Nine of the 18 lawmakers on the rules committee voted to move
the abortion bill to the full House, but that was one vote short of
the required majority of 10. Eight lawmakers voted against further
action and one was absent.
   The panel's approval was required for further action on abortion
legislation in the fall session, which is limited to emergency
legislation and action on the governor's vetoes.
   A draft of the bill would require doctors to determine the
viability of a fetus believed to be 20 weeks old or older before
performing an abortion, and require that a second physician be
present for abortions of viable fetuses.
   It also would bar public employees and public facilities from
direct involvement in abortions, except when performed to save the
life of the mother.
   The bill required three-fifths majorities in both houses of the
assembly to reach the governor's desk.
   Before the committee vote Gov. James R. Thompson had warned
lawmakers against hasty action on the abortion legislation. He
declined to take a position on the measure.
   In the past, the Republican governor has vetoed most abortion
restrictions on constitutional grounds.
   The Pennsylvania bill would ban abortions after the 24th week of
pregnancy, except to save the life of the mother. It also would
prohibit abortions based on the sex of a fetus and require women in
most cases to notify their husbands if they plan to get an abortion.
   The bill, approved by the House Judiciary Committee, also calls
for a 24-hour waiting period for abortions.
   Democrat Robert O'Donnell, the majority leader, has said the
House will consider the measure Oct. 24.
</TEXT>
