<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Shelter     10-18 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Shelter,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Cross Shelter Draws Shocked, Weary Crowd</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A downtown emergency shelter drew a mixed
group of about 100 stranded tourists, conventioneers and residents
from nearby transient hotels who fled pitch dark streets looking
for a safe place to spend the night.
   No food or cots were available in the makeshift Red Cross
shelter late Tuesday in the ballroom of the Moscone Convention
Center, near the heart of the city's financial district and near
major rail and bus terminals.
   People ousted from their hotels or unable to reach them rested
their heads on tables set for conventioneers. Others stretched out
in corners trying to sleep.
   An emergency power supply provided dim lighting in the
underground convention center.
   The Red Cross had no food to offer, but volunteers were trying
to find some, combing nearby streets for any small market that
might be open despite the lack of electricity.
   ``Once you (provide) food, everything else becomes secondary,''
said shelter manager Theresa Hull, adding that she hoped those
foraging for food could at least buy some peanut butter and jelly
for sandwiches
   Radio notices informed those seeking safe haven about the
shelter, thought to be the city's only Red Cross outpost in the
first night following the devastating quake. Others said they were
directed there by police officers on the street.
   The mood in the dimly lighted ballroom was one of shock as
people recalled the wave of Earth movement.
   ``I thought it was a train going across the building,'' said
Phyllis Shook, a tourist from Des Moines, Iowa. ``It had a roar.''
   ``We heard an explosion and it turned out to be concrete from
the walls and windows blowing out,'' said Kim House, of San Jose,
who was walking in the San Francisco's Tenderloin district with her
fiancee when the quake hit.
   ``At first we thought it was a bomb and that's when all hell
broke loose. People were running out the buildings.''
   Douglas Schmillen, a transient staying at hotel where the city
refers the homeless, was lying on his bed when the tremor struck.
   ``The bed moved from one side (of the room) to the other,''
Schmillen said. ``I didn't know if the walls were going to come
down next.''
   Schmillen said he was evacuated from the hotel because of a gas
leak and the lack of electricity.
   Bob Witzgall, a conventioneer from Sacramento, said he was in
the shower of his Union Square hotel room when the earthquake hit.
   ``It was scary. I couldn't get out of there fast enough,''
Witzgall said. ``It started out as a little rumble, but it was
pretty violent where I was.''
   Lack of electricity and fears of being stranded on the street
all night sent Witzgall back to the shelter.
   ``I'm going to stay here until the power is back on and once
it's back on, I think I'll get in my car and leave,'' he said.
   Frank Odill, a Milwaukee visitor traveling with his wife, said
he was grateful they did not have to spend the night in total
darkness.
   ``At least here we've got power and light,'' he said, but his
wife, Betty, was less able to see a bright side.
   ``I can't wait to leave,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
