<FIRST>r a PM-Academy-Black     10-18 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Academy-Black,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>All-White Academy Plans on Playing Game Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An all-white high school academy has
agreed to play a football game against a school that has a black
player, reversing a decision that had prompted several team members
to quit.
   The headmaster of the all-white East Holmes Academy said he
decided not to cancel Friday's game against Columbus Heritage
Academy after the Mississippi Private School Association threatened
to expel the school.
   Headmaster Frank Drake continued to insist that the earlier
decision to cancel the game wasn't based on racism. However, he
wouldn't say what it was based on, and he refused to comment when
asked whether East Holmes discriminated on the basis of race.
   ``I'm not saying we violated a rule,'' Drake said Tuesday after
a meeting with a committee of the private school association. ``I'm
saying (the association) told us we violated a rule.''
   Coaches on both sides of the week-long controversy said they
hope all can be forgotten by game time.
   ``All we intend to do now is to get our football team ready to
play and to get on with the season with as few distractions as
possible,'' Heritage Academy headmaster and coach Ray Wooten said.
   Seven East Holmes players who had quit the team in protest of
the planned forfeiture of their game to Heritage have been
reinstated, school officials confirmed.
   ``The only thing I ever wanted to do was play the game,'' said
East Holmes coach Riley Myers. ``I just want my humans to block and
tackle their humans. Now that the game is back on, it's a huge
sense of relief. To me, it's the right thing to do.''
   Wooten had said earlier that East Holmes and other private
schools were considering forfeiting games against his school
because of Scott Fuller, a 15-year-old black student who
transferred to the school from West Point High School five weeks
ago.
   Sharkey-Issaquana Academy forfeited its game with Heritage last
Friday. At the time, headmaster Wayne Pinkerton said his team
wouldn't play because it was riddled with injuries and needed time
to mend.
</TEXT>
