<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0415EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Abortion     10-18 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Promises to Veto Medicaid Abortion Expansion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, setting the stage for a nasty
confrontation with Congress, is promising to veto legislation
allowing federally financed abortions for rape and incest victims.
   ``I think wisely, that taxpayer funds should be used only in the
most narrow of circumstances, where the life of the mother is
endangered,'' Bush said Tuesday in a letter that drew criticism
from Democratic leaders in Congress and abortion rights activists.
   ``Unfortunate and regrettable,'' House Speaker Thomas Foley said
after Bush issued his veto threat. He conceded the House might
sustain the veto, but said he would make an attempt to override it.
   Sen. Robert Packwood, R-Ore., a pro-choice lawmaker, said the
fallout from the battle could wind up harming GOP candidates.
   But Bush's decision was hailed by Rep. Chris Smith, R-N.J., a
leading abortion foe in the House. He said the president had taken
a ``very principled, albeit very difficult stand,'' and added,
``Doing right isn't always popular.''
   Bush issued his veto threat several days after saying publicly
he hoped there could be flexibility on the controversial issue, and
after quiet talks designed to draft a compromise that could satisfy
pro-life lawmakers who oppose any liberalization of the current
restrictions on Medicaid funding for abortion.
   ``No blame, it just didn't work out,'' White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater said.
   At issue is a provision attached to legislation funding programs
for the Department of Health and Human Services. It would permit
Medicaid funds to be used not only for abortions to save the life
of the mother, as is now the case, but also for cases of incest and
rape.
   The legislation has passed the House on a vote of 216-206, far
less than the two-thirds majority needed to override a veto. It is
still awaiting Senate action.
   Bush's decision was a bow to conservatives.
   ``That ... a child may have been conceived through an
unconscionable act of violence makes this question difficult and,
indeed, agonizing,'' Bush said. ``It does not, however, alter the
basic fact that federal funding is being sought that would compound
a violent act with the taking of a human life.''
   Bush wrote to Byrd because the West Virginia Democrat, as
chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee, will manage the
legislation on the Senate floor.
   In the past, administration officials had suggested a veto was a
strong likelihood. Fitzwater on Tuesday ended any doubts.
   ``In the end we couldn't find any flexibility,'' Fitzwater
contended.
   Fitzwater insisted that Bush last week never intended to signal
a liberalization in his position on the issue, and was only
speaking about ``flexibility in the process.''
   The abortion provision is part of a spending bill for the
departments of Labor and Health and Human Services that has already
been approved by a House-Senate conference committee and by the
full House. It awaits final Senate approval.
   Packwood, who favors the broadening provision, said Bush's
intention to veto the measure ``hurts the Republican party; it
hurts our candidates.''
   ``It is clear that the time and tides are on the side of us on
the pro-choice side,'' he said. He told reporters that when a
Republican president vetoes such legislation, ``that becomes the
Republican party position'' in voters' eyes.
   But Fitzwater denied that current election campaigns in Virginia
and New Jersey, where public opinion polls suggest Republicans
voicing strong anti-abortion views are trailing, had been a factor
in Bush's interest in finding a compromise.
   ``No, the president said early on, `You know my position. I
don't want to change it,''' Fitzwater asserted.
   While opposing use of federal funds for abortions in cases of
incest or rape, the president has a slightly less restrictive
position when it comes to abortions that are not paid for by the
public _ and he would not ban those privately financed abortions
for pregnancies from rape or incest.
</TEXT>
