<FIRST>r a PM-Brown-Attacks     10-18 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brown-Attacks,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brown President Considers Federal Help to Stem Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spate of racially charged attacks on
and near the Brown University campus has prompted the school's
president to consider asking for federal assistance to protect
students.
   In a letter to students released Tuesday, Vartan Gregorian said
racism apparently was the motivation for some of the attacks.
   ``The adminstration ... will join the local, state, and, if need
be, federal law enforcement agencies to prosecute the perpetrators
of such cowardly acts,'' Gregorian wrote.
   In a letter Monday to Providence Mayor Joseph R. Paolino Jr.,
Gregorian also said he might ask for unspecified federal assistance.
   ``I believe I have a moral and legal obligation to protect the
welfare of the Brown community and I am determined to take every
measure to do so,'' he said.
   Robert Reichley, vice president of university affairs, would not
say whether Gregorian was considering asking for help from the FBI,
the Justice Department's Civil Rights Division or another federal
agency, or when he might make the request.
   Sixteen attacks with racial overtones have occurred since
classes began in September, Reichley said. In most cases, black men
have jumped white male students, punching and beating them, and
sometimes drawing guns or other weapons, Reichley said. No one has
been seriously injured, he said.
   Reichley said it was almost certain the attackers were not
students.
   The campus newspaper also has reported that black and Asian
students have been taunted by whites on campus.
   ``We have anxious parents and a student body that is clearly on
edge,'' Reichley said. ``Anything could set it off ... a larger
internal action, vigilantism, what have you.''
   Gregorian asked students ``to use good judgment and caution.
This is not a time for the bravado of vigilantism.''
   Brown has been troubled by racial episodes since last spring,
when racist and anti-homosexual epithets were scrawled in some
parts of campus, including a dormitory.
   Gregorian warned students that the latest incidents were more
serious than the ones last May. He urged students to use campus
shuttle buses, lighted walks, emergency call boxes and student-run
escort services for safety.
</TEXT>
