<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0448EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WhaleAnniversary     10-18 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Whale Anniversary,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trapped Whales Unlikely This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARROW, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's not much chance of a sequel to
last year's big event in this northern Alaskan outpost: the rescue
of three whales trapped in an ice floe.
   Conditions are warmer this fall, leaving much less ice in the
lagoon where the whales were sealed, according to the biologist who
led the international rescue effort.
   ``The situation is just totally opposite this fall,'' Geoff
Carroll said this week. ``The pack ice is way, way offshore. There
is no chance of a pressure ridge forming.''
   Last year, the pack ice had formed a pressure ridge by early
October, sealing off a shallow lagoon northeast of Barrow.
   An Eskimo hunter scouting for bowhead whales was startled to
find three young California gray whales clustered around a small
breathing hole in the rapidly thickening ice in the lagoon.
   When word of the whales' plight went out, an international
clamor arose to rescue them. Even President Reagan got involved,
authorizing the use of military planes and personnel and
telephoning encouragement to rescue officials.
   While the government, the military and the oil industry monkeyed
with a series of expensive high-technology solutions, Carroll and
local whalers set to work with chainsaws.
   By cutting a path of new breathing holes toward the open water,
they lured the whales toward freedom. One of the whales disappeared
early in the effort, but the two others followed the path with
growing enthusiasm.
   Finally, two Soviet icebreakers battered through the
30-foot-tall ridge of ice, and the whales were on their own.
   Their fate remains unknown as government scientists chose not to
attach transmitters that would have kept track of the whales'
progress. Although free of the Barrow ice, the whales faced more
than 200 miles of heavy pack ice before open water in the Chukchi
Sea.
   Unlike last fall, when Barrow was a nightly fixture on
television newscasts around the world, this autumn has slipped into
the quiet rhythm of the arctic as winter approaches.
   There is no ice on Elson Lagoon. Whalers are ranging out in
search of their favorite target, the bowhead. A 39-footer was taken
Tuesday, the sixth of the fall season.
   Although there is no horde of reporters and photographers
clamoring about town, no fleet of helicopters clattering overhead,
the whale rescue isn't forgotten.
   A small ceremony and dance were held Thursday to commemorate the
long hours of hard work by people in a community hard-pressed to
cope with the onslaught of media attention.
   Carroll, who worked as a biologist for the North Slope Borough
last year and went to work for the state last week, said there were
discussions during the winter about what to do if the trapped-whale
dilemma ever arises again.
   Carroll said no consensus was reached, but many whalers he knows
say privately they would harvest any whales trapped in the future.
Others would ignore trapped whales, leaving them on their own to
find a way out.
   ``A lot of people had a pretty good time with it last year,
although nobody wants to go through another full-scale effort that
was so expensive,'' Carroll said.
   The borough estimated it spent about $750,000 on the rescue.
Government, military and oil industry officials involved in the
operation steadfastly refused to give estimates of their expenses.
   Interest in the fate of the two freed whales remained high
during the summer as an unusually large number of gray whales
turned up dead, Carroll said. On one 40-mile stretch of beach
southwest of Barrow, nine grays washed ashore.
   One was about the size as the surviving whales and had numerous
wounds on its snout similar to those the trapped whales suffered as
they nosed up through their ice-clogged breathing holes.
   ``He was kind of cut up, but we came to the conclusion it wasn't
as bad as they (the survivors) were,'' Carroll said. ``I'm pretty
confident it wasn't the same whale.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
