<FIRST>r a PM-TapesConfiscated     10-18 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tapes Confiscated,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Music Store Owner To Appeal Obscenity Conviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDER CITY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A music store owner fined $500 for
selling a rap recording that police found sexually offensive has
accused the city of selectively enforcing its obscenity statute.
   Tommy Hammond, owner of the Taking Home the Hits music store in
this city of 14,000, said his attorney will ask a Tallapoosa County
circuit judge at a Nov. 9 hearing to throw out the conviction.
   Hammond was convicted and fined in August 1988 for selling a
cassette, 2 Live Crew's ``Move Somethin'.''
   Hammond said other stores in Alexander City are carrying the
same cassette and he believes he was singled out for what he
considers wrongful prosecution.
   ``I stepped on some toes,'' he said.
   John Dillon, an attorney who works as a prosecutor for the city,
said he was certain police would charge other store owners if the
cassette was found in their shops.
   But Hammond said his attorney had someone purchase the recording
at another store and present it to police, who took no action
against that store's owner.
   Hammond said police told him a parent complained about the sale
of the cassette, but Hammond said he was careful not to sell ``Move
Somethin''' to minors.
   Daniel Brown, another attorney for the city, said 2 Live Crew
violates the city's obscenity laws because its lyrics provide
detailed descriptions of perverse sexual acts and sadomasochism.
   Hammond's lawyer, Elizabeth Johnson of Montgomery, disagreed.
   ``Profanity and offensive music are not what obscenity is all
about,'' Ms. Johnson said. ``You may be offended by it, but that
doesn't make it obscene.''
   The group in question, 2 Live Crew, records on the Miami-based
Luke Skywalker label, which is paying half of Hammond's legal fees.
   Debbie Bennett, a publicist for the recording company, said 2
Live Crew can be raunchy, but is not obscene.
   ``It's very restricting to consider it pornography,'' she said.
``It's far, far from being that. It's humorous rap. The group
considers themselves the founders of comedic rap.''
</TEXT>
