<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-USQuake 1stLd-Writethru a0448 10-18 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-US Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0448,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Japanese Saw U.S. Quake Live on TV</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with kaifu offer help in rescue
and rebuilding. Picks up 3rd pvs, ```Earthquake. Oh ...' SUBS last 3 grafs
to ADD comment from Philippines president. ^By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opean apart but linked by deep sensitivity to
earthquakes, Japanese watched with sympathy as a major temblor hit
the San Francisco area. Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu offered today
to help in rescue and rebuilding efforts.
   Kaifu said he was ``deeply saddened'' by Tuesday's disaster.
   ``As we ourselves are so vulnerable to this natural disaster
that we view the fate of its victims much as that of our own ... we
are following the news from San Francisco with intense care,'' he
said in a message to President Bush.
   ``We are prepared to contribute to your efforts of emergency
rescue and reconstruction as much as we can.''
   Some Japanese, watching a live telecast of the prelude to the
World Series baseball game in Candlestick Park, saw the quake
wobble a TV camera that was showing Americans riding an escalator
into the stadium.
   ``Earthquake. Oh, oh,'' correspondent Naoki Morinaka said into
the microphone from the Candlestick Park press box. ``It's shaking
quite a lot ... almost all the lights are out ...''
   Green bars and static flashed on TV screens, showing partial
disruption of the broadcast.
   The transmission on the Japan Broadcasting Corp. (NHK) satellite
service had started at 9 a.m. Japan time, four minutes before the
quake struck.
   NHK quickly shifted the signal to its regular nationwide
network, and Japanese crowded around TV sets to see repeated scenes
from the disaster.
   Helicopter shots showed a break on the Bay Bridge, crumpled
sections of an elevated freeway, flames from a major fire in San
Francisco and baseball stars comforting their wives at the
postponed World Series game.
   Japan's volcanic islands are as seismically active as the San
Andreas Fault, and the 122 million Japanese have known repeated
disasters. The biggest this century was a Sept. 1, 1923, quake that
killed 140,000 people in Tokyo and Yokohama.
   On Saturday, a moderate quake of 5.9 on the Richter scale hit
deep under the Pacific Ocean near the coast, swaying buildings in
Tokyo and reminding the Japanese of the disaster they surely face _
big quakes are said to occur in 70-year cycles _ and for which
civil authorities are refining emergency plans.
   Foreign Minister Taro Nakayama reported first details of the San
Francisco quake to Parliament today, and Chief Cabinet Secretary
Mayumi Moriyama told reporters the government would consider
offering emergency help if needed.
   Concern in Japan, Hong Kong and the Philippines was heightened
because of the large numbers of their people living in California.
   More than 9,300 Japanese live in the San Francisco Bay area,
Mrs. Moriyama said. The Philippine Department of Foreign Affairs
said at least 500,000 Filipinos live in the area, one of the
largest concentrations of Filipinos in the United States.
   Hong Kong has strong links to the San Francisco area, which has
an estimated 200,000 ethnic Chinese.
   Radio stations in the Philippines interrupted regular
programming for frequent and extensive reports on the earthquake
and news organizations were flooded with calls from anxious
Filipinos with relatives in the Bay Area.
   President Corazon Aquino expressed sympathy to quake victims and
said she was directing her country's consulate in San Francisco to
``extend whatever help they can'' to Filipinos in the area.
   In Hong Kong and the Philippines, long-distance lines were
jammed by concerned people trying to call San Francisco for
information on relatives and friends.
</TEXT>
