<HEAD>Former Head of HUD Regional Office to Retain Full Benefits in Retirement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former head of the embattled Washington
field office of the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development will retire with full benefits next month despite
allegations of mismanagement of the office, an agency spokeswoman
said.
   Under a settlement reached Monday, I. Margaret White, who had
been fighting to keep her job, will retire Nov. 3 and HUD will drop
its three-month pursuit of her termination, the spokeswoman told
The Washington Post.
   White, a 28-year employee of the agency, had faced firing for
her role in alleged improprieties in the Washington office.
   In today's editions, the newspaper quotes White as saying she
was ``ecstatic'' about the news.
   White earns $74,303 annually and her retirement benefits will be
based on that pay.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Danforth Introduces Living Will Legislation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John Danforth, an Episcopal priest before
entering politics, has introduced legislation he says is aimed at
letting people know ``it's OK'' to plan for death just as they
think about life.
   ``We are walking along, living our lives and thinking everything
is fine,'' the Missouri Republican said at a news conference
Tuesday. ``Then suddenly, somebody you've never met before has you
hooked up to a machine you've never heard of before in an
institution you've never seen before.''
   Far better, says Danforth, is for each individual to plan for
the possibility and decide in advance whether they want to be
allowed to die with dignity when all hope of recovery is gone or be
maintained in a vegetative state by machines for weeks or months or
even years.
   The legislation he introduced Tuesday along with Sen. Daniel P.
Moynihan, D-N.Y., would require the 10 states that do not already
have so-called ``living will'' laws to adopt one, although the
details would be left to the states.
   It also would require U.S. hospitals and nursing homes which
accept federal health dollars to advise their patients upon
admission of their right to executive a living will.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Study Says Low Wages Affect Child Care Quality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national study says low teacher pay is
threatening quality at most child care centers by driving trained
instructors away in droves.
   The study, released Tuesday, found child care teachers earn less
annually than the 1988 national poverty level for a family of
three, $9,431.
   ``Nearly half of all child care teachers leave their jobs each
year, many to seek better-paying jobs,'' according to the National
Child Care Staffing Study, titled ``Who Cares?''
   ``As the nation deliberates on what is best for its children,
the question of who will care for them grows increasingly
critical,'' said the study, which was funded by $500,000 from a
consortium of foundations, including the Ford Foundation and the
Foundation for Child Development.
   Congress is trying to work out differences in child care
legislation that has passed in the House and Senate.
</TEXT>
