<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     10-18 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Peace Negotiations Go Into Overtime With Agreement In
Sight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Wirter</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist Salvadoran rebels and
government negotiators broke a deadlock over truce conditions and
agreed to meet again today for peace talks aimed at ending their
country's decade-old civil war.
   The talks nearly broke off after men firing automatic weapons
killed the daughter of an army colonel in San Salvador on Tuesday.
   The Salvadoran government accused the rebels of the killing, but
guerrilla leaders emphatically denied the charge.
   Both sides later agreed to extend the two-day session another
day in response to an appeal by President Oscar Arias of Costa
Rica, who won the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for his plan to bring
peace to Central America.
   ``There are agreements. The meeting has been saved. It was
already known that this would be a critical meeting,'' said Bishop
Gregorio Rosa Chavez of El Salvador, who has been monitoring the
talks.
   ``We know the process will continue and there is more than a
mere agreement to continue meeting,'' he said, adding that both
sides pledged not to comment further until today's session ends.
   Rosa Chavez, one of several Roman Catholic leaders and
international observers monitoring the talks, spoke to reporters
during a dinner break late Tuesday.
   Both sides had appeared eager to call a cease-fire in the civil
war that has killed more than 70,000 people, but differed sharply
on the terms.
   The rebel Farabundo Marti Liberation Front called for a
temporary truce beginning Nov. 15 and for broad political and
social reforms. President Alfredo Cristiani's rightist government
demanded an immediate cease-fire with virtually no preconditions.
   Arias intervened Tuesday night when it appeared the talks were
seriously threatened by the deadlock and the slaying Ana Isabel
Casanova. She was shot to death in her car a block from her home as
she celebrated her 23rd birthday.
   Arias rushed to the parish house in the little town of Moravia
just north of the capital, where the talks are being held.
   ``I came to encourage both sides to continue,'' he told
reporters. ``I know that after 10 years of war, it is difficult to
attain peace, which is a slow and complicated process.''
   Arias invited the two delegations to dinner after they promised
to continue talking today.
   The talks are the second meeting between the rebels and the
Cristiani government, which took office in June. An opening session
was held in Mexico City in September.
   A previous round of negotiations between the government and
rebels, in October 1987, broke off because of the assassination of
Herbert Anaya, the leader of a leftist human rights group.
</TEXT>
