<FIRST>r a PM-People-Kidder-Teachers     10-18 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Kidder-Teachers,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers Identify With Author Tracy Kidder's Classroom Chronicle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Educators and their supporters at the Statehouse
turned out to honor Pulitzer Prize-winning author Tracy Kidder, who
chronicled a year in the life of a Massachusetts teacher in his
latest, highly acclaimed book.
   ``Among Schoolchildren,'' the chronicle of Kidder's year with
Holyoke schoolteacher Chris Zajac's fifth-grade class, has left a
lot of people nodding in reluctant recognition.
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis says it's among the best four or five
books he's ever read and public schoolteachers are using it as a
rallying cry.
   About 200 education activists showed up at a Statehouse
reception Tuesday for Kidder, the author of ``The Soul of a New
Machine'' and ``House,'' and hear him read excerpts from his latest
effort.
   ``Everyone who has read (the book) agrees: It tells it like it
is,'' said Phyllis Smith, a former teacher and now an administrator
at Marblehead's public schools. ``No honey-faced lies and a lot you
can identify with.''
   In the book, Kidder doesn't gloss over low pay, lack of respect
and poor working conditions teachers face. He demonstrates little
patience with high-minded reform efforts that he says ``seem to
leave teachers right out of the equation.''
   The story has had particular resonance in Massachusetts this
fall because of the state's fiscal crisis and the resulting
financial problems of many public schools.
   In Holyoke, for instance, students don't have physical
education, art or music courses this year because the funds aren't
available and residents aren't willing to approve a tax increase,
Kidder said.
   ``I constantly am questioning why I'm doing something and
reflecting on my weaknesses,'' said Zajac, who was 34 years old
when Kidder persuaded her to let him join her class three years ago.
   ``I am not a saint or a miracle worker or even a witch doctor,''
she told her colleagues Tuesday afternoon. ``I'm a public school
teacher from Holyoke, just one of millions.''
   ``It's important for us to be as concerned with what something
is worth as with what it costs,'' said Rep. Nicholas A. Paleologos,
chairman of the House Committee on Education, Arts and Humanities
and sponsor of a petition introduced Tuesday to add a penny for
education to the 5 percent sales tax.
</TEXT>
