<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionNotification     10-18 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Notification,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Asked to Clear Way for State to Implement Notification Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia officials have asked a federal appeals
court to let them enforce a law requiring young women to inform
their parents before having an abortion.
   But a lawyer representing Planned Parenthood urged the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals on Tuesday to uphold lower court decisions
that for two years have blocked enforcement of the law.
   The law would require young women under age 18 to bring a note
from a parent before having an abortion or otherwise show the
parents had been notified. It includes a provision under which a
minor could secure the permission of a juvenile court judge to
undergo an abortion without parental knowledge.
   The law mandates a 24-hour wait between parental notification
and an abortion.
   The statute was passed in 1987, but a challenge by Planned
Parenthood resulted in key portions being ruled unconstitutional
before it took effect.
   The Legislature revised the statute in 1988 with the same result.
   Among other things, U.S. District Judge Robert Hall cited the
statute's failure to provide for swifter forms of written notice
and held that it improperly allowed a juvenile court ``intake
officer'' to screen and possibly dismiss a young woman's request
for a waiver.
   Kathryn Allen, a senior assistant state attorney general,
complained to the three appeals court judges that Hall applied too
strict a standard.
   She argued that the state ``is not required to meet every
contingency as long as the statute is narrowly drawn.''
   If anything can be learned from the U.S. Supreme Court's
abortion decision last summer, Ms. Allen added, ``it is that state
statutes will be given the benefit of the doubt and the court will
attempt to read it in a manner that will make it constitutional.''
   But Dara Klassel, an attorney representing Planned Parenthood
chapters in Atlanta and Augusta, argued that the Supreme Court
decision did nothing to change the standard of review.
   Laws affecting ``a fundamental constitutional right have to be
subjected to strict scrutiny,'' she said.
   The court took the appeal under consideration without indicating
when it would rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
