<FIRST>r a PM-RecruitSuicide     10-18 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Recruit Suicide,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Trainee's Death Mourned as Part of Violence Affecting Society</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM LAVELETTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rows of police officers flanked a coffin draped
in white to mourn a young recruit who shot himself to death after
he fell short of his lifelong goal of becoming a policeman.
   Danny Morales was not depressed and was not the type to plan his
death, the Rev. Robert Stiefvater told about 250 mourners who
packed a Roman Catholic church Tuesday.
   When his dream of becoming a police officer began slipping, the
21-year-old Morales took his revolver and shot himself in the head
Friday in front of his instructor at the Police Training Academy
shooting range.
   ``We cannot condone what he did,'' Stiefvater said. ``We cannot
condemn him for what he did. What he did is a part of us.''
   Stiefvater said all of Milwaukee, where homicides and
drug-related crimes have risen to record levels this year, is
hurting ``in this autumn of a hundred violent deaths.''
   ``There is something missing in the way we support each other
that allows these things to happen,'' he said. ``But we can turn
things around and we can start right now.''
   Turning to Morales' uniformed academy classmates who were seated
in pews at the side of the altar, Stiefvater said, ``The Lord tells
us to live our values the way you wear that patch ... so that all
can see it.''
   Stiefvater's church is across the street from Milwaukee
Technical High School, where Morales launched the second generation
of his family's tradition of winning high school wrestling
championships. Morales helped coach sports teams at the parish.
   He was remembered as a promising young man whose suicide stunned
family and friends.
   Inspector Joseph Kalivoda, commander of the Police Department's
training bureau, recalled Morales' role within the current training
class and how he would be remembered.
   ``Every recruit class has a different personality. A few days
after they started, an instructor noted this class was very
team-oriented,'' Kalivoda said.
   ``Danny was taken from us because of the will of the Lord. Some
day we will understand why. When his class graduates January fifth,
I believe his spirit will be with them.''
   Morales was accepted to the recruit class that started training
Aug. 20. A month later, he failed a firing range test and then
failed the retest and resigned from the academy Sept. 29.
   After finding out he was nearsighted, Morales got glasses and
appealed his resignation. He was allowed another chance to take the
shooting test.
   On Friday, after a week of remedial training and full of renewed
hope, he returned to the range to retake the test. But it quickly
became clear the glasses weren't the only problem with his
marksmanship.
   Morales needed a score of 210 of 300 in three rounds of shooting.
   He scored a poor 62 in the first round, and 66 in the second. He
needed an 82 in the third round, and it was clear he couldn't get
it. He used the remaining shot to kill himself.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
