<DOCNO> AP891018-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0530EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Turkey-Politics     10-18 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turkey-Politics,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ozal Seeks Job That Will Move Him Out of Active Politics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Turgut Ozal has announced he will
run for president, a post that would remove him from day-to-day
politics and could lead to a fight for leadership of his governing
Motherland Party.
   The presidency is a prestigious post but is mainly ceremonial
with few executive powers. Also, the president cannot belong to a
political party.
   Ozal announced his intentions Tuesday to the parlimentary
deputies of his party, whose members include Moslem fundamentalists
and pro-Western moderates pushing for Turkey's membership in the
European Economic Community.
   ``Time will come when we will have to part, if for no other
reason then when Allah calls us to his bosom,'' Ozal said to the
deputies, who gave him a standing ovation. ``This way it will be
easier. There will be change.''
   Analysts say Ozal, 62, who had a triple heart bypass operation
three years ago, wants the less strenous job of president for
health and political reasons.
   Parliament will begin voting Friday to elect a successor to
President Kenan Evren, whose seven-year term expires Nov. 9.
   The Motherland Party has a 289-seat majority in the 450-member
legislature.
   The opposition parties came out strongly against Ozal's
candidacy but so far they have not offered a candidate of their
own. Erdal Inonu, leader of the chief opposition Social Democrat
Populist Party, said Tuesday that party members would boycott
Parliament sessions during presidential balloting.
   The opposition says an Ozal presidency would be against the
spirit of the constitution because he lacks sufficient public
support and could never be the non-partisan president required by
the constitution.
   Under Turkey's constitution, general elections must be held if
Parliament fails to elect a president by the fourth and final
ballot, which is scheduled for Nov. 4.
   A two-thirds majority is necessary on the first two ballots and
political analysts say Ozal is likely to be elected Oct. 31 on a
third ballot, when a simple majority is sufficient.
   Ozal said party members have indicated they will allow him to
designate his successor as party leader and premier. But some
analysts say the party could be divided over the choice and that a
government crisis could follow.
   Some names mentioned as possible candidates for premier are
Foreign Minister Mesut Yilmaz, Finance Minister Ekrem Pakdemirli
and former Education Minister Hasan Celal Guzel.
   Ozal became premier six years ago when the newly formed
Motherland Party won elections that restored civilian rule. A
military junta had taken over in 1980 at a time of widespread
political terrorism and an economic crisis.
   During military rule, Ozal served as deputy premier in charge of
the economy and implemented economic liberalization measures that
since have quadrupled Turkey's exports.
   There also has been a massive investment in roads, power plants
and telecommunications during Ozal's leadership.
   But the price has been high inflation, which has run at 75
percent for the past two years.
   Public support for Ozal and his party has been sliding. In
recent polls published by Turkish papers, at least 60 percent of
the respondents opposed an Ozal presidency. In local elections in
March, the Motherland Party won only 21.75 percent of the vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0538EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Quake-Candlestick     10-18 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Candlestick,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Puts World Series in Perspective for Ballplayers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD BLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The earth shook for 20 seconds, and when it
stopped the big-league ballplayers weren't talking about their
championship anymore.
   Frightened Giants and Athletics dashed out of their dugouts,
while in the stands their stunned fans watched the concrete
overhang ripple ominously as Tuesday's earthquake struck and forced
cancellation of the third game of the World Series at Candlestick
Park.
   ``It makes you realize just what place baseball should have in
your life,'' said San Francisco Giants catcher Terry Kennedy. ``I
found that out tonight.''
   ``You can't stop concrete,'' Oakland outfielder Dave Henderson
said. ``Forget the World Series.''
   Fans in the sellout crowd of about 60,000 remained calm when the
tremors struck. Several people were hit by small chunks of metal
and concrete before Candlestick was calmly evacuated. No serious
injuries were reported at the stadium.
   As of early today there was no word on when the series might
resume.
   ``We needed to get everybody out of here before it gets dark,''
baseball commissioner Fay Vincent said. ``That was the governing
issue in the decision to postpone the game.''
   Game No. 3 of the championship series between the San Francisco
Bay area teams had been scheduled to start at 5:30 p.m. The quake
struck at 5:04 p.m.
   Viewers of ABC's World Series pregame show saw the picture turn
to static and heard an unidentified voice yell, ``We're having an
earth...'' before the transmission was lost.
   The picture then disappeared and the network put up a still
slide for the World Series, before switching to the program
``Roseanne.''
   ``It could have been a catastrophe,'' said Will Clark, the San
Francisco Giants star first baseman. ``We had one in L.A. last
year, but this was more scary because we have a packed house here.''
   Security guard Mark Dandridge, 26, said he saw a stadium light
tower sway, ``and then I looked down to the luxury boxes and I saw
all that starting to shake, and I said `Oh, God help us!' ''
   Said Oakland slugger Jose Canseco, ``I didn't know where I was
for five seconds.''
   ``It was a steady sort of shake and roll and it was an extremely
uneasy moment,'' said Al Michaels, ABC-TV's announcer, who was in
the Candlestick press box when the quake hit. ``The sense I got for
a split second was we were going backward.''
   Umpire Al Clark was still in the dressing room.
   ``It was one of the scariest situations I've ever been in. As
soon as it started, my legs went numb,'' he said. ``I looked up,
and the walls were waving. I became frightened, and I realized it
was an earthquake.''
   ``I knew something was wrong when I saw the first base dugout
moving,'' said Kennedy. ``My first thought was to look for my wife
in the stands. I spotted her and rushed over.''
   Carl Epolite of San Jose decided to leave as soon as he felt the
first aftershock, about 35 minutes after the quake. He was sitting
in the upper deck under a concrete overhang.
   ``We saw the overhang starting to ripple,'' Carl said. ``It
rippled all around the stadium, but we kind of took it in stride,
and people started cheering. Some people took it as a good sign for
the Giants, that it was a sign from God that the Giants would start
winning.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
