<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead of first item.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMARILLO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Cosby told an audience of children
how they could return the favor of his showing up at their school:
``Study and become somebody.''
   ``Remember what I did tonight for you,'' Cosby told about 50
Carver Elementary Academy second-graders Monday. ``You're looking
at a grown-up who could be home with his wife, sitting there
watching `Monday Night Football.'''
   Cosby performed in a benefit show that brought in $175,000 for
the school, which opened this fall in an predominantly minority
neighborhood and stresses the use of computers to help youngsters
learn.
   Cosby had been enlisted to help by oilman T. Boone Pickens,
whose company Mesa Limited Partnership last March contributed more
than $400,000 to the school district and agreed to seek other
donors. The district, struggling with a $7.3 million budget
shortfall, had considered postponing the school's opening.
   Cosby said he believes private financing of public education
will become more common.
   ``I gave this up to come here and save your school,'' Cosby told
the pupils in mock seriousness. ``At least you could study and
become something. I didn't come out here so that you guys could
become nothing.''
</TEXT>
