<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Bombing 1stLd-Writethru   10-18 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Bombing, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0491,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Expected To All Three Convicted of Bombings To Be Freed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with comment from Amnesty International, INSERT 2
grafs after 15th graf pvs, `In ordering...' Pickup 16th graf pvs, `All
four...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government appeared ready today to allow the
release of at least three people convicted of 1974 Irish terrorist
bombings and news reports said police investigators involved in the
cases would be prosecuted.
   The Home Office, responsible for law enforcement, announced
Tuesday that it would not oppose an appeal by the so-called
Guildford Four, who were imprisoned 14 years ago for the two fatal
IRA bombings that targeted British soldiers.
   The three man and a woman have maintained their innocence since
being convicted of murder and sentenced to life in prison. News
reports said at least three probably would be released soon after a
Court of Appeal hearing Thursday.
   The government refused to comment on reports that police
involved in the investigation of the case would face prosecution.
   The Times of London reported today without attribution: ``A
handful of officers, who were then of relatively junior rank, will
face charges after an investigation by ... police into a number of
aspects of the original inquiry.''
   The Independent quoted unidentified parliamentary sources as
saying two or three police officers were expected to face criminal
proceedings for alleged corruption.
   A third newspaper, The Guardian, said the government's former
director of public prosecutions, Sir Norman Skelhorn, withheld
crucial alibi evidence from defense lawyers at the 1975 trial.
   In January, Home Secretary Douglas Hurd agreed to a review by an
appeals court following mounting pressure from the Irish
government, church leaders, former Cabinet ministers and senior
judges.
   ``Circumstances have recently come to the notice of the Director
of Public Prosecutions (Allan Green) which have caused him to
conclude that it would be wrong for the Crown to seek to sustain
the convictions,'' said a statement issued by Green's office on
Tuesday.
   Paul Hill, Gerard Conlon and Patrick Armstrong, all of Belfast,
and Armstrong's English girlfriend, Carole Richardson, were
convicted of bombing two pubs in Guildford, southwest of London, in
Oct. 5, 1974. Five people, including two soldiers, were killed and
65 injured.
   Armstrong and Hill also were convicted of a pub bombing in the
London suburb of Woolwich on Nov. 6, 1974, in which two people died
and 26 were injured.
   Hill is serving a concurrent sentence for the murder of a former
British soldier in Belfast. That conviction, also in 1975, was
based on statements obtained by Belfast police while he was in
prison in Guildford.
   His lawyer, Michael Fisher, said he hoped the Home Office ``will
have the decency to release him from the Belfast conviction.''
   The Guardian, quoting unidentified Home Office sources,
reported: ``There is written evidence that a conscious decision was
taken ... to withhold alibi witness statements'' from Conlon's
lawyers.
   In ordering the case reviewed, Hurd had cited possible alibi
witnesses for two of the convicts, and evidence that Ms. Richardson
had been injected with drugs during interrogation because she was
suffering from withdrawal from barbiturates.
   Amnesty International, the London-based human rights group,
issued a statement today welcoming the government's announcement.
   ``Amnesty International said it had for years been concerned
about the ... Guildford convictions, which were based solely on
confessions allegedly obtained through coercion and had repeatedly
called on the government to review the case,'' the statement said.
   All four were convicted on the basis of incriminating statements
they repudiated at trial.
   Four members of an Irish Republican Army unit confessed to the
Guildford pub bombings after their arrest in December 1975, but
they were never charged. In Dublin, the Irish government welcomed
the decision ``in the most positive terms.'' Cardinal Basil Hume,
head of the Roman Catholic Church in England and Wales, told
British Broadcasting Corp. television he was ``immensely grateful''
for the decision.
   But Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, the outlawed IRA's
legal political wing, told 500 supporters at Hackney in east London
Tuesday night: ``We don't thank the British government. They've
only done what they should have done 14 years ago.''
   The almost exclusively Catholic IRA is fighting to push the
British out of Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland and join it
with the Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
