<FIRST>r a PM-Quake-PlanesDiverted     10-18 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Planes Diverted,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flights Bound For San Francisco Diverted, Others Halted</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of airline passengers were stranded today after flights
to the San Francisco area were diverted or canceled because of the
earthquake.
   The delays and cancellations affected travelers as far away as
Japan, which has direct air service to San Francisco, and some
passengers landed far from their destinations.
   The quake stranded more than 800 travelers at O'Hare
International Airport in Chicago, where crowds huddled around TV
sets Tuesday night watching news reports about the quake.
   ``Most of the ones who were trying to get back to their families
were pretty distressed,'' said Racquel O'Bryant, spokeswoman at the
Holiday Inn O'Hare, where more than 100 stranded travelers stayed.
``A lot of people were calling for their families, but there was
just no way to get through. The phone lines were open only for
emergencies.''
   San Francisco International Airport and Oakland Airport remained
closed early today. San Jose International Airport was open with
only minor damage, officials said.
   United Airlines had at least 30 flights canceled or diverted
because of the earthquake as of Tuesday night, said spokesman Joe
Hopkins in Chicago. He said San Francisco is a major hub for
United, with about 140 arrivals and 140 departures every day.
   Al Becker, a Chicago-based spokesman for American Airlines, said
several hundred of the airline's flights had been affected by the
disaster.
   Five United and American flights bound for the San Francisco
area were diverted to Salt Lake City, said Tom Hill, airport
authority supervisor in Salt Lake.
   Five Delta Air Lines flights were ended prematurely in Salt Lake
City, and one was canceled, said Fred Rollins, Delta district
marketing director.
</TEXT>
