<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0846EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-USGS-Quake 1stLd-Writethru a0551 10-18 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USGS-Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0551,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aftershocks A Danger in Quake</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with updated information on aftershocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RESTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of small earthquake aftershocks were
continuing along the San Andreas fault where Tuesday's tremor
struck Northern California, government scientists said today.
   ``We are looking for any unusual characteristics and will be
putting out more portable instruments to measure the aftershocks,''
said Dave Russ, assistant chief geologist for the U.S. Geological
Survey.
   ``An earthquake of this size will typically by followed by many
thousands of aftershocks in the weeks to come,'' a USGS statement
said. California still faces the danger of large tremors as well,
said Russ.
   ``This certainly was not the `Big One,''' he said, referring to
a major quake that has long been feared for California. The
anticipated big quake would be expected to read at 8.0 or more on
the Richter scale, while Tuesday's quake is being estimated at 6.9.
   The temblor was centered between Los Gatos and San Juan
Bautista, an area south of San Francisco where scientists said in a
report last year was among three regions where dangerous tremors
were likely.
   A serious shock of magnitude 7.0 or more is still a possibility
along the nearby Hayward Fault, Russ said. And, he said, the
continuing chance of a quake of magnitude 8.0 or more in Southern
California ``has us very worried.''
   Russ explained that when an earthquake occurs, it releases
stress in the ground. That action, however, can increase the stress
in nearby areas, resulting in many aftershocks that follow major
earthquakes.
   Earthquakes result from the movements of plates deep within the
earth, Russ said. These plates can move fairly easily at depths of
six miles or more because the heat and pressure cause the rocks to
become like plastic so they can slip past one another.
   Closer to the earth's surface, however, the rocks are more rigid
and stick together, causing strain to build up until it is released
in an earthquake.
   In California, the boundary between the Pacific plate that
underlies that ocean and the North American plate forms a series of
faults running north and south through the state. these plates move
in different directions at a rate of about two centimeters, which
is nearly an inch a year.
   The major and best known fault is the San Andreas, which
consists of a series of segments that Russ said do not all move
together. Thus, there can be an earthquake in one area without
necessarily causing a tremor in another part of the fault.
   The region where Tuesday's quake was centered had been
relatively quiet in recent years until 1988. A strong quake, rated
at 5.1 on the Richter scale, occurred in June 1988 and a second
rated 5.2 occurred in August of this year.
   Such quakes can indicate that a larger one will follow, Russ
said.
   Scientists had rated the probability of a severe quake in this
region at about 30 percent, he said.
   By comparison, the geologist said, some studies have indicated a
60 percent chance of a severe quake in the Los Angeles region some
time in the next 30 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
