<FIRST>u i PM-CommonwealthSummit     10-18 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commonwealth Summit,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Argues Against Sanctions, New Secretary-General Elected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER O'LOUGHLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malayasia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher told a summit meeting of the 49-nation Commonwealth today
that imposing sanctions on South Africa would be ``utterly
irresponsible,'' her aides said.
   Mrs. Thatcher said South African President F.W. de Klerk had
made a ``major step forward'' by releasing eight black nationalist
leaders, allowing peaceful demonstrations and being willing to
``consult all shades of opinion.''
   ``We are most likely to achieve our aim by giving encouragement,
not by trying to behave as if nothing significant had happened,''
an aide, who asked not to be identified, quoted her as saying.
   Mrs. Thatcher, the sole opponent in the Commonwealth of
sanctions against South Africa, spoke during a closed session soon
shortly after the weeklong biennial summit opened.
   Her aide said the prime minister ``thought sanctions at this
stage would be utterly irresponsible.''
   Gongs, cymbals and Malaysian dancers greeted the leaders of the
association of Britain and its former colonies as they filed into
Kuala Lumpur's Putra World Trade Center.
   In another development, the Commonwealth leaders elected Chief
Emeka Anyaoku of Nigeria as the new secretary-general over former
Australian Prime Minister Malcolm Fraser. Malayasian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad, the summit host, refused to disclose the voting
breakdown after what had been a closely fought contest.
   Anyaoku, 56, has been deputy secretary-general at the
Commonwealth Secretariat in London since 1975. He will replace
Guyuanan Sir Shridath Ramphal, whose third five-year term expires
next June.
   Earlier, in opening speeches before the summit went into closed
session, Mahathir called for stronger sanctions against South
Africa, while Canada's Prime Minister Mulroney urged the
maintenance of existing measures.
   The opening speeches reflected differences on whether to press
for tougher sanctions against South Africa now, or give de Klerk
six months to implement promised reforms.
   British officials said Mrs. Thatcher will oppose any move to set
a six-month deadline as well as any tougher measures.
   Debates on the deterioration of the global environment and
international drug trafficking were also scheduled to dominate the
informal agenda. Mahathir, in a speech, blamed developed countries
for the world's environmental problems on the developing countries.
   Pakistan returned to the Commonwealth this month after a 17-year
absence, and Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto headed the delegation.
   The leaders will spend the weekend in retreat at Langkawi Island
off West Malaysia.
</TEXT>
