<FIRST>u i PM-Quake-WorldReax     10-18 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-World Reax,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Leaders Send Sympathy; Pope Prays For Quake Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The pope sent prayers and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev
offered relief aid today as the world expressed grief for the
victims of the devastating earthquake in northern California.
   Thousands jammed international phone lines seeking to get in
touch with relatives in the area hit by Tuesday's quake, which
killed more than 270 people, flattened brides and buildings and
started fires in the San Francisco Bay area.
   Offers of aid came from the Philippines, Japan, France, Britain,
Switzerland and several other nations. An estimated 500,000
Filipinos live in the San Francisco area, one of the largest
Filipino communities in the world.
   ``I would also like to extend my sympathy in a very special way
to our countrymen residing in the area,'' President Corazon Aquino
said in a statement. ``They have our nation's collective prayers
for their safety, and I am directing our Philippine consulate there
to extend whatever help they can to them.''
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev sent condolences in a telegram to
President Bush today, the Soviet news agency Tass said.
   A Soviet Foreign Ministry official said his countrymen
understand the grief of the Americans because of the quake in
Armenia that killed 25,000 people less than a year ago.
   Yuri Dubinin, the Soviet envoy to Washington, was assigned to
contact the Bush administration to learn ``what sort of aid could
be given by the Soviet side, by government or social channels,
towards liquidating the consequences of the earthquake,'' the
official Tass news agency said.
   If the Soviets do help the victims of an American quake, it
would be a first. Millions of dollars of U.S. assistance, along
with aid from numerous other countries, poured into Armenia
following the Dec. 7 quake in the Soviet republic.
   Gennady I. Gerasimov, the Foreign Ministry spokesman, told a
government news briefing the consequences of the Armenian disaster
made the Soviets especially sensitive to the plight of California
residents stricken by the Tuesday quake.
   ``For the Soviet people, who experienced not long ago the pain
of loss from the catastrophe in Armenia, the feelings of grief that
the American people are feeling today are especially close and
understandable,'' Gerasimov told reporters in Moscow.
   A team of four to six British engineers specializing in
earthquake safety design will fly to San Francisco Thursday to help
assess damage, said Alistair Soane, chairman of the consulting firm
Bingham Cotterell in northwest England.
   ``They will be assisting in the damage assessment and learning
lessons to apply for the next time, because there will be a next
time in San Francisco,'' he said.
   Three Swiss experts left for California today to assess what
help their country might give to the earthquake-stricken area. A
French disaster-relief agency also offered to send specialists to
San Francisco to find any survivors trapped under rubble.
   Japanese Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu offered help in rescue and
rebuilding efforts.
   ``As we ourselves are so vulnerable to this natural disaster
that we view the fate of its victims much as that of our own ... we
are following the news from San Francisco with intense care,'' he
said in a message to Bush.
   ``We are prepared to contribute to your efforts of emergency
rescue and reconstruction as much as we can.''
   Thousands of Asians jammed trans-Pacific telephone lines seeking
word of relatives in California.
   ``Every second we get calls for California from those with
relatives there,'' said one of the 100 telephone operators on duty
at the Philippine Long Distance Telephone Company. ``Sometimes they
beg us to connect them but our circuits are down, and we tell them
that much as we want to help them we can't do anything,'' she said.
   In Rome, a Vatican spokesman said Pope John Paul II was ``deeply
saddened'' by the deaths and destruction in the earthquake and was
praying for the victims.
   ``His Holiness joins the population in their suffering and
offering special prayers to God for San Francisco and surrounding
areas,'' said a telegram sent by Cardinal Agostino Casaroli, the
Vatican secretary of state, to Archbishop John Quinn of San
Francisco.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher sent a message to Bush
offering help.
   ``I am very distressed indeed to hear of what is clearly a major
disaster and hasten to send my deepest sympathy to you and all
those who have suffered,'' she said in a statement released by her
office.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and French President Francois
Mitterrand also expressed condolences to Bush.
</TEXT>
