<FIRST>r a PM-FDABribery     10-18 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FDA Bribery,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Company Official Fined $150,000 in FDA Bribery Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pharmaceuticals executive was fined $150,000
and placed on 18 months' probation for bribing a Food and Drug
Administration chemist in a generic drug scam.
   Ashok Patel, 49, of Upper Saddle River, N.J., was also sentenced
Tuesday a year of community service.
   The former senior vice president of Par Pharmaceuticals of
Spring Valley, N.Y., pleaded guilty in July to paying a $500
gratuity to FDA chemist David Brancato.
   Prosecutors said Patel paid Brancato a total of $1,600 to
influence FDA approval of Par generic drugs. He was also accused of
paying $2,900 to Charles Chang, Brancato's boss in the FDA generic
drug division.
   Generic drugs are the chemical equivalents of brand-name drugs.
The rush by generic companies to get approval from the FDA for
their cheaper products has created a lucrative market susceptible
to corruption, investigators said.
   Authorities are investigating allegations that FDA chemists
accepted cash for inside information and favorable treatment of
drug applications.
   Earlier this month, Chang was fined $10,000, ordered to spend a
year in a work-release program and perform 1,000 hours of community
service. Brancato is to be sentenced Wednesday.
   The investigation so far has resulted in guilty pleas from three
generic drug company officials, three FDA chemists and two
pharmaceutical companies.
</TEXT>
