<FIRST>u a PM-Quake-SantaCruz 1stLd-Writethru a0573 10-18 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Santa Cruz, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0573,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Santa Cruz's Historic Center Severely Damaged</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with buildings collapsing in Los
Gatos, looting reported, millions of dollars in damage reported; Picks
up xx graf, `The cave-ins ...'; DELETES now-redundant 16th graf pvs, `In
Watsonville ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police patrolled for looters in the
historic downtown district today and hundreds of people who spent
the night in shelters faced homes and businesses destroyed by the
earthquake centered near here.
   At least five people died in Santa Cruz and surroundings, said
Dinah Phillips, the county's emergency services coordinator. Some
officials put the local death toll from Tuesday's quake as high as
14, but that could immediately be confirmed. More than 200 were
killed in the San Francisco Bay area.
   Devastation also was widespread in Los Gatos, 40 miles to the
northeast. Several blocks in the commercial old town district and
two homes were destroyed, and 30 houses were knocked off
foundations.
   ``Many buildings have collapsed. Damages are in the millions and
millions of dollars,'' said Police Chief Larry Todd. There were no
deaths, but about 25 people suffered injuries ranging from broken
bones to heart attacks.
   Gas and water lines burst and electricity was cut by the quake.
Authorities said it could take up to 72 hours to restore power and
water to Los Gatos.
   Some looting was reported in Los Gatos' central business
district, but no arrests were made, Todd said.
   In Watsonville, dozens of people camped overnight in an open lot
at a subdivision. Some 350 people stayed in six shelters in Santa
Cruz and Watsonville, Ms. Phillips said. In Los Gatos, about 75
people spent the night in Red Cross shelters or at a high school
football stadium.
   Authorities were thankful for the relatively low death toll in
the coastal Santa Cruz area, the closest to the earthquake's
epicenter. The quake registered 6.9 on the Richter scale of ground
motion.
   ``To have an earthquake of this magnitude, and to have as few
fatalities as we've had, I think we were very lucky,'' Ms. Phillips
said.
   Two people were killed when a department store and a coffee
sales shop collapsed in a downtown Santa Cruz shopping mall, she
said.
   Another person died in a traffic accident south of the city when
the car struck horses that had gotten loose on Highway 1, Ms.
Phillips said. One person died when a bakery shop collapsed in
Watsonville, 15 miles south of Santa Cruz; an elderly nursing home
patient in Santa Cruz died of a heart attack.
   The cave-ins were among 40 buildings that collapsed in the two
cities, she said. Preliminary damage estimates totaled $250 million
to private property and $100 million to public property, she said.
   The historic Pacific Garden Mall, a renovated downtown shopping
center of gardens and brick walkways, suffered significant damage.
   National Guard soldiers searched for victims in the rubble well
into the night.
   ``Virtually all the buildings in the Pacific Garden Mall have
structural problems and broken glass,'' said city spokesman Larry
Pearson. ``Many may need to be demolished and others need
reinforcing.''
   Several buildings along a six-block area at the heart of the
development crumbled during the temblor. Ford's, a downtown
department store, sustained major damage and was the site of one
death.
   Twisted mannequins lay in the street atop a pile of broken
glass. Sections of wall collapsed, spewing debris and dust.
   James Campos, a security guard at the mall, said he helped pull
a woman out of the rubble, only later to learn she had died.
   ``The dust was like fog,'' Campos said.
   The quake touched off fires that destroyed nearly 20 homes and
businesses around the county. Two wildfires raged well into the
night before they were contained.
   ``We had so many broken gas lines it was just unbelievable,''
said Matt Ryan, a reserve firefighter standing watch at one
destroyed home.
   Officials in Watsonville described property damage there as
extensive, particularly to brick structures around the town square.
   ``We have no power, a lot of property damage, and some
injuries,'' said police Lt. M. Aluffi.
   Lacking power, Santa Cruz was blacked out overnight. Most roads
from Santa Cruz to the San Francisco area were closed by landslides
or fissures sewn into them by the quake.
   At least two bridges in the Santa Cruz area collapsed and other
highways leading out of the city suffered significant damage, said
Officer Kim Penrose of the California Highway Patrol.
   ``All the mountain passes are closed because of major landslides
and fissures in the road,'' Penrose said.
</TEXT>
