<FIRST>u w PM-PresidentialPensions 1stLd-Writethru a0496 10-18 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Presidential Pensions, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0496,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Bill With $1.8 Million for Former Presidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 3 grafs new with Senate passage; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
Under a.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate sent President Bush legislation
today providing $1.8 million for pensions, office costs and other
expenses of the nation's four living former presidents and Lady
Bird Johnson.
   On a voice vote, the Senate gave final congressional approval to
a spending bill containing the money. There was no debate, and only
four senators were in the chamber when the measure passed.
   The House approved the legislation Tuesday on a 383-30 vote.
   Under a 1958 law, the government each year provides former
presidents and their widows with pensions and money for their
office space, furnishings, equipment, staffs, telephone, mail and
travel.
   This year, the legislation provides $559,500 for Ronald Reagan,
$387,800 for Jimmy Carter, $426,800 for Gerald Ford, $426,700 for
Richard Nixon and $22,200 for the widow of Lyndon Johnson.
   Each president's annual pension is $99,500. Their other expenses
vary.
   The figures do not include the costs of the Secret Service for
protecting the former chief executives. The Secret Service is
expected to spend $12.5 million this year to provide security to
the former presidents and their families.
   There was no separate vote on the money for the former
presidents. But at one point Rep. Paul Kanjorski, D-Pa., complained
about the costs, singling out Reagan's plans to travel to Japan
shortly to reportedly deliver a pair of speeches for a $2 million
fee. He said it was an ``unmitigated atrocity'' for Reagan to make
such a trip with the help of taxpayers' money.
   ``This Congress should examine whether we are too great in our
largesse in providing services and costs to former presidents who
engage in personal income endeavors,'' he said.
   The money was included in an $18.4 billion spending bill for the
Treasury Department, Postal Service and several smaller agencies
for fiscal 1990, which began Oct. 1.
   Other parts of the bill provide:
   _$200,000 to renovate rooms in the vice president's formal
residence to accomodate the young family of Dan Quayle. The Quayle
family had said they would raise money privately to pay for the
work.
   _A 3.6 percent pay raise for all federal civilian employees
except for members of Congress, federal judges, and top executive
branch officials.
   _A prohibition against the use of federal employee health
benefits to pay for abortions unless the woman's life is endangered
by the pregnancy.
   _Grants to several schools represented by members of Congress'
appropriations committees, including $1.5 million for the Rochester
Institute of Technology, $5 million for Michigan Technological
Institute, $1.5 million for the University of Maryland, $1 million
for the University of Hawaii; and $4 million for the University of
Texas, El Paso.
   _Other grants to institutions favored by committee members,
including $2 million to develop a Marine Biomedical Institute for
Advance Studies at Woods Hole, Mass.; $1.5 million for a science
center at Smith College in Massachusetts; and $1.5 million to
design a marine research center in Baltimore.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
