<FIRST>r w PM-US-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0492 10-18 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Believes Soviets Boosting Arms Shipments to Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs with fresh quotes, picking up at pvs 11th graf,
Secretary of</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has boosted military aid to
Afghanistan, prolonging the bloody civil war in that country,
members of Congress said today.
   The Soviets this month increased the amount of arms in daily air
cargo shipments to the Afghan capital of Kabul and are sending Scud
missiles that are being fired against guerrilla positions by 300
Red Army advisers, Rep. Don Ritter, R-Pa., told a news conference.
   Ritter estimated Soviet arms deliveries to Kabul at $400 million
in October. The previous level was estimated by government
officials at between $250 million and $300 million a month.
   U.S. military aid to Afghanistan's mujahedeen guerrillas has
been running at $550 million to $600 million per year, according to
congressional sources. The exact level of the covert American
program is classified.
   The Afghan and Soviet governments boosted the proportion of
weapons in air cargo sent to Kabul from about two-thirds of the
daily volume to about three-quarters, Ritter said.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said on Monday that an
earlier boost in Soviet arms deliveries had prolonged the fighting.
   ``These disturbing actions, this seeming preference for military
solutions, may work in the short run to keep a Najibullah ... in
power,'' Baker. ``In the long run, however, only political
solutions can settle these conflicts.''
   One administration analyst, however, said calculating the exact
tonnage and value of Soviet arms shipments to Kabul was very
uncertain, and stressed the mujahedeen also were beset by internal
rivalries and disorganization.
   The increase in Soviet arms shipments, and problems among the
guerrillas, have prompted the United States to find new arms routes
to the mujahedeen, say congressional and administration sources.
   The CIA, working through Pakistani intelligence, is sending
fewer arms through seven resistance parties based in Peshawar,
Pakistan, and channeling them instead to guerrilla commanders who
control the countryside and who increasingly are thought to hold
the key to Afghanistan's future, according to the sources.
   Neither the exile Afghan Interim Government, formed last
February when the Soviets withdrew, nor the guerrilla commanders
have shown inclination to compromise with Najibullah. Forces loyal
to Najibullah remain entrenched in Kabul and other major cities,
and the battlelines have shifted little since the Red Army left.
   U.S. arms shipments slowed to a trickle at the beginning of the
fighting season last summer, say administration, congressional and
Afghan sources, although that point is in dispute.
   Some arms shipments were disrupted last summer because of the
turmoil in China, which sends arms by rail to Pakistan for
distribution to the mujahedeen, according to a report released Oct.
1 by the chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Sen.
Claiborne Pell, D-R.I.
</TEXT>
