<FIRST>r a PM-FoiledTakeoff     10-18 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foiled Takeoff,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-age Bank Robbery Suspects Nailed Moments Before Airplane Getaway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teen-agers suspected in a bank
robbery were seconds away from what they thought would be their
flight to freedom when their wings were clipped by police.
   The suspects, ages 16 and 17, were aboard a United Airlines
plane Tuesday at Kent County International Airport awaiting takeoff
to Orlando, Fla., when the pilot returned the aircraft to the
terminal, telling passengers there were mechanical difficulties.
   Airport police had contacted the pilot seconds earlier, saying
the two suspects were aboard, police said. When the pair walked off
the plane with the other passengers, police were waiting.
   The two Lowell-area teen-agers, who awaited arraignment today,
used rifles in a hold-up at a bank in Alto hours earlier and
escaped with an undisclosed amount of cash, police said.
   Investigators identified the suspects from a bank camera, and a
tip helped police track them to the airport.
   ``The first one (airport police) checked was United Airlines,''
said Detective Jerry Miedema. ``They were already on the plane with
one-way tickets.''
   Investigators said they recovered some of the money. A portion
was spent on the tickets, they said.
