<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Legislature 2ndLd-Writethru   10-18 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Legislature, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0600,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Denied Chance to Defend Editor on Legislature Floor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with seven grafs to UPDATE with Yeltsin claiming Gorbachev
trying to purge him; picks up 4th graf: The tabloid .. .</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers in Parliament today were denied the
chance to defend a daring editor who had been rebuked by President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and is in danger of being fired, one of the
parliamentarians said.
   It was the second time the group of lawmakers was kept from
speaking in the Supreme Soviet legislature. Nikolai A. Kutsenko, a
deputy from the Ukraine, said the group will submit a petition
signed by 34 legislators accusing Gorbachev of using ``pressure
tactics'' that contradict his own reforms.
   Also today, Communist lawmaker Boris N. Yeltsin accused
Gorbachev of masterminding a campaign to purge him from politics.
   The 58-year-old Yeltsin, who was ousted as Moscow's Communist
Party boss in 1987 but staged a spectacular comeback by winning a
seat in this spring's legislative elections, made the claim in a
printed statement.
   On Monday, Interior Minister Vadim Bakatin told the Supreme
Soviet of an investigation into Yeltsin's report of an attack on
his life. Bakatin said police found the charge to be unfounded, and
Yeltsin replied on the floor of the legislature that the affair
stemmed from a joke he made to a policeman.
   The strange encounter was carried on the national evening news
program, Vremya. Yeltsin accused Gorbachev of making a ``new
attempt to ruin my health and knock me out of the sphere of
political struggle.''
   Meanwhile, Kutsenko said leaders of the Supreme Soviet
legislature decided not to permit the defense of Vladislav A.
Starkov, editor of the weekly Arguments and Facts, to be raised at
the legislature because they considered it an affair of the
Communist Party rather than the government.
   The tabloid was responsible for several sensational stories in
the past year, including the first Soviet disclosure that dictator
Josef Stalin imprisoned or killed as many as 40 million people. It
was also the first Soviet publication to print excerpts of the
memoirs of Nikita S. Khrushchev.
   Kutsenko said he wanted to speak at this morning's session of
the legislature but was told he could not have the floor by
Gorbachev's hand-picked vice president, Anatoly I. Lukyanov, and
the chairmen of the bicameral legislature's two houses, Rafik N.
Nishanov and Yevgeny M. Primakov.
   The petition Kutsenko hoped to read on the floor of the
legislature accuses Gorbachev of trying to discredit the weekly. He
tried to be recognized at Tuesday's evening session, but was denied
the floor by Lukyanov.
   Gorbachev lashed out at selected Soviet editors at a closed-door
Communist Party meeting Friday in an apparent attempt to regain a
measure of control over the press, which has been carrying daily
reports critical of the Soviet system and occasionally of its
leaders.
   The journalists, quoting their bosses who attended and asking
not to be identified, said Gorbachev accused Starkov and other
editors of seeking his political downfall when the nation is torn
by economic crisis and ethnic strife.
   One journalist said Gorbachev likened the situation in the
country to a lake of gasoline that could be set afire by a single
match.
   Soviet journalists said chief party ideologist Vadim A. Medvedev
has told Starkov he must resign and offered him a post at the state
publishing committee, but that Starkov intended to fight to keep
his job.
   Human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov called today for
journalists around the world to stand up for Starkov.
   ``I call on journalists of the world to defend him,'' Sakharov,
the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize laureate, told The Associated Press in
an interview outside the Supreme Soviet hall.
   Sakharov also called on the Supreme Soviet today to strip the
Communist Party of its constitutional monopoly on power, calling it
an anachronism. Most lawmakers appeared to dismiss the idea.
   Known for critical and poignant articles written in plain
language, the weekly Arguments and Facts is the country's most
widely read newspaper, with a circulation of 26 million.
   The tabloid recently calculated that according to readers' mail,
Sakharov was more popular than Gorbachev or any other member of the
Soviet Congress of People's Deputies.
</TEXT>
