<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1159EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-EGermany-Krenz     10-18 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EGermany-Krenz,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Krenz Takes Over From His Aging Mentor Honecker</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egon Krenz, who cautiously fashioned his career by
closely following Erich Honecker, has replaced his mentor as the
new East German leader.
   The state-run news agency ADN announced today that the
52-year-old Krenz would succeed Honecker as head of the Communist
Party and head of state. Honecker had come under increasing fire at
home as opposition mounts and a refugee exodus continues.
   Krenz is by far the youngest official on the 21-member Politburo
dominated by aging Communists, many of them in their 70s. But he
has a reputation for following Honecker's hard-line stance.
   A burly, bushy-haired man, Krenz for long has been plagued by
rumors he was an alcoholic, although there has been virtually
nothing to substantiate that.
   He is known for his spontaneous visits to local bars and
restaurants that are the bane of his bodyguards.
   Krenz was born the son of a tailor in Kolberg, a coastal town in
what is now northwestern Poland, on March 19, 1937.
   He joined the FDJ Communist youth organization in 1953, while he
was still in high school and East Germany was only four years old.
   Krenz studied to be a teacher, but joined the East German army
and rose to the rank of lieutenant before being discharged in 1959.
   After studying in Moscow from 1964 to 1967, Krenz returned to
become a leading official of the Communist youth organization in
East Germany.
   He has been a member of the Communist Party's Central Committee
since 1973 and joined the ruling Politburo 10 years later.
   In recent years, he has been in charge of the Communist youth
organizations and internal security officials, while many
acknowledged he was being groomed to take over from Honecker.
   Krenz lives in a heavily guarded compound reserved for
high-ranking Communist Party officials at Lake Wandlitz, about nine
miles north of Berlin.''
   He has long mirrored Honecker's line on various issues, for
example, repeating the long-held assertion that the allegedly
``imperialist'' West poses a threat to Communist East Germany.
   West Germany's Bild am Sonntag newspaper, in a profile on Oct.
8, said that Krenz is married and has two children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
