<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Hungary 2ndLd-Writethru   10-18 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0626,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Changes Country's Formal Name, Approves Multi-Party Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with amendments including change
in country's formal name, parliament speaker to temporarily assume presidential
powers; picks up 3rd graf pvs: One amendment...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament today overwhelmingly
approved constitutional amendments that are to transform Communist
Hungary into a multi-party democracy.
   Among the 94 changes passed by the 380-member Parliament were
amendments eliminating all references to the leading role of the
newly dissolved Communist Party. Justice Minister Kalman Kulcsar
said they effectively end one-party rule in the East bloc nation.
   The country's formal name also was changed from People's
Republic of Hungary to Republic of Hungary to reflect a break with
the Communist past.
   Another change in the 1949 Constitution abolishes the 21-person
collective presidency and replaces it with the office of the
president.
   The powers of president, who also is commander-in-chief of the
armed forces and wields other authority, will be temporarily
assumed by Parliament Speaker Matyas Szueros until democratic
elections are held next year.
   One amendment states that ``political parties may be freely
established and may freely function providing that they respect the
Constitution and the laws.''
   Another declares that the ``leading role of the Marxist-Leninist
party of the working class ... has been outdated. Instead the
necessary legal framework of a multi-party system must be stated.''
   The historic voting came on the heels of another landmark
decision _ the dissolution last week of the Communist Party and its
replacement by the Hungarian Socialist Party.
   Unlike its monolithic, Marxist-Leninist predecessor, the new
party created last week professes commitment to multi-party
democracy and market forces in the economy.
   The moves are the latest in Hungary's dizzying moves in the past
year to break with its socialist past by establishing democratic
economic and social reforms and improve ties to the West. Like
Poland, Hungary's rush to reform has created friction with
hard-line Warsaw Pact allies.
   One-party rule continues at least temporarily, despite
termination of the Communist Party. Its successor continues to
dominate politics pending the nation's first national multi-party
elections in 41 years.
   Today's session also revealed differences on a key aspect of the
country's democratic strivings _ when and how to choose the
nation's president.
   The government wants the election this year but opposition
parties seek a postponement, asserting they have no time or
resources to organize against Socialist Party candidate Imre
Pozsgay.
   The opposition League of Free Democrats called for a plebiscite
on a postponement and they want Parliament to elect the president
after a new legislature is chosen.
   Legislators today overwhelmingly approved a suggestion by
Premier Miklos Nemeth that Parliament should not put the referendum
issue to the vote, but that separate committees deal with the topic
later.
   Parliamentary elections to be scheduled by June would be the
first instance of free multi-party voting on the national level
since the Communists consolidated power in 1948.
</TEXT>
