<FIRST>u a PM-MarketsRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0604 10-18 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets Rdp, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0604,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Quake Drives Up Some Insurance Stocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with stocks affected by earthquake, overall
market conditions; EDITS to tighten and conform. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California earthquake registered only mildly
this morning on the nation's stock exchanges.
   Stocks of companies in San Francisco and Silicon Valley were
mixed, with some, such as Apple Computer Inc., higher. Many
insurance stocks also rose, apparently on speculation the quake
would provide an opportunity for companies to raise rates.
   The overall stock market opened lower after chaotic trading that
began with Friday's 190-point plunge in the 30 blue-chip stocks
that make up the Dow Jones industrial average. The Dow was up 2.66
points at 2,641.39 at mid-morning today. The number of advancing
issues slightly outpaced decliners on the Big Board.
   The deadly earthquake Tuesday night in the San Francisco area
raised concerns about the extent of insurance companies'
liabilities, which could weigh down those stocks. Technology
companies with operations in California also could encounter some
selling.
   Meanwhile, new evidence of weakening economic activity raised
speculation that a significant slowdown might be a serious drag on
corporate profits.
   Before the market opened, the Commerce Department said housing
construction fell 5.2 percent in September to the lowest level
since the 1982 recession.
   The strongest performers among insurance stocks were the
so-called reinsurers that absorb risk from policy-writing firms.
General Re Corp. was up $4.12{ at $87.87{ and Marsh &amp; McLennan Cos.
was up $3.50 a share at $76.25.
   Among insurers, stocks rebounded quickly after a selloff
triggered by the earthquake, whyich killed more than 250 people.
Some analysts said the quake could produce more than $1 billion in
claims but that the quake losses, coupled with losses from
Hurricane Hugo, could trigger a round of rate increases that would
help the industry's profitability.
   Hardest hit on the stock market was Everex Systems Inc., a maker
of personal computer equipment based in Fremont, Calif., on the
east side of San Francisco Bay. It was off 20 percent, falling
$2.37{ to $9.25.
   Pacific Gas and Electric, the big San Francisco-based utility,
was down 37{ cents a share at $19.62{. Chevron Corp., which has
headquarters in San Francisco, was off 12{ cents at $63.87{. Apple
was up 50 cents at $47.75 a share.
   Before the California disaster, markets around the world had
been stabilizing after the tumultuous period that started with
Friday's plunge in the Dow.
   Stocks lost little ground Tuesday in spite of continued
uncertainty surrounding a proposed buyout of UAL Corp. and a
government report showing a bigger-than-expected trade deficit in
August. The Federal Reserve helped by adding a modest amount of
reserves to the banking system.
   The earthquake caused some nervousness on foreign stock markets
today. In London, dealers said they expected the disaster to affect
trading on Wall Street, and the quake was blamed for declines on
the Australian and New Zealand markets.
   Prices opened higher on the London exchange, but analysts said
fears of a further slump had not dissipated. The Financial
Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was up 14.0 points, or 0.7
percent, at 2,149.5 when trading began.
   Dealers said the quake did not affect trading in Tokyo but said
if it did affect Wall Street, the fallout could hit Tokyo on
Thursday.
   In Tokyo, stocks posted moderate gains today, with the 225-issue
Nikkei Stock Average gaining 111.48 points, or 0.32 percent, to
close at 35,107.56.
   The Federal Reserve pumped $1.5 billion into the banking system
to make sure banks had enough reserves for emergency loans to any
traders who lost big in the market's gyrations. It had injected $2
billion in reserves Monday.
</TEXT>
