<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1238EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-PrincessGina     10-18 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Princess Gina,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Princess Gina of Liechtenstein Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VADUZ, Liechtenstein (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Gina of Liechtenstein, wife
of the head of state of Liechtenstein, died Wednesday, six days
before her 68th birthday, the government announced.
   The popular Austrian-born princess had been hospitalized since
last month for treatment of an undisclosed illness. A government
communique said her condition suddenly worsened late Tuesday and
she died Wednesday morning.
   ``Her family was with her when she passed away peacefully
shortly after receiving the last sacraments,'' the communique said.
   She is survived by her 83-year-old husband, Franz Josef II, the
world's longest ruling head of state.
   They married in 1943, five years after Franz Josef II took
office as the 12th ruling prince of Liechtenstein, a tiny
principality between Austria and Switzerland. It has become one of
the world's wealthiest countries.
   In 1984, Franz Josef II turned over the running of the country
to his son, Hans Adam, oldest of their five children, but he
remained head of state.
   Princess Gina was president of the Liechtenstein Red Cross and
active in many other charities. The government proclaimed a week of
official mourning. Funeral services were scheduled Oct. 24.
</TEXT>
