<FIRST>r i AM-SovietDefector     10-18 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Defector,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Rejects Soviet's Request To Defect, Refers Him to U.N.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet artist appealed to the United
Nations for refugee status Wednesday after the U.S. Embassy
rejected his bid to defect.
   Daoud Alyev, of the Soviet republic of Azerbaijan, asked the
Cairo office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees to put him
under its protection.
   The agency's representative, Abdel-Mawla el-Solh, said the case
would be examined to decide whether Alyev is eligible. Under the
1949 Geneva Convention on Refugees, a person qualifies for asylum
if he is in peril of political or religious persecution at home.
   Alyev, 45, dropped out of a tour group visiting Egypt last week.
He first asked the Turkish Embassy for asylum but was rejected. He
went to the U.S. Embassy on Sunday with a note that said: ``I am a
Soviet citizen. I want to defect to the United States. I speak only
Russian.''
   U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Marcelle Wahba confirmed Tuesday that
Alyev had requested to defect and had been referred to the United
Nations.
   Alyev said he defected because he did not have enough artistic
freedom in the Soviet Union. He also said political turmoil in his
republic is stifling his creativity.
   Azerbaijan is involved in a long-running dispute with the
neighboring republic of Armenia over a piece of land known as
Nagorno-Karabakh. The enclave is in the republic of Azerbaijan, but
most of its residents are Armenians, and Armenia is fighting to
annex it.
</TEXT>
