<FIRST>r i AM-Cyprus-Turkey     10-18 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cyprus-Turkey,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protest Over New Plan to Settle Bulgarian Turks in North Cyprus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cyprus filed a protest with the U.N.
Security Council on Wednesday over plans to settle ethnic Turks
from Bulgaria in Turkish-occupied northern Cyprus.
   The protest followed a statement by the Turkish Cypriot leader,
Rauf Denktash, earlier in the week about the settlement of 200
families of ethnic Turks in northern Cyprus.
   Government spokesman Akis Fantis said the protest asks the five
permanent Security Council members _ Britain, China, France, the
Soviet Union, and the United States _ ``to intervene in the
direction of Turkey to end the illegal actions of Denktash.''
   This is the second protest by the Cyprus government to the
Security Council over the settlement of Bulgarian Turks in Cyprus,
which is divided into Turkish and Greek sectors.
   North Cyprus has been under Turkish control since a 1974
invasion that forced the Greek Cypriot population of the region to
flee south.
   About 40,000 Turkish Cypriots moved north from the south, and
Turkey has shifted 35,000-50,000 more settlers from the mainland to
north Cyprus to take over homes and properties of the Greek Cypriot
refugees and strengthen the Turkish presence.
   U.N. resolutions have called for the withdrawal of the Turkish
troops and settlers from north Cyprus and the return of the Greek
Cypriot refugees.
</TEXT>
