<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Reagan     10-18 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Reagan,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President Reagan Making High-Priced Visit to Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just weeks after Sony Corp.'s controversial
purchase of Columbia Pictures, another Japanese company is spending
big money on an American media giant _ former President Ronald
Reagan.
   Officials of the Fujisankei Communications Group, Japan's
largest media conglomerate, say they are spending about $7 million
to bring Reagan and his wife, Nancy, to Japan for nine days
beginning Friday.
   Welcome posters showing pictures of the former first couple dot
subway stations. Advertisements on Fujisankei's television and
radio stations publicize a ``Friendship Concert'' during the visit
that will feature Perry Como and benefit the Ronald Reagan
Presidential Library Foundation.
   The company chartered a TWA Boeing 747 to bring Reagan's
20-member party to Tokyo.
   A guest house near Mount Fuji, where the Reagans will stay two
nights, was specially refurbished for them at a price of $140,000.
   Reagan is to use two of the nine days to meet with present and
former Japanese government officials. On Monday, he and Mrs. Reagan
are to attend a lunch given by Emperor Akihito and Empress Michiko,
and in the afternoon he is to meet with Prime Minister Toshiki
Kaifu.
   The Reagans also will attend a luncheon given by former prime
ministers Yasuhiro Nakasone and Noboru Takeshita, both of whom
served during Reagan's presidency.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Taizo Watanabe said Tuesday the
government is considering a $2 million donation to the Reagan
library to be announced during the former president's visit.
   Japan has donated in the past to the libraries of former U.S.
presidents Lyndon Johnson, Richard Nixon, Jimmy Carter and Gerald
Ford, Watanabe said.
   For the last seven days of his visit, Reagan will be under the
wing of Fujisankei, which owns the Fuji Telecasting Corp., the
newspaper Sankei Shimbun, and Nippon Hoso, Japan's biggest
commercial radio network.
   The conglomerate is known for a combination of conservative
ideology, low-brow programming, and impressive private art
collections.
   Fujisankei Chairman Nobutaka Shikanai ``is a great fan of Reagan
and thinks that the Reagan presidency did a lot for U.S.-Japan
relations,'' said a Fujisankei official.
   ``He wants to bring Reagan in and give him a chance to talk to
the Japanese people, and hopefully the visit will help smooth over
some of the problem areas in U.S.-Japan relations.''
   Company officials say Shikanai first invited Reagan to visit
Japan in 1983.
   Accompanying Reagan will be Charles Z. Wick, former director of
the U.S. Information Agency, who helped arrange the visit.
   Also traveling with Reagan will be his chief of staff, Frederick
J. Ryan, Reagan spokesman Mark Weinberg, and Mrs. Reagan's
hairdresser, Julius Bengtsson.
   Filling up the plane will be about 200 relatives of U.S. armed
forces personnel currently serving in Japan.
</TEXT>
