<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1320EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     10-18 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Callers trying to connect with ``Julie,'' a
beautiful bikini-clad blonde portrayed on Johnny Walker scotch
billboards in southern California, are getting a Dr. George, a guy
named Rich or a fax machine.
   The advertisement on more than 60 billboards in the area invites
people to call Julie and gives her telephone number.
   But the ad doesn't include Julie's area code. The sprawling
urban region has five area codes and callers have been trying each
one.
   Callers using the 213 area code can hear Julie say: ``I was just
thinking how much I love athletic men.''
   But calls to the same number in the 805 area code get a
physician who asked that he be identified only as George.
   ``It's a nuisance,'' he said. ``It's irresponsible and it's a
waste of time.''
   A call to the same number with the 714 area code is answered by
the electronic whistles of a facsimile machine.
   An 818 area code call gets a phone company recording saying the
``call cannot be completed as dialed.''
   In the 619 area code, the number reaches the answering machine
of a guy named Rich, who tells callers: ``Thanks a lot and have a
great day.''
   Gannett Outdoor Advertising in Southern California put up the
billboards for Smith-Greenland Advertising of New York City and has
agreed to paint on an area code, said Gannett spokesman Ron
Cipriani.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WAUWATOSA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dispatcher Cheryl Ann Heck says the
incoming call to the city's 911 emergency number sounded like it
could be the work of a prankster _ but she wasn't about to take any
chances.
   ``We could hear some clunking and clicking on the phone, and
every once in a while you would hear the tones, like someone was
depressing the push buttons,'' she said.
   She traced the call and sent police, medical and fire department
personnel rushing to the address.
   Rescue workers broke into the locked house but found nobody home
except the apparent emergency caller: a 1-year-old basset hound
named Mandy.
   ``We've played back the tape several times,'' Ms. Heck said.
``Once you know it's a dog, you can hear it gnawing on the phone
and running down a hallway.''
   Jim Jermain, manager of product marketing for Wisconsin Bell,
said the dog apparently had been carrying and chewing on a cordless
phone.
   ``It appears that with some cordless phones, as the battery gets
low, they send out clicking sounds that are interpreted by our
electronic switcher as a 911 call,'' he said.
   Lisa Booz, Mandy's owner, said she was gone only about 45
minutes to take her cat to the veterinarian about five blocks away.
   ``By the time I got home, all the trucks were gone. My neighbors
told me what happened,'' she said, adding that she called
authorities to apologize.
</TEXT>
