<FIRST>u w PM-SFEarthquake-FEMA 3rdLd-Writethru a0606 10-18 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Earthquake-FEMA, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0606,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says the Disaster System Works</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 10 grafs with Bush quotes, Fitzwater estimate; picks up
at pvs 7th graf, Shortly after; deletes last graf to shorten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials moved quickly today to
assess the damage from Tuesday's disastrous California earthquake
and speed aid to the region as President Bush declared, ``The
machinery is working.''
   The president, whose administration's response to Hurricane Hugo
last month was criticized by some lawmakers as slow and
bureaucratic, signed a declaration triggering a flow of federal
financial aid to the quake-stricken San Francisco Bay area.
   Bush then went to the headquarters of the Federal Emergency
Management Agency and met with officials for about 25 minutes. On
his way out, he told reporters: ``What I have seen is a highly
coordinated, effective federal effort.''
   ``In the sense that if there's anything good, it's that the
agency is well-prepared ...,'' he said. ``The machinery is
working.''
   He said officials were continuing to assess the damage estimates.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said there is $273
million in unallocated funds from a $1.1 billion appropriation for
the Hurricane Hugo cleanup ``which can be used for immediate
assistance in San Francisco.''
   ``That obviously means that we won't have enough for all of the
emergencies that are now facing us, and we will have to consider
appropriate requests for follow-on funding,'' said the presidential
spokesman.
   Asked whether the federal response to the earthquake will be
faster than it was to Hugo, Bush said, ``I hope there will be less
carping ... I think they took a hit on that.''
   ``I guess you can never avoid all criticism. FEMA then responded
very promptly and they're responding very, very promptly now,'' he
said.
   FEMA has an emergency fund that can be used for a variety of
purposes, including hotel accomodations for homeless people and as
much as $10,000 per family for recovery assistance, said the
agency's associate director, Grant Peterson.
   Shortly after the quake occurred, FEMA set up a disaster field
office in The Presidio, an Army post in San Francisco, headed by
regional director Robert Vickers.
   Peterson said about 100 FEMA employees were on the scene,
coordinating with state energency workers, and the agency has told
its staff in areas as far away as Seattle, Wash., to remain on
alert indefinitely.
   Peterson said the agency was making a concerted effort to avoid
the kind of criticism it faced after Hurricane Hugo devastated
South Carolina last month.
   During that emergency, Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C. referred to
the agency as ``a bunch of bureaucratic jackasses'' for its alleged
slowness in responding to to needs of victims.
   This time, Peterson said, FEMA is taking steps to fully inform
the news media about its actions and avoid misunderstandings.
`We're not waiting to respond, we're responding right now,'' he
said Tuesday night.
   Peterson said the agency had found itself severely strained in
South Carolina because Hugo already had hit the U.S. Virgin Islands
and Puerto Rico.
   In California, disaster officials had been preparng for years
for an expected major earthquake by holding dress reheasrsals.
   Peterson said the agency has a $1.18 billion pool that was set
up to deal with damage from Hurricane Hugo last month, and some of
that money can be used to help victims of the earthquake.
   The agency's first action was to shuffle officials from one
place to another to be in position to respond quickly to requests
when they come in from California. For example, FEMA officials were
being flown from Denton, Texas, to Sacramento to help with the
paperwork, Peterson said.
   After Hugo swept across the Virgin Islands, a FEMA official said
no aid was being sent right away because the territory's governor
had not asked for it. The official acknowledged at the time that
one reason the request may have been slow in coming was that the
hurricane knocked out telephone lines.
   ``There's not going to be a problem with California asking the
right questions,'' Peterson said Tuesday night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
