<FIRST>r a PM-HUD-Forfeiture     10-18 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Forfeiture,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD to Order Group to Forfeit Nearly $700,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior HUD official has decided a real estate
partnership that includes a former lawyer of President Reagan must
repay $700,000 in government grant money, a published report said.
   The decision by C. Austin Fitts, the newly confirmed assistant
secretary for housing at HUD, reversed an earlier judgment by a
ranking official of the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, The New York Times reported in today's editions.
   HUD investigators say federal funds were spent inappropriately
and that the partners, including Washington lawyer Edward
Weidenfeld, failed to invest sufficiently from their own funds in
the federally subsidized housing project in Brunswick, Ga.
   Part of the $700,000 that Weidenfeld and his two partners must
repay will go to the government, and the remainder will be
reinvested in the Cypress Mill Plantation apartment complex.
   The chief HUD housing official in Atlanta, Neil Zittrauer, said
he understood the partners invested as little as $100 in the
complex, which received mortgage assistance from two HUD programs.
   ``It was a very negligible investment on their part,'' Zittrauer
said.
   In the earlier ruling, HUD deputy assistant secretary R. Hunter
Cushing, overrode regional housing officials in Atlanta and said
the partnership should repay only $88,000. Cushing resigned earlier
this year and since has become a focus of congressional
investigations into political abuses at HUD.
   Weidenfeld was deputy general counsel and later general counsel
in Reagan's 1980 campaign. He was chairman of the legal advisory
committee to the 1984 campaign committee.
</TEXT>
