<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-EastGermany 2ndLd-Writethru a0689-aJ</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-East Germany, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0689-a0615,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Challenges New East German Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today the turnover in East
Germany's government may not lead to improvements in East-West
relations, but his administration challenged the new party
leadership to make an effort in that direction.
   Bush told reporters he was following with interest the
replacement of Erich Honecker as East Germany's leader with
Politburo member Egon Krenz.
   But, he told reporters, ``whether that reflects a change in
East-West relations, I don't think so. I don't think it does.
Because Mr. Krenz has been very much in accord with the policies of
Honecker. So it's too early to say.''
   At the same time, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said:
``We hope this change signals movement by the (East German)
leadership toward reforms and responds to the hopes and aspirations
of its people.''
   ``The United States is prepared to develop stronger and more
constructive relations with (East Germany). It is up to the new
leadership there to demonstrate through its deeds that it's ready
to move in that direction,'' Fitzwater said.
   Honecker, 77, was removed as party leaders met to discuss the
flight of East Germans to the West and growing pro-democracy
protests.
   The state-run news service, ADN, reported that Krenz, 52, in
charge of security issues as well as government-run youth groups,
had taken over as the party chief.
   Bush was asked about the government turnover by reporters as he
met with congressional leaders to discuss the San Francisco
earthquake and other issues.
   ``There's dynamic change taking place in Eastern Europe and now,
it appears, the GDR (East Germmany). But whether this step is a
step toward more openness, I think it's way too early to say,''
Bush said.
   ``There's nothing in the record to indicate it is,'' he added.
   Privately, administration officials expressed guarded optimism
that the change might spell movement on the part of East Germany
toward more political openness.
   ``We've been closely following events in East Germany. There's
been a lot of activity and there's an obvious connection between
Honecker's departure and recent events,'' said an administration
official who spoke on the condition of anonyity.
   As to whether the administration would use the changes to make
new overtures toward the East German government, the official said,
``we'll have to see.''
</TEXT>
