<FIRST>u w PM-Quake-Phones     10-18 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Phones,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pacific Bell Says Telephone Network Survived Without Significant
Damage</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Lissa, 7th graf, is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pacific Bell officials said today their
telephone network survived Tuesday's devastating Northern
California earthquake without significant damage, but the system
was being overloaded by a huge increase in calls into and out of
the San Francisco area.
   Because of the surge in long-distance calls to the region, many
calls were being blocked. Recorded messages told callers to try
again later.
   The local network around San Francisco was unscathed, but
because of the big increase in calls, callers were having
difficulty connecting with the network, said Mary Hallisey, a
Washington spokeswoman for Pacific Bell's parent, the Pacific
Telesis Group.
   ``The local network is in fine shape,'' Hallisey said. ``There
is no damage to the central offices or the network itself. It is
operating. There is a gridlock problem based on the fact that so
many people are trying to call in all at once. ... When you pick up
the phone out there you don't get a dial tone right away. ... The
system is not out, it's just a very slow dial tone.
   ``You've got customers trying to get ahold of friends, loved
ones, work,'' said Sue Galloway, district manager for Pacific
Bell's network in Southern California.
   ``It's extremely heavy, and my anticipation is it will get
heavier as the day goes one,'' Galloway said by telephone from Los
Angeles.
   ``We're asking people not to call in for a 24-hour period,''
said Lissa Zanville, a Pacific Bell spokeswoman.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., which handles about 70
percent of the nation's long-distance calls, appealed to people not
to try telephoning the earthquake area.
   AT&amp;T spokesman Herb Linnen said the company was blocking part of
a flood of calls into the area so San Franciscans could call out.
   ``Between 2 a.m. (EDT) and 10 a.m. there were 17 million calling
attempts in AT&amp;T's nationwide network. That compared with 13
million long-distance calling attempts during the same 2 a.m to 10
a.m time frame the week before,'' Linnen said.
   He did not know how many calls were placed to the San Francisco
area.
   ``Clearly, we have not seen volumes of this kind in the memories
of veteran network managers, and it is clearly the interest in and
concern for the San Francisco Bay situation.
   ``We are urging people elsewhere to not call into that area so
we can devote more of our circuits to what we're trying to do _
give priority to calls coming out of that affected area,'' he said,
and this request will apply until further notice.
</TEXT>
