<FIRST>u i PM-UN-Cuba     10-18 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Cuba,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuba Elected To Security Council, First Time Since Revolution 30
Years Ago</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to restore AP logo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba was elected today to the Security
Council for the first time since its revolution 30 years ago.
   Diplomats said Cuba's election was a sign of increasing
respectability and importance for the communist nation still
shunned by the U.S. government and subjected to a trade embargo.
   The U.S. government, which did not openly oppose Cuba's seating,
said it hoped the Havana government would act constructively on the
council. It called on Cuba to respect the Central American peace
accords and not to interfere with military or covert aid in
regional affairs.
   ``We hope it will recognize that it has a special responsibility
as a member of the Security Council to act constructively to end
regional conflicts, not contribute to them,'' according to a
statement read by a State Department spokesman.
   Washington has accused Cuba of subversion and military
involvement in Latin America as well as in Africa. Cuba, however,
has been withdrawing its troops from Angola as part of an overall
political agreement in Southern Africa.
   The last time Cuba served on the council was in 1956, before its
1959 revolution. The only other time was in 1947.
   Cuba was elected by the General Assembly in a secret ballot,
along with four other non-permanent members of the council serving
two-year terms. Cuba, which replaces Brazil, received the highest
number of votes in the balloting _ 146 out of 156 votes cast.
   The other new members are the Ivory Coast replacing Algeria,
Zaire replacing Senegal, Romania replacing Yugoslavia and
Democratic Yemen replacing Nepal. The other non-permanent members
are Canada, Colombia, Ethiopia, Finland and Malaysia.
   The five permanent members are the United States, Britain,
China, France and the Soviet Union, all of whom hold veto power.
   The election of Cuba and Yemen, another communist nation
critical of the West, were not expected to significantly alter the
balance in the council.
   The Security Council has responsibility for maintaining
international peace and security and its resolutions are considered
binding, although they often are flouted.
</TEXT>
