<FIRST>r w PM-US-Turkey 1stld-Writethru a0498 10-18 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Turkey, 1st ld-Writethru, a0498,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration to Fight Genocide Measure</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs grafs 9-10, Whether or not, with new grafs 9-11 to
add background.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle over whether the United States
should commemorate an ``Armenian genocide'' is going to the Senate
floor where the Bush administration will try again to defeat the
measure.
   The Democrat-controlled Senate Judiciary Committee, on an 8-6
vote, approved the measure Tuesday.
   The move angered Turkey, which had waged a full-scale lobbying
campaign to kill the measure in committee. The NATO ally, which
receives about $500 million in U.S. aid a year, sees the resolution
as tantamount to a comparison with Hitler's regime in Germany.
   ``Now we've got to concentrate on 100 people,'' said Mike
McNamara, a lobbyist for Turkey. No date has been set for full
consideration by the Senate.
   Turkey was aided in its campaign by the administration, which
summoned the American ambassador from Ankara to help work against
the measure. Publicly, however, the State Department did not
announce its opposition to the resolution until after the vote.
   ``The bottom line is that we oppose it,'' Roman Popadiuk, a
White House spokesman, said late Tuesday.
   Before the panel passed the measure, Sen. Howard Metzenbaum,
D-Ohio, tried unsuccessfully to soften it by eliminating the word
``genocide.''
   Bush's national security adviser, Brent Scowcroft, suggested the
change, Metzenbaum said. He sought to replace the word genocide
with a ``national day of remembrance'' for Armenians.
   ``Whether or not it is a genocide is arguable,'' Metzenbaum
said, discussing the reported deaths of 1.5 million Armenians in
the Ottoman Empire between 1915 and 1923.
   Armenians, the bulk of whom now live within Soviet borders, have
a long history of ethnic and religious conflict with Turks. Turkey
claims hundreds of thousands of people, not 1.5 million, died from
war, famine and epidemics during the war years and that many Turks
were among them.
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., chairman of the Judiciary Committee,
said, ``The only debate is whether it was attempted genocide or
genocide.'' Moreover, Biden said Turkey's opposition to the
resolution was irrelevant.
   ``The fact that the government of Turkey opposes it is of no
consequence,'' he said.
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., argued genocide did occur. ``People
were massacred because of their ancestry,'' in the Ottoman Empire,
he said.
   The measure, sponsored by Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of
Kansas, aroused strong feelings among Americans of Turkish and
Armenian descent.
   ``I became the focal point for the greatest lobbying campaign
I've experience in a long while,'' said Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo.
   The Dole measure would set April 24, 1990 to memorialize the 1.5
million Armenians who were killed between 1915 and 1923 during the
days of the Ottoman Empire.
   Although the Bush administration opposes it, President Bush
voiced support for language marking the ``Armenian genocide''
during the 1988 campaign.
   The Reagan administration opposed similiar resolutions when they
came before the House in past years. None of those passed.
</TEXT>
