<FIRST>r w AM-FlagBurning     10-18 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Burning,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democratic Leader Blasts Bush on Flag Amendment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democratic Leader George Mitchell,
gaining confidence that a constitutional amendment to ban burning
the American flag will be defeated, said Tuesday it is ``tragic''
that President Bush had championed the measure.
   ``The Bill of Rights has never been amended or tampered with in
200 years of our nation's history and now, tragically, the
president of the United States himself ... is leading the effort to
change the Bill of Rights,'' Mitchell, the Senate majority leader
from Maine, told a group of reporters.
   ``Just a minute, I'm just getting warmed up,'' a broadly
grinning Mitchell declared when a reporter tried to ask a question
about an unrelated issue.
   Mitchell said it was ``most unfortunate'' that Bush had
campaigned for the amendment and said the measure sought ``to force
Americans to choose between the flag and the Constitution.''
   ``Americans do revere the flag and they do revere the
Constitution and they can do both,'' Mitchell said.
   The Senate planned to vote on the amendment Thursday morning.
   Critics say it would curb freedom of speech. Proponents call it
the only way to prevent recurrence of the Supreme Court ruling in
June that held existing law against flag burning unconstitutional.
   Bush has been the most visible champion of the measure while
Senate Democrats have provided the bulk of the opposition. But two
former Republican sponsors, Sens. John Danforth, R-Mo., and Warren
Rudman, R-N.H., dropped their support on Tuesday because of the
measure's impact on the Bill of Rights.
   The House last week approved and sent to Bush's desk a new
approach to ban flag burning by simple statute. It was carefully
worded in an effort to bring it into line with the Supreme Court's
ruling.
   Bush said that he would allow it to become law while continuing
to press for the amendment.
   Growing surer that they would prevail against the amendment,
Democratic senators trooped to the floor to denounce it.
   Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said that Americans ``are not
clamoring at us to amend the Constitution.''
</TEXT>
