<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-TwinPeaks     10-18 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Twin Peaks,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mountaintop Views of the Quake Attract the Curious</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the sun rose Wednesday in San Francisco,
residents went to the top of the scenic 900-foot Twin Peaks area to
see the city for themselves.
   What they saw underneath the haze, smog and dust shocked them _
perfect stillness and practically no traffic.
   ``It's so quiet,'' said an awestruck Marianne Wong as she gazed
toward downtown and the Golden Gate Bridge.
   Wong arrived at the Twin Peaks Vista Point _ called the
``natural dividing point of the city'' _ with a friend about 9
a.m., skipping the normal routine of school and work to see the
city firsthand the morning after a catastrophic earthquake rumbled
through a wide area of Northern California.
   The chance to see the San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge without
traffic was also what brought Paul Brager to the mountain.
   ``I think we are very lucky it wasn't like the 1906 quake, but I
didn't think a (magnitude) seven would cause this much damage,'' he
said.
   Looking from the vista point toward the Marin headlands, bridges
and city neighborhoods had only light traffic. Above, only the
Goodyear blimp could be seen floating over the city.
   Sirens continually pierced the otherwise quiet morning. Beyond
that, the only noise to be heard came from chirping birds.
   John Brown and Tim Tanner showed up at the Twin Peaks site,
which is near their apartment, carrying cups of coffee and
marveling at the scene.
   ``I've been in other earthquakes, but nothing like this,'' said
Tanner.
   Tanner told Brown, who runs a travel agency, that he will be
busy for the next few days.
   ``People will want to be getting out of here,'' Tanner said.
</TEXT>
