<FIRST>r w AM-HousingStarts     10-18 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Starts,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Starts at Slowest Pace in 7 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction, buffeted by rising
mortgage rates, fell for a second straight month in September,
declining to the weakest pace in seven years, the government
reported Wednesday.
   The Commerce Department said that construction of new homes and
apartments dropped 5.2 percent following a 6.2 percent August
decline.
   The back-to-back drops pushed construction starts down to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.26 million units, the slowest
pace since October 1982.
   Many analysts blamed the September decline on builders' concerns
about high levels of unsold homes and worries that rising mortgage
rates during the month might further crimp new home sales.
   Because much of the fall-off was concentrated in the South, some
analysts suggested that Hurricane Hugo affected construction in
that area.
   David Seiders, chief economist for the National Association of
Home Builders, said that the housing weakness highlighted the
urgent need for the Federal Reserve to lower interest rates to keep
the economy from toppling into a recession.
   Many analysts said they believed that the central bank has begun
a series of small credit-easing moves. They noted that a closely
watched indicator of Fed intentions, the overnight federal funds
rate, has dropped about 0.25 percentage point to 8.75 percent since
the Friday the 13th stock market crash.
   The Fed pumped an additional $1.5 billion into the banking
system Wednesday, the third consecutive daily cash infusion since
Friday's market turmoil.
   While the Fed's efforts were aimed at reassuring skittish
financial markets about plentiful reserves for emergency loans,
analysts said that the Fed was likely to keep interest rates at
lower levels because of the weak housing construction and other
signs of a slowing economy.
   Fixed-rate mortgages, which climbed as high as 10.22 percent in
early September, have fallen slightly in October and now stand at
9.95 percent, according to a weekly survey by the Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp.
   So far this year housing construction is running 6.2 percent
below a year ago with housing starts down in six of the last nine
months.
   For September, construction of single-family homes fell by 2.1
percent to an annual rate of 971,000 units, the second consecutive
month that single-family homes have been below the 1 million mark.
Construction of multi-family units was down 14.1 percent to an
annual rate of 292,000 units.
   In a disturbing sign for the future, permits for new units
dropped as well in September, falling 2.4 percent to 1.30 million
units.
</TEXT>
