<FIRST>r a AM-People     10-18 0929</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0968</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William F. Buckley Jr., the columnist,
conservative, television host, espionage author and sailing
aficionado, has still another description to his name:
harpsichordist.
   Buckley, host of PBS' ``Firing Line'' and founder of the
conservative National Review, made his debut as a solo
harpsichordist Tuesday night with the Phoenix Symphony Orchestra
after only a year of practice.
   Buckley performed an encore after the audience of 550 at the
Scottsdale Center for the Arts gave him a standing ovation for his
performance of Bach's Concerto in F Minor.
   He came off stage agonizing over a miscue. ``How could I have
screwed those three bars up?'' he groaned.
   ``We finished together,'' said conductor James Sedares, assuring
Buckley that everything went fine.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During her 54 years in show business, Jane Wyman
has answered calls for 86 movies and nine years of ``Falcon
Crest.'' But the actress says she doesn't answer any calls as
Ronald Reagan's ex-wife.
   ``I don't have to be known as that,'' said Wyman, who ended an
eight-year boycott on interviews by speaking to Vanity Fair for its
November issue. ``I've been in this business longer than he has.
It's such bad taste.
   ``They wouldn't say it if I was Joe Blow's ex-wife. It wouldn't
even be mentioned.''
   Wyman and the former president were married from 1940-48.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Not everybody likes fireworks, at least at 3
a.m., filmmaker Barry Levinson has discovered.
   Levinson's production company apologized Wednesday for staging a
fireworks show that dragged on until the wee hours Tuesday,
prompting residents of Baltimore's Fells Point neighborhood to
clamor for a noise curfew.
   The Oscar-winning director of ``Rain Man'' had obtained a
fireworks permit to film a recreation of a 1914 Fourth of July
celebration in the picturesque neighborhood by the harbor.
   After receiving numerous complaints from sleepless residents,
the Baltimore Fire Department placed an 11 p.m. curfew on the film
company's permit.
   ``We did get permission by the city to show fireworks, but the
vintage fireworks for the 1914 scene were a lot noisier than we had
envisioned,'' said Marie Rowe, a spokeswoman for Rowhouse
Productions. ``We're in the process of distributing explanations
and an apology to residents of Fells Point to make some kind of
recompense.''
   The film, now untitled, stars Aidan Quinn of ``Desperately
Seeking Susan'' and Elizabeth Perkins of ``Big.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Sea of Love'' actress Ellen Barkin has given
birth to an 8-pound boy, the Daily News reported Wednesday.
   The News said Barkin gave birth to the baby, named Jack, at an
undisclosed New York hospital.
   It is the first child for Barkin and her husband, Irish actor
Gabriel Byrne, a former member of Dublin's Abbey Theater. They were
married in 1988.
   ``We've been asked not to make comment,'' said a woman who
identified herself as an assistant to Hildy Gottlieb, Barkin's
agent in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guitarist Bob Mould said the year he spent working
on his farm after the painful breakup of the three-man band Husker
Du was therapeutic. After nine years and eight albums, the
Minneapolis-based band that was a favorite of critics and college
radio programmers split up in early 1988.
   ``It was always part of the chemistry of that band _ there were
certain elements of self-defeatism in there that I was getting real
tired of: fear of success, fear of not being the hippest
underground band,'' said Mould, who will perform Friday in Dallas
to promote his new solo album, ``Workbook.''
   After the year on his Minnesota farm, Mould moved to New York
City.
   ``I thought last year was pretty intense when I isolated myself
in the farm working. I look forward to recreating that kind of
intensity, and what better place than New York to feed off,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail Baryshnikov says he plans to keep
dancing _ even though his career in ballet is almost over.
   ``My strongest talent, I would say, is to be a dancer,'' the
41-year-old dancer and film star told Vanity Fair. ``But that's
pretty much gone. ... Maybe two more good years.''
   ``My body is not what it used to be, because I really abused
myself a lot trying to learn so many dancing styles,'' said
Baryshnikov, who recently resigned as artistic director of the
American Ballet Theatre.
   But he said there was one style he failed to master: tap. ``Just
forget it,'' he said. ``I tried very hard when Gregory Hines (his
co-star in the film ``White Nights'') gave me pointers, but I was
the dumbest. My legs wouldn't work that way.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Diana presented the British Designer of
the Year Award to the designing duo of Graham Fraser and Richard
Nott, but she stole the show in a stunning white strapless beaded
gown and high-collared jacket.
   At a glittering ceremony Tuesday night climaxing a charity
fashion show at Royal Albert Hall, the British Classics award was
presented to designer Nicole Farhi and the British Glamour award to
Antony Price. Catherine Walker, who designed Diana's dress, was a
nominee in the glamour category.
   Sir Hardy Amies, 80, who has designed Queen Elizabeth II's
clothes since the 1950s, was given a special award for his lifetime
contribution to fashion. ``Longevity pays,'' he said afterward.
   Fraser and Nott established Workers for Freedom in 1985 in a
tiny shop in London's Soho district and have built an enthusiastic
international following for their romantic folkloric style and use
of natural fabrics.
</TEXT>
