<FIRST>r w AM-Mosbacher-Mexico     10-18 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mosbacher-Mexico,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mosbacher Predicts Free Trade Treaty With Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher said
Wednesday he can foresee the day when the United States and Mexico
will have a free trade treaty similar to the U.S-Canadian
arrangement.
   Looking even further into the future _ perhaps 20 years or so _
Mosbacher told a Senate banking panel the United States should set
a goal of having free trade among all countries in the Western
Hemisphere.
   Mosbacher said informal talks have already been held with
Mexican trade officials about removing trade barriers separating
the two countries.
   ``They are cautious,'' he said. ``We should not push them too
hard, too fast. But they are interested, very interested.''
   Earlier, Mosbacher had told the international finance and
monetary policy subcommittee that the Bush administration hopes
Mexico will ``be the first olive out of the jar'' among Latin
American nations able to shore up their economies and provide
expanded markets for U.S. exporters.
   He noted Mexico is the first of those nations to work out
agreements on handling its huge foreign debt and, under the
nation's new leadership, has reduced its inflation rate below 20
percent.
   Responding to skepticism from several Democratic committee
members about the merits of the so-called Brady plan for Third
World debt relief, Mosbacher said: ``I agree the ... plan will not
work by itself, but it's part of the puzzle.''
   Continuing his focus on Mexico as an early barometer for overall
administration policy, Mosbacher said that country's ability to
reduce some of its big interest payments has freed money for
investment.
   Mosbacher said a key to developing export markets in Latin
American countries will be for U.S. businesses to take a long view
of their investments rather than short-term profits.
</TEXT>
