<FIRST>r a AM-StamfordMural     10-18 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stamford Mural,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules City of Stamford True Owner of Depression-Era Mural</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An art restorer has no claim of ownership of a
Depression-era mural that the city of Stamford, Conn., mistakenly
threw in the garbage in 1970, a judge ruled.
   The 8-by-100-foot mural, painted in 1934 by artist James
Daughtery as part of the federal Works Progress Administration, has
been appraised at $1.25 million by Sotheby's.
   The discarded mural was obtained by an official of the federal
General Services Administration who oversaw the restoration of WPA
artwork, and sent to restorer Hiram H. Hoelzer to keep until
federal funding was found to restore it, according to court records.
   In 1986, when the city planned to apply for its own grant for
restoration, Hoelzer claimed the city had given up its rights to
the mural, and he claimed ownership.
   U.S. District Judge Louis Stanton ruled Tuesday that ``it was
reasonable for city officials to believe that, as long as Mr.
Hoelzer did not assert ownership of the mural, he continued to
possess it as a custodian or bailee,'' a person who holds something
temporarily in trust.
</TEXT>
