<FIRST>r a AM-SwaggartSued     10-18 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swaggart Sued,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honduran Network Sues Swaggart Ministries Over Broadcast Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Honduran television network has sued
Jimmy Swaggart Ministries for nearly $14,000 in fees and interest
for broadcasting programs, but an attorney for Swaggart said the
organization is paid up.
   The Corporacion Centroamericana de Comunicaciones, which
operates under the name VICA TV, claims the ministry and its
broadcast affiliate owe $13,700 from a $111,600 contract executed
two years ago.
   The Swaggart ministries and Swaggart Television and Radio
Communications, or Starcom, owe $6,100 in principal and $7,600 in
interest, according to a lawsuit filed earlier this month in
Judicial District Court.
   But Emile Weber, an attorney for Swaggart, said Wednesday, ``We
paid them all we owe. ...I have the canceled check for $6,100 right
here.'' He thought the lawsuit stemmed from a breakdown in
communications.
   The lawsuit states that VICA TV agreed to broadcast Swaggart's
shows between Nov. 1, 1987 and Nov. 30, 1988 over three channels:
Channel 2 in San Pedro Sula, Channel 13 in Comayagua and Channel 9,
serving LaCeiba and the Honduran capital of Tegucigalpa.
   ``Defendants have paid some of the monies owed,'' the suit said,
but a balance of $6,100 remains payable.
   It seeks interest because of the alleged failure to make proper
monthly payments, as well as legal interest, attorney's fees and
court costs.
</TEXT>
