<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Quake 8thLd-Writethru a0680 10-18 0949</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Quake, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0680,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Disaster-Relief Declaration for Earthquake Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs 2nd graf, White House, with 3 grafs on Bush trip; deletes
pvs 9th graf, The president, now redundant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today signed a disaster-relief
declaration for the earthquake-ravaged San Francisco Bay area and
said ``we will take every step and make every effort'' to help spur
recovery from the devastation.
   Bush said he probably will fly to the area for a personal
inspection but left open when that might happen. ``I don't want to
get in the way,'' he said, adding that ``the last thing we want to
do is clutter things up.''
   His press secretary, Marlin Fitzwater, said later that the trip
``won't be for a few days,'' but an official said it could be
Saturday.
   Fitzwater said there is $273 million in unallocated funds from a
$1.1 billion appropriation for the Hurricane Hugo cleanup ``which
can be used for immediate assistance in San Francisco.''
   ``That obviously means that we won't have enough for all of the
emergencies that are now facing us, and we will have to consider
appropriate requests for follow-on funding,'' said the presidential
spokesman.
   Fitzwater said the earthquake relief would cost ``more'' than
the $1.1 billion Hugo cleanup, but he declined to estimate how much.
   Numerous world leaders have sent Bush messages of sympathy and
offers of support, including Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev,
who received U.S. help after last December's devastating earthquake
in Armenia.
   ``If these countries can help, we certainly welcome their
assistance,'' said Fitzwater.
   Bush announced his action during a morning meeting with
Republican congressional leaders.
   ``As daylight breaks there in California, I want the citizens of
the San Francisco Bay area and its neighbors first to know that our
hearts are with them as they face this terrible tragedy,'' the
president said. ``Words can't adequately convey our sadness.''
   Bush said ``we will take every step and make every effort to
help the bay area in its hour of need.''
   He said he received an update by telephone from Vice President
Dan Quayle, who was preparing to take a helicopter tour of the
ravaged area.
   Asked about the extent of the damage, Bush said the death toll
``seems to be mounting and we are concerned. But it's hard to put a
total number on it at this point. I've seen none.'' Authorities in
California say more than 270 people were killed and hundreds were
injured.
   ``We're working with state and local officials to assure the
relief effort is coordinated and effective as possible,'' Bush said.
   He praised the efforts of private relief agencies such as the
Red Cross and called on Americans to support those organizations.
   The disaster-relief declaration will authorize use of federal
funds in the recovery effort. Bush said his chief of staff, John
Sununu, was trying to ensure that the relief effort is
``coordinated and effective as possible.''
   He said the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA), which
was criticized for its response to Hurricane Hugo, ``is doing a
good job. They're out front and they're trying to respond.''
   Later, Bush left the White House to tour FEMA's Emergency
Information and Coordination Center and defended the agency. ``I
hope there will be less carping ... I think they took a hit on the
other one (Hurricane Hugo),'' he said.
   In an operations room, Bush talked by telephone with Jeff Rubin,
director of California's Emergency Medical Services, who had just
called federal officials.
   ``Jeff, this is the president. How's it doing out there? Are you
getting a lot of requests for emergency medical service?'' Bush
said.
   He ended the conversation saying, ``Well, that's good.'' Bush
then told aides, ``He says, `Not so many requests'.''
   Bush's declaration said a major disaster exists in a
seven-county area in Northern California. The federal government
normally pays at least 75 percent of the cost of rebuilding bridges
and other public facilities that are destroyed, and provides
low-cost loans for individuals and businesses.
   The areas covered by Bush's order include the city and county of
San Francisco and the counties of Alameda, Monterey, San Benito,
San Mateo, Santa Clara and Santa Cruz.
   FEMA said damage surveys are continuing in other areas and
additional counties may be added later.
   Bush met during the morning with a group of elementary school
principals and singled out Ray E. Tolcacher, superintendent of the
Windsor School District in the bay area. ``We just hope that your
kids and your schools and all the families are safe and sound,''
Bush said.
   He said the damage was ``a matter of grave national concern.''
   Within a few hours of the quake, the bureaucracy was in motion,
from Bush's decision to send Transportation Secretary Sam Skinner
flying overnight to California to the establishment of a command
center at the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) a few
blocks from the White House.
   The administration, which was criticized for its response to
Hurricane Hugo, made a determined effort to demonstrate that the
government was moving quickly now.
   Fitzwater, during an early-morning appearance at FEMA, said,
``At the moment, it is very reassuring to see that the
response-organization at the local, state and federal (levels) is
performing so well. People in San Francisco are responding in
heroic fashion in many cases.
   ``People are staying calm but it looks like, in this major
disaster, that the people and organizations involved are performing
with distinction,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``Obviously, we've already started moving,'' said FEMA's Grant
Peterson. ``We're not waiting to respond, we're responding right
now,'' he added as the agency strove to avoid the criticism it
reaped for its response to Hurricane Hugo last month.
</TEXT>
