<FIRST>r w AM-US-EastGermany     10-18 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-East Germany,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Hopes for Better Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush held out the prospect of
improved relations with East Germany on Wednesday but suggested it
was ``way too early to say'' whether Wednesday's power shuffle
could pave the way.
   U.S. officials reacted to the ouster of longtime Communist Party
Leader Erich Honecker by challenging his successor _ Politburo
member Egon Krenz _ to embrace reforms sweeping other Eastern bloc
nations.
   ``The United States is prepared to develop stronger and more
constructive relations with the German Democratic Republic (East
Germany),'' said presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   ``It is up to the new leadership there to demonstrate through
its deeds that it's ready to move in that direction,'' the
spokesman said.
   Still, Bush himself voiced skepticism over the prospects of any
major policy turnabouts as a result of Wednesday's upheaval.
   ``There's dynamic change taking place in Eastern Europe and now,
it appears, in (East Germany). But whether this step is a step
toward more openness or not, I think it's way too early to say,''
the president said.
   ``There's nothing in the record to indicate that it is,'' he
added.
   Speaking with reporters during a picture-taking session with
Republican leaders, Bush said Krenz had been ``very much in
accord'' with the hardline policies of Honecker, who was stripped
of power after 18 years of rule.
   Honecker, 77, was removed as party leaders met to discuss the
flight of East Germans to the West and growing pro-democracy
protests. He was replaced by the younger Krenz, 52, who had been in
charge of security issues and government-run youth groups.
   Whether the selection of a new party chief ``reflects a change
in East-West relations, I don't think so. I don't think it does,''
Bush said.
   Fitzwater called Honecker's removal by communist party leaders
``obviously a response to the mass exodus of tens of thousands'' of
East Germans ``who have sought freedom and a better life in the
West.''
   ``We hope thus change signals movement (by East Germany) toward
reforms and repsonds to the hopes and aspirations of its people,''
Fitzwater said.
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the
United States will be watching to see if the new East German
leadership is ``prepared to bring perestroika to East Germany.''
</TEXT>
