<SECOND>AM-Voodoo Abuse,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grandmother Accused in Voodoo Weekend</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who chased her teen-age daughter
from their home in a dispute over voodoo power has been arrested
after the teen-ager's severely battered baby was thrown from a
window.
   The 8{-month-old baby, who suffered tears in her vagina, burns
on her arms and buttocks and bruises and abrasions all over her
body, was reported in stable condition at the University of
Mississippi Medical Center.
   Lou Vera Denson, a former city employee, was booked Monday on a
felony child abuse charge.
   When officers arrested her, she ``was telling us she was a
devil,'' said police Sgt. Keith Burton.
   Burton said Denson threatened officers, telling them: ``I'll put
a curse on you.''
   The baby's 17-year-old mother, not identified because of her
age, told authorities that Denson made her leave home about a week
earlier.
   ``This grandmother claimed that the (child's) mother had more
power by looking at you and she couldn't stand it and made her
leave,'' said police Capt. Larry Wallace.
   Neighbor Robert Porter said he saw Denson mix some sort of
chemical and ``sprinkle it around the house and doors'' over the
weekend, and smear it on another daughter, Judy Marie Denson, 22,
who lives with her.
   At one point, Porter said, he saw the elder Denson sitting
outside holding a butcher knife.
   Officers went to the home Friday to investigate a disturbance,
but left after being told the baby was all right, police said
Tuesday.
   Police returned Monday when a neighbor reported a child had been
thrown from the house.
   Inside, police said, windows were broken and furniture was
smashed. Food and debris covered the floor. Telephones had been
ripped out and thrown outside. Pages were torn from a Bible and
scattered inside the house.
   ``Every faucet in the house was running,'' said Burton. ``There
was such a stench of Clorox and ammonia that you could not breath
for any length of time.''
   Denson also was charged with abusive language and assault on a
police officer, as was Judy Marie. The Densons remained jailed
without bond Wednesday.
   Denson's brother, John Hicks, said Tuesday that his sister was
mentally ill and had been hospitalized at least once.
   ``A year ago she had a breakdown,'' Hicks said. ``My sister's
very nice. Nobody would ever think she would do anything like this.
But she's sick. She's just really sick.''
</TEXT>
