<FIRST>r a AM-RestrictionLifted     10-18 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Restriction Lifted,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Officer in Spy Investigation No Longer Restricted to Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force officer whose activities in West
Berlin are under investigation because of espionage allegations has
been released from restriction to Kelly Air Force Base, authorities
said.
   Capt. John Vladimir Hirsch, 34, an electronic security officer,
has been at Kelly since Aug. 30 after he was taken into custody by
the Air Force Office of Special Investigations. Since arriving at
the base he has been accompanied everywhere by an escort.
   A search of his West Berlin apartment turned up records of
$120,000 in bank accounts, photographs of NATO military
installations and classified documents.
   Hirsch has not been charged with any crime, but he has been
under suspicion of selling secrets to the Soviet bloc.
   He was released from restriction to base Tuesday because
military law limits the amount of time someone can be restricted
without charges being filed, said Lt. Col. John Worthington, a
spokesman for the Electronic Security Command headquartered at
Kelly.
   Hirsch does not have to stay on the base but must tell his
commander if he plans to leave San Antonio, and his top-secret
security clearance remains revoked, officials said.
   The investigation began in July when polygraph examiners decided
Hirsch was not telling the truth during a routine security update.
   He had been assigned to West Berlin at a communications unit
belonging to the secretive Electronic Security Command, which
collects intelligence on Warsaw Pact radar and communications.
   His current duties as an electronic engineer do not involve
classified projects, Worthington said.
   Hirsch, 33, was born in Prague, Czechoslovakia, and became a
U.S. citizen in 1971. He has been in the Air Force since 1979.
</TEXT>
