<FIRST>r w AM-US-Extradition     10-18 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Extradition,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Accused as Nazi Criminal Arrested in California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal marshals have arrested a California
man sought by West Germany on charges he murdered prisoners while a
Nazi concentration camp guard during World War II, the Justice
Department announced Wednesday.
   Bruno Karl Blach, 69, was arrested Tuesday night at his home in
La Habra, Calif., based on a warrant issued by a court in Duisburg,
West Germany last June, the department said.
   Blach is charged with killing three prisoners being transported
from the Wiener Neudorf concentration camp to the Mauthausen death
camp in Austria between April 2 and 14, 1945, the department said.
   If extradited, Blach would become only the fourth American ever
extradited for Nazi war crimes.
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service already has ordered
Blach's deportation to West Germany, after finding that he
participated in Nazi persecution. He is currently appealing the
April 1987 ruling, as well as the German extradition warrant.
   Blach was denied bail at a bond hearing in Los Angeles on
Wednesday, but he will get a chance to challenge the extradition at
another hearing Monday in U.S. District Court there, officials
said. The Justice Department will represent West Germany's claim.
   ``We are very encouraged by West Germany having taken this case
very seriously in fulfilling its responsibilities of prosecuting
Nazi crimes,'' said Neal Sher, who heads the department's Office of
Special Investigations.
   The U.S. Immigration Court found in 1987 that Blach, who
immigrated here in 1956 from Austria, served as a guard and
dog-handler at the Dachau concentration camp in Germany from 1940
to 1943, and later at the Wiener Neudorf camp in Austria.
   The court also found that in April 1945, Blach took part in the
forced evacuation by foot of prisoners to Mauthausen, during which
he shot to death at least one person _ an elderly, disabled Jewish
inmate, the Justice Department said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
