<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle-Baker     10-18 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle-Baker,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Denies Rift on U.S. Policy Toward Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House on Wednesday denied any
internal rift on U.S. policy toward the Soviets despite seemingly
divergent tones in recent comments by Secretary of State James A.
Baker III and Vice President Dan Quayle.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater acknowledged,
however, that ``We sing from the same song sheet, but there are
several verses.''
   While Quayle appeared to hew to a harder line, citing the
``potential source of serious problems in Soviet-American
relations,'' Baker, in a Monday speech, seemed to take a more open
and expansive approach. He said, ``The prospects for a lasting
improvement in U.S.-Soviet relations are better than ever before.''
   Baker announced that the United States stands ready to give the
Soviets technical assistance to help ``in certain areas of Soviet
economic reform.''
   The Washington Times quoted Quayle as telling reporters Tuesday
in San Francisco, ``Let them reform themselves,'' meaning the
Soviets.
   Quayle spoke later Tuesday in Los Angeles to a Town Hall of
California meeting, a day after Baker spoke in New York to the
Foreign Policy Association.
   Asked if their comments indicated a rift within the
administration over how to deal with the Soviets, Fitzwater said,
``There are no differences ... between Vice President Quayle and
Secretary Baker on U.S.-Soviet relations.
   ``We all agree that glastnost and perestroika are encouraging
trends that America supports. It is in the western interest for
these reforms to succeed. We offer democracy as an example to the
world and we have continually said the Soviets must solve their
internal structural problems themselves but we are always ready to
provide advice and counsel.''
   Baker's comments appeared to indicate a more open-arms approach
for the Bush administration in the face of criticism from some
quarters that it has been too reticent to take advantage of the
opportunities to urge on reform movements in the East Bloc
governments.
   He did, however, mix praise with criticism, stating that the
Soviets were reluctant to withdraw from regional conflicts.
   Quayle did not mention offers of technical assistance in his
speech on Tuesday.
   He also mentioned Soviet involvement in regional conflicts _ in
Nicaragua, North Korea, Afghanistan and Cambodia _ that have been a
sore spot for the United States, and said they showed the ``darker
side of Soviet foreign policy.
</TEXT>
