<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1709EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SFQuake-PrivateRelief     10-18 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Private Relief,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Private Agencies First on Scene with Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Salvation Army had the food cooking almost
before the earth quit shaking in Northern California. Nearly as
quickly, the Red Cross opened the doors and unfolded cots in 25
shelters. The federal government called a meeting.
   Once again, the nation's volunteer agencies were the quickest to
assist local authorities when disaster struck, even as the White
House and other federal institutions, stung by complaints of a
sorry, tardy effort in the wake of Hurricane Hugo, burned the
midnight oil this time.
   Hugo's devastation last month in Puerto Rico, the Virgin Islands
and the Carolinas extended into the treasuries of the private
relief agencies. Even so, they were ready for the San Francisco
shaker.
   The Red Cross, the Salvation Army, church groups and other
organizations like REACT, the citizens-band radio volunteers, all
work with the Federal Emergency Management Agency as well as local
officials in planning for disasters. But none awaits orders from
the Washington bureaucracy, which still took hours getting into
gear.
   ``We don't wait for anybody,'' said Col. Leon Ferraez,
communications director of the Salvation Army. ``We're there the
minute the news is on.''
   According to Ferraez, the Salvation Army had 12 mobile canteens
on their way to the hardest-hit earthquake areas within minutes.
All Salvation Army facilities in the bay area, including 34
community service centers and scores of other units, have been
turned over to the relief effort. Thousands of meals had been
served and hundreds, if not thousands, housed in those facilities
by noon Wednesday, Ferraez said.
   In the first hours, the canteens provided beverages, sandwiches
and donuts to victims of the quake as well as police, firefighters
and volunteer relief workers. Longer term services range from
providing housing and clothing to counseling. ``If somebody just
needs to talk, we're prepared to do that,'' Ferraez added.
   Nationwide, the Salvation Army relies upon 1.2 million
volunteers, as measured against just 5,000 paid workers _ low pay
at that. The organization has long had the reputation of directing
the most of every donated dollar into services, as opposed to
administrative and fund-raising costs.
   The Red Cross mobilized hundreds of disaster workers and opened
25 shelters when the quake struck. Distribution centers in Los
Angeles, Sacramento and Portland, Ore., began shipping cots,
blankets, and other supplies by Wednesday morning.
   In San Francisco, a downtown convention center housed more than
1,000 evacuees under Red Cross auspices. More than 500 residents of
the fire-ravaged Marina area took refuge in a local middle school.
   The Red Cross also transformed an airport terminal into a
shelter, and three nearby hotels, the Sheraton, Ramada and Embassy
Suites, turned over their lodgings to the agency. Other Red Cross
shelters included one at San Andreas High School, bearing the name
of the fault which triggered the calamity.
   The Red Cross began its fiscal year July 1 with $18.5 million in
its disaster budget, and had spent 40 percent by September, mostly
on flood relief in Texas. Then Hugo came along, triggering an
effort the agency estimates will cost $42 million _ the most ever.
   ``When a major earthquake and a major hurricane hit
back-to-back, you can bet it will stretch Red Cross disaster
resources and manpower,'' said Bob Vessey, director of disaster
services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1556EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Timeline Bjt   10-18 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Timeline, Bjt,0891</SECOND>
<HEAD>What They Were Doing When The Quake Hit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY RYCKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Susie Allen was fighting rush-hour traffic on her way home
across the San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge, Kim House was walking
with her fiance and Bob Witzgall was taking a shower in his hotel
room. Then it hit.
   Northern California's earthquake at 5:04 p.m. Tuesday turned a
routine rush hour into tragedy, sent frightened tourists and
natives rushing into the streets and left victims and heroes.
   At 3 p.m., thousands of baseball fans began streaming into
Candlestick Park for Game No. 3 of the World Series, scheduled to
begin 2{ hours later. The first pitch was never thrown.
   Ms. Allen was amid heavy traffic heading out of San Francisco on
the lower tier of the Bay Bridge when the span began to ripple and
sway.
   ``First I thought my shocks weren't working,'' she said. ``Then
I realized the car wasn't having problems; the ground was having
problems.
   ``The road rose up to meet me,'' said Ms. Allen, who was heading
from her office in San Francisco to her home in Oakland. ``I
couldn't figure out why the road was at a 50-degree angle to my
face.''
   Ms. Allen, 26, stopped her car, locked it, and joined other
motorists walking toward a 30-foot gap created when a piece of the
upper deck collapsed onto the lower level.
   Thomas and Debby Kelly, a vacationing couple from Ringwood,
Okla., were on the upper level and took home video pictures,
acquired by ABC station KGO-TV. Their shots included one of a small
car that tumbled nose first over the gap.
   ``Ohhh, gosh! That could have been us....'' Mrs. Kelly gasped as
the red car fell to the bridge's lower level. Then, to her husband,
she said, ``Thomas, we need to get down there and help!''
   Cathy Miranker was driving north on an elevated section of
Highway 101 to her home in San Francisco.
   ``It was like bumper cars,'' she said. ``It literally started to
buckle bend and bounce. Cars were bounced into the air on the
roadway. Cars tried to stop but the motion kept them running even
if you slammed on the brakes.''
   Cars slammed into each other and into guardrails and stopped.
One woman rolled down her window and asked if she had car problems.
   ``I said, `No, it's not your car, it's an earthquake.'''
   Across the bay in Oakland, George Donovan was driving his
tractor-trailer rig on the upper deck of Interstate 880, the Nimitz
Freeway.
   ``The pavement started to move. I had waves of asphalt come up
over my windshield,'' he said. ``It was undulating all around me.
It was like a Disney ride.''
   A mile-long stretch of the highway's upper level collapsed onto
the lower deck, crushing more than 250 people, authorities
estimated. Motorists and passers-by rushed to help those trapped.
   Ms. House, of San Jose, was walking in San Francisco's
Tenderloin district with her fiance.
   ``We heard an explosion and it turned out to be concrete from
the walls and windows blowing out,'' she said. ``People were
running out of the buildings.''
   At the same time, a transient lay on his bed in a hotel for the
homeless.
   ``The bed moved from one side (of the room) to the other,''
Douglas Schmillen said. ``I didn't know if the walls were going to
come down next.''
   Witzgall, a conventioneer from Sacramento, was showering in his
Union Square hotel room.
   ``It was scary. I couldn't get out of there fast enough,'' he
said. ``It started out as a little rumble, but it was pretty
violent where I was.''
   Dick Moore, news director of WSOC-TV in Charlotte, N.C., was in
a third-floor office in San Francisco.
   ``The first thing I saw really was someone who knew what was
going on standing in a doorway bracing themself under a doorway,''
Moore said. ``We went out on the street and saw a lot of people
pouring out into the streets, looking up at the buildings to see
any signs of physical damage.''
   People throughout the city gathered outside after the quake.
Some congratulated each other over surviving and other talked about
what they were doing when the earthquake struck.
   ``I'm religious,'' Roland Hidalgo said, standing in a parking
lot off Market Street. ``I prayed.''
   At Candlestick Park, 60,000 baseball fans had been waiting for
the game to begin. Members of the Oakland Athletics and the San
Francisco Giants warmed up on the field.
   Umpire Al Clark was in the dressing room.
   ``As soon as it started, my legs went numb,'' he said. ``I
looked up, and the walls were waving. I became frightened, and I
realized it was an earthquake.''
   Some fans cheered as the stadium's concrete overhang rippled
ominously; other sat shaken and cried. All were sent home and the
game was canceled.
   The Gatlin Brothers, the country group scheduled to sing ``The
Star-Spangled Banner,'' thought fans were stomping until they saw
the stadium sway.
   ``The ground was moving and all three of us began praying,''
said Larry Gatlin, according to group spokeswoman Kathy Gangwisch.
``It was one of the scariest moments of my lifetime.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
