<DOCNO> AP891018-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1557EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Savimbi-Cease-Fire     10-18 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savimbi-Cease-Fire,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Leader Optimistic on Cease-Fire Prospects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebel leader Jonas Savimbi said Wednesday he
is optimistic that a cease-fire agreement with Angola's Marxist
government can be revived before the end of the month.
   Savimbi, speaking in a telephone interview with The Associated
Press from the Ivory Coast, also said there was a good possibility
for a mutual release of war prisoners with the government.
   The Angolan peace process had been stalled following what
appeared to be a breakthrough last June between Savimbi's UNITA
rebel, who receive U.S. backing, and the Soviet-supported
government. Among other measures, the two sides reached agreement
on a cease-fire to end their 14-year conflict.
   But fighting resumed within weeks, and Savimbi felt that the
chief peace mediator, President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire, was
taking sides with the MPLA government. There also were
recriminations about whether Savimbi had agreed to go into exile
and to integrate his forces into the Angolan army.
   Savimbi patched up his differences with Mobutu during weekend
meetings in Paris following discussions in Washington, and he
sounded more upbeat Wednesday than he has at any time since the
breakthrough in June.
   He said he was optimistic the cease-fire could be back on track
``during this month of October.'' He raised the possibility that
some African nations might contribute troops to monitor the
cease-fire if it is revived.
   But even if a truce is agreed to, the MPLA and UNITA face the
challenging task of reaching a political settlement. With U.S.
support, UNITA is calling for free and fair elections to be a key
ingredient of the peace process.
   The Angolan government has a much narrower view of national
reconciliation, insisting that the existing constitution remain
unchanged.
   But Savimbi said recent statements by senior Angolan officials
suggest a more flexible attitude on reconciliation.
   They are ``not so intransigent'' as they were before, said
Savimbi, who stopped off in the Ivory Coast while en route to his
home base in rebel-held southeast Angola.
   Savimbi said there are between 3,000 and 5,000 MPLA prisoners in
UNITA hands. He said the government has refused to disclose the
number of rebel prisoners it holds.
   The United States provides about $40 million to UNITA, and Bush
administration officials were angry when Savimbi declined to attend
talks last month designed to reinstate the cease-fire.
   Savimbi agreed to resume his role in the peace process after
talks with President Bush on Oct. 5 in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
