<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Yeltsin     10-18 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Yeltsin,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Claims Gorbachev Directed Effort to Oust Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris N. Yeltsin, the Communist Party's traveling
maverick, accused President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Wednesday of
directing a campaign of ``provocative, tendentious, lying
statements'' to drive him out of politics.
   In the past month, Yeltsin has been accused in print and on
television of turning a U.S. speaking tour into a drinking and
spending spree and of showing up at a police station late at night,
dripping wet, with an elaborate and false tale of an attempt to
drown him.
   Yeltsin once was Gorbachev's man at the helm of the Moscow
Communist Party, but he was fired from there and the ruling
Politburo in 1987 after demanding faster reform and saying a
personality cult could develop around his mentor.
   He made a unique political comeback by winning 89 percent of the
vote to represent Moscow in the Congress of People's Deputies.
   A statement signed by Yeltsin and distributed Wednesday by his
aides said of Gorbachev: ``At his command, a whole series of
provocative, tendentious, lying statements have been published in
the Soviet press and broadcast on television.''
   In May, Yeltsin said he spoke with Gorbachev often by telephone.
At a closed party meeting Friday, Gorbachev accused Yeltsin and
several other legislators who favor rapid change of forming ``a
fascist clique striving for power,'' said editors who attended.
   Yeltsin's statement Wednesday accused Gorbachev of a ``political
farce ... a new attempt to ruin my health and to knock me out of
the sphere of political struggle.''
   ``I consider it unacceptable and dangerous to shift from
political struggle to immoral and unscrupulous methods of moral and
psychological elimination of opponents,'' the statement said.
   ``This will result in a complete breakup of moral and ethical
principles, curtailment of democratic principles of perestroika and
finally to establishment of a cruel totalitarian regime.''
   It cited Monday's report in the Supreme Soviet legislature,
broadcast on television, of a police investigation of an alleged
attack on Yeltsin's life.
   Interior Minister Vadim Bakatin told the deputies Yeltsin
appeared at the police station late the night of Sept. 28 and said
unidentified men had assaulted him and thrown him off a bridge into
the Moscow River.
   Bakatin said Yeltsin then asked officers to tell no one about
the incident, but that they were duty-bound to report it,
``especially since they had a waterlogged man'' as evidence.
   An investigation determined Yeltsin could not have fallen 50
feet into shallow water without injury, Bakatin said, and Yeltsin
said Sept. 30 that no attack occurred.
   In the Supreme Soviet, the working legislature within the
Congress of People's Deputies, Yeltsin said he had not filed a
written complaint and there had been no attempt on his life. He did
not address whether he had appeared at a police post soaking wet.
   Gorbachev summed up the discussion by saying Yeltsin told the
Supreme Soviet Presidium he had been joking and the police
misunderstood him.
   Adding to the mystery is the fact that Yeltsin disappeared from
both legislative and public view for two weeks. He reappeared at a
rally Sunday and said he had been suffering from a cold.
</TEXT>
