<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Predictions     10-18 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Predictions,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quakes: Scientists Can Say Where But Not When</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RESTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The science of predicting earthquakes is
still largely an exercise in probabilities, with little warning
possible when disaster is actually about to strike.
   ``It's difficult to make short-term predictions,'' said Robert
Wesson, chief of the Office of Earthquakes, Volcanoes and
Engineering at the U.S. Geological Survey, when asked if there were
warning signs of Tuesday's disastrous earthquake in Northern
California.
   ``I would say there was a successful long-term prediction,'' he
said, pointing out that a USGS report last year listed the region
as a likely site for a major tremor. ``Unfortunately we didn't have
any warning of this earthquake last night.''
   Sometimes smaller shocks foreshadow a major quake, and that may
have happened in this case too _ although too far removed to make
any short-term prediction. A quake estimated at 5.1 on the Richter
scale occurred on June 27, 1988, and another rated at 5.2 struck on
Aug. 8 of this year.
   Those events prompted the agency to pay increased attention to
the Loma Prieta region and notify California officials. But little
could be done beyond that because there was no way to tell if the
tremors were foreshocks or just individual quakes on their own.
   Using historical records, measurements of ground motion and
other analyses, scientists are able to single out places where they
believe tremors will strike.
   Such predictions ``are not useful in evacuating dangerous
buildings, but they are useful in land use planning and resource
allocation in anticipation of future events,'' said Wesson.
   In addition to the region that was struck on Tuesday, the nearby
Hayward fault has been identified as a likely site for a serious
quake and an even stronger tremor seems probable for the Southern
California portion of the San Andreas Fault, the same one that
moved this time.
   Whether this quake will trigger other major ones remains to be
seen, however.
   Dave Russ, assistant chief geologist at the Survey, explained
that quakes occurring along faults in the earth release stress that
builds up over time. When this movement releases stress in one area
the strain can be increased elsewhere.
   In California the San Andreas fault is the major problem region,
marking the spot where two of the giant plates that make up the
Earth's crust are moving alongside one another.
   Several miles below the surface the pressure and heat make the
rocks like plastic and they can slip past one another, Russ
explained. But the cooler surface rocks grind and lock together.
   Over time strain builds up until the surface rocks slip in an
earthquake, moving to catch up with the deep layers below, Russ
said.
   Such a movement always triggers thousands of smaller aftershocks
as the many rocks along the fault line adjust themselves, and there
remains the chance of strong aftershocks, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
