<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-EC     10-18 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-EC,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Envoy Calls For Lifting of High-Tech Import Barriers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West's efforts to withhold
sensitive technology from the Soviet Union have hurt the country's
economy, the Soviet ambassador to the European Community said
Wednesday.
   Vladimir Shemiatenkov, the Kremlin's first ambassador to the
trading bloc, said the Western panel that screens high-tech sales
to the Soviet Union is ``obsolete nowadays, it is very clear.''
   Shemiatenkov said the restrictions hinder the Soviet Union's
efforts to reach a trade agreement with the 12-nation European
Economic Community.
   The United States and 15 of its allies belong to the
Coordinating Committee on Multilateral Export Controls, which
controls products that could contribute to the military might of
the West's adversaries.
   Some Western nations believe the restrictions should be eased
with the warming of relations between East and West.
   Shemiatenkov said the high-tech restrictions have not
``prevented us from developing advanced military techniques, but in
order to achieve that level we had to allocate much greater
resources (to defense) than otherwise.
   ``But at the same time, it was a very powerful factor in
disfiguring our internal development and I think in constraining
the development of international trade,'' he said.
   Because of the barriers, he said, some Western companies have
been unable to sell telecommunications equipment to the Soviet
Union to help improve the ``exceptionally weak'' phone system.
   However, Shemiatenkov said Moscow was ``very satisfied with
progress'' overall in negotiating the trade agreement with the
European trading bloc.
   The accord would be the fourth between the community and an East
bloc country since a thaw in relations a little more than a year
ago. The trading bloc recently signed a pact with Poland after
earlier arrangements with Hungary and Czechoslovakia.
   ``For many years, we have more or less underestimated the impact
of the West European integration,'' said Shemiatenkov.
   Community officials have suggested the negotiations with Moscow
could be wrapped up by year's end but Shemiatenkov would not make a
prediction.
   He confirmed the sides were at odds over the community's
insistence on considering the Soviet Union a state trading country
rather than a market. The European Community is able to impose
price restrictions on imports of state trading countries.
   Shemiatenkov said the description was a ``major problem (for)
our integration to the world economy.'' He said it could require
the government to set export prices at artificially low levels so
they would not create disadvantages for other community trading
partners.
   ``The situation with the Soviet Union today is such that the
government does not ... control prices in (foreign) transactions,''
he said.
   To do so now, officials would have to ``reverse the situation
(and) reinstitute the government control over prices,'' he said.
   ``This is outright fantasy ... It would be contrary to the very
spirit of our reform because we want to have decentralization,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
