<FIRST>r w AM-Quake-Military     10-18 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quake-Military,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Joining Quake Aid Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two hundred Navy Seabees equipped with
backhoes, trench diggers and water storage equipment headed for the
San Francisco area on Wednesday to aid in the quake-relief effort,
as military hospitals in the afflicted region opened their doors to
help wounded civilians, officials said.
   ``The Seabees' specialty is disaster recovery and they will
focus on making repairs to water and sewage lines,'' said Connie
Taylor, a public affairs officer at the Naval Construction Training
Center in Port Hueneme, Calif.
   Other heavy-lift equipment from the Naval Air Station Alemeda
was sent to help recovery efforts at the nearby freeway collapse,
officials said.
   In Washington, Pentagon officials reported that damage at other
military facilities around the San Francisco bay area was
``comparatively minor,'' and consisted primarily of power outages,
broken gas and water lines, and some structural damage to buildings.
   No deaths of military personnel had been reported and injuries
were ``relatively few and minor,'' a statement said.
   In response to a request from the Federal Emergency Management
Agency, a C-141 transport plane was set to carry some 27,000 pounds
of FEMA equipment and 12 FEMA employees to San Francisco, the
statement added.
   Maj. Gen. Todd P. Graham, the deputy commanding general of the
6th Army headquarters at the Presidio in San Francisco, was named
the disaster control officer on the scene, the Pentagon said.
   Injured quake victims were being treated at the Letterman Army
Medical Center in San Francisco and at the Naval Hospital in
Oakland, where 100 beds were made available. Fort Ord, near
Monterey, was providing blood, the Pentagon said.
   Navy medical spokesman Lt. Dallas Swenson said 12 civilians had
been admitted to the hospital in Oakland and two of them had
arrived in serious condition.
   The 304th Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Squadron from Portland,
Ore., sent 21 para-rescue jumpers, two physicians, two rescue
helicopters and a communications van to the quake area aboard a
HC-130 transport plane, the Pentagon said.
   About 20 military police from the Army base at the Presidio,
located near the Golden Gate bridge, were helping local police
control traffic.
   The Navy said a pier buckled at the Naval Air Station in
Alemeda, causing two minor injuries.
</TEXT>
