<HEAD>Alcoa Chairman to Head Advisory Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Wednesday named the chairman
of the Aluminum Company of America, Paul O'Neill, to head a newly
created committee that will advise him on education policy.
   The Education Policy Advisory Committee, which has no other
members yet, will advise the president on the objectives and
content of education policy and recommend ways that federal and
local governments, as well as the private sector, can improve
education.
   The committee, as announced by Bush earlier this year, will have
from 12 to 20 members.
   Bush said he chose O'Neill as chairman of the education panel
because ``he is deeply concerned about helping to bring quality
education to all Americans.'' He mentioned a program at Alcoa to
help improve the literacy of its employees.
   Bush made the announcement in remarks to the National
Association of Elementary School Principals.
