<FIRST>u a AM-Floods-Rescue Bjt   10-18 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Floods-Rescue, Bjt,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Coal Miners Rescue Replacement Workers from Floodwaters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEHUE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking United Mine Workers set aside 2{
months of hostility to rescue three non-union coal company workers
whose van slid down a hillside into a flooding creek, state police
said Wednesday.
   ``We really hate these guys, but we couldn't let them die,''
striking miner James Justice said Wednesday. ``We don't like them.
We don't want to kill them, though.''
   Three men who went to work in August for Con-Serv Inc., a
non-union company hired by A.T. Massey Coal Co. to operate its Rum
Creek Coal Sales tipple, where coal is loaded into trucks, were
headed home after Tuesday's day shift.
   High water from Rum Creek blocked the normal road leading away
from the Logan County operation, and they got stuck.
   Another Con-Serv employee in a four-wheel-drive truck hooked a
chain to the van to pull it loose and was towing it along an
alternate exit road leading up a steep hillside when the van
lurched sideways and fell 75 feet into Rum Creek.
   ``The water probably cushioned their fall,'' Justice said.
   Witnesses said about eight UMW men who also were blocked by the
high water were following the truck and van up the hill when the
accident occurred. All jumped out of their cars and helped the
three escape from the rising water.
   One of the workers, Rodney Walker of Cincinnati, was trapped
with his foot pinned in the van, said state police Trooper Ric
Robinson.
   The UMW men held Walker's head above the rising water while
waiting for emergency workers to arrive, said state police Sgt.
G.A. Ables.
   ``Without a doubt, had they not helped, he'd have died,'' Ables
said. ``He could not have extricated himself from that vehicle
himself.''
   Justice is a Pittston Coal Group employee who has been on strike
since April. He and others throughout southern West Virginia and
Kentucky have picketed Pittston and other non-union operations
since.
   ``We don't want to see anyone killed over this,'' he said. ``We
don't want nobody hurt. We just don't want anybody taking our
jobs.''
   Walker and the other workers, plus one of the UMW men, were
treated at Man Appalachian Regional Hospital for cuts and bruises
and released, Robinson said.
   ``Yesterday was a little common human bonding,'' said Ables.
``Today they'll be hating each other again. They'll be fighting up
there again this evening.''
   Seven company workers are charged with attempted murder in the
shooting of a UMW demonstrator in August, and six pickets have been
charged with rock throwing, according to the Logan County
Magistrate's office.
   When the UMW members arrived back at their picket shack, some
were subjected to razzing and told they should have let the
replacement workers, known in picket-line taunting as scabs, drown.
   ``You don't know what to do until you're in the situation,''
said Andrew Perry, another Pittston employee on the Massey picket
line.
   ``Sitting around and watching a man drown, now that's cruel.''
   A UMW official said the rescue was not unusual.
   ``I'm not surprised, because that's just the kind of people we
are,'' said Danny Wells, a local board member of UMW District 17.
``We hate what's going on up there, but any time you see someone
that's in trouble, that's the immediate response of the United Mine
Workers.''
   Elsewhere in southern West Virginia, and in neighboring eastern
Kentucky, heavy rain from the remnants of Hurricane Jerry produced
flooding that blocked roads, closed schools and forced some people
to evacuate. The Tug Fork River overflowed its banks by 6 feet
Tuesday night in low-lying areas of Matewan. The river at
Williamson crested about 3 feet above flood stage.
</TEXT>
