<HEAD>Bush Presents Medals To 27 Scientists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Wednesday presented the
National Medal of Science and the National Medal of Technology to
27 American scientists who contributed in specialities ranging from
computers to genetics to planets.
   ``Today we celebrate dreams that you are making possible, dreams
that will keep America competitive, raise our standard of living,
improve our quality of life,'' Bush told the scientists who
gathered for the award ceremony in the East Room of the White
House. ``And your dreams presage a new golden age of information,
understanding and technology and show how creativity comes from the
human heart and mind.''
   The recipients of the National Medal of Technology and their
fields of specialty were: Robert R. Everett and Jay W. Forrester,
computer technology; Helen Edwards, Richard A. Lundy, J. Ritchie
Orr and Alvin Tollestrup, the TEVATRON particle accelerator; and
Herbert W. Boyer and Stanley N. Cohen, gene splicing techniques.
   Those receiving the National Medal of Science were: Rober W.
Sperry, behavioral sciences; Katherine Esau, Viktor Hamburger,
Philip Leder, Joshua Lederberg, and Harland G. Wood, biological
sciences; Richard B. Bernstein, Melvin Calvin, Rudolph A. Marcus
and Harden M. McConnell, chemistry; Harry G. Drickamer and Herbert
E. Grier, engineering; Samuel Karlin, Saunders MacLane and Donald
C. Spencer, mathematics; Arnold O. Beckman, Eugene N. Parker,
Robert P. Sharp and Henry M. Stommel, physical sciences.
