<HEAD>Storm Victims Send Relief to Earthquake Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city of Charleston, still digging
out from last month's pounding by Hurricane Hugo, on Wednesday set
up a relief fund and dispatched a planeload of bottled water for
earthquake victims in California.
   ``I know we still have and will have great needs here and
charity certainly begins at home,'' Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. said.
``However, it would be wrong for this community ... not to reach in
and contribute to those who are hurt and suffering right now.''
   An Air Force C-141 transport plane carrying a cargo of fresh
water also took Charleston Police Chief Reuben Greenberg and
several of his officers to Northern California to help with
emergency operations.
   In addition, the city has set up a California Earthquake
Disaster Relief Fund to raise money for victims of the disaster.
   After Hurricane Hugo slammed into Charleston with 135 mph winds
on Sept. 21, relief poured into the city from across the nation.
   ``We realized the extraordinary help that (the relief) gave us
and made a commitment that if ever another community in the United
States ... was hit with a disaster, we would want to respond,''
Riley said.
