<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Barred From Defending Newspaper Editor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Sakharov barred from TV program,
details. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet legislators were barred on Wednesday from
defending a daring newspaper editor President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
wants dismissed, one deputy reported.
   Nikolai A. Kutsenko, a lawmaker from the Ukraine, said the group
will submit a petition signed by 34 legislators charging Gorbachev
with using ``pressure tactics'' that contradict his own reforms.
   Kutsenko said Supreme Soviet leaders would not permit the
defense of Vladislav A. Starkov, editor of the weekly Arguments and
Facts, because they viewed his case as a matter for the Communist
Party rather than the government.
   Starkov's tabloid has been at the forefront of Gorbachev's
policy of glasnost, or openness.
   Kutsenko said he wanted to speak for Starkov on Wednesday but
was told he could not have the floor by Gorbachev's hand-picked
vice president, Anatoly I. Lukyanov, and the chairmen of the
legislature's two houses, Rafik N. Nishanov and Yevgeny M. Primakov.
   The petition he hoped to read accuses Gorbachev of trying to
discredit Arguments and Facts. Kutsenko said Lukyanov also refused
to recognize him on Tuesday.
   Gorbachev lashed out at selected editors at a closed Communist
Party meeting Friday. He apparently was trying to regain some
control over the press, which has carried daily reports criticizing
the system and sometimes its leaders.
   Journalists, quoting their bosses who attended and asking not to
be identified, said Gorbachev accused Starkov and others of seeking
his political downfall.
   Yegor Yakovlev, chief editor of the weekly Moscow News, wrote in
the current issue Wednesday that Gorbachev said the country was
``at the peak of tension,'' with passions flaring over economic
crisis and ethnic strife.
   He blamed the press for warning of famine, a coup or plot and
accused it of offering anti-communist views, demanding instead that
the press make a sober analysis of events, Yakovlev's article said.
   Human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov called Wednesday for
journalists around the world to stand up for Starkov.
   In an interview Wednesday, the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize laureate
also urged the Supreme Soviet to strip the Communist Party of its
constitutional monopoly on power. He called it an anachronism.
   Most lawmakers appeared to dismiss the idea.
   Journalists, speaking on condition of anonymity, said top
broadcast officials barred Sakharov at the last minute from
appearing live on last Friday's popular television show, Vzglyad.
   Also on Wednesday, the Supreme Soviet gave preliminary approval
to a bill that would give local governing councils more power to
control the economies in their areas. It would also give the
councils, known as soviets, the power to levy local income taxes.
</TEXT>
