<FIRST>u w AM-Spending-Taxes     10-18 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending-Taxes,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Won't Go Along with Slimmer Deficit-Cut Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House refused Wednesday to endorse a
slimmed-down deficit-reduction bill that includes a cut in the
capital-gains tax but no improvement in child-care benefits.
   The non-binding 228-181 vote was against a Republican motion
that would have instructed House negotiators to strip from the
deficit bill virtually all spending increases and tax reductions.
   However, the bill would have retained provisions repealing
catastrophic medical protection for retirees and wiping out a law
requiring that employer-paid health insurance not discriminate
against lower-paid workers.
   ``It is hard for us to conceive of a budget bill fatter than
this one,'' said Rep. Bill Frenzel of Minnesota, senior Republican
on the House Budget Committee, in arguing for the motion to trim
the measure.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, accused Republicans of talking from both sides of
their mouths by arguing for a leaner bill while insisting on repeal
of the two health-insurance provisions.
   Rostenkowski accused President Bush of sitting on the sidelines
in the budget fight _ ``content to provide absolutely no leadership
on real deficit reduction'' _ leaving his top advisers to ``the
collective pursuit of short-term gratification ... (and) pursuing
shallow political victories and bankrupt budget policies.''
   Rostenkowski's remarks were aimed at Bush's insistence that
taxes on capital gains be cut. The House voted last month for such
a cut over opposition from Democratic leaders.
   Negotiators from the Senate and House will work out a compromise
between the competing deficit-reduction plans passed by the two
chambers.
   The Senate bill is a lean version that contains neither the
capital-gains reduction nor repeal of the health provisions.
   The House approved those three items in the bill by lopsided
margins. Thus, it would be difficult for House negotiators to drop
them from the final compromise unless given assurances that they
could be added to some other bill later this year.
</TEXT>
