<FIRST>r w AM-Hastings     10-18 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Lawmakers Urge Ouster of Hastings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawmaker active in the civil rights movement
urged the Senate on Wednesday to remove Judge Alcee L. Hastings
from the bench, saying Florida's first black federal judge
``betrayed'' his position of leadership.
   ``There have been a lot or cases in our judicial system in which
race has been a problem,'' said Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., as
final arguments began in the Senate impeachment trial. ``This isn't
one of them or I would be the first to tell you so.''
   ``We did not wage the civil rights struggle in order to trade
one form of judicial corruption for another,'' Conyers said. He
said a federal judgeship entailed trust and Hastings had ``betrayed
that strust and betrayed those who looked to him for leadership.''
   House members act as prosecutors in such proceedings. If the
Senate votes to remove Hastings from office, he would be the sixth
federal official to be removed in such a fashion.
   Hastings, 53, is accused of conspiring to obtain a $150,000
payoff and lying to a federal jury that acquitted him of it five
years ago. The Senate heard closing arguments in the case on
Wednesday.
   The Senate plans to deliberate the evidence behind closed doors
on Thursday and later vote on whether to remove him from the bench.
   Hastings, taking the Senate floor, once again denied that he had
taken part in a payoff plot.
   ``I am not guilty of having committed any crime _ that is my
defense,'' Hastings said. ``Please act fairly.''
   Hastings disputed a statement by Conyers that race would be at
the core of his defense. Hastings had, however, told a news
conference only a day earlier that he would not have been awaiting
removal from office if he had been white.
   The House prosecutors urged the Senate to ignore Hastings'
acquittal in 1983, saying he lied. They also dismissed defense
complaints that the impeachment trial is a second trial for
Hastings, violating the prohibition against double jeopardy.
   Hastings would be removed as a judge immediately upon conviction
by the Senate on any one of the 17 articles of impeachment approved
by the House.
   Conviction would not only remove Hastings from the federal bench
but also halt payment of the $89,500 judicial salary that he
continues to collect.
