<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica-Sisulu Bjt   10-18 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Sisulu, Bjt,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0700 to restore AP logo</HEAD>
<HEAD>ANC Leaders Recall Hardships And Triumphs Of 26 Years In Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter Sisulu was mocked by guards,
strip-searched and forced to break rocks in a quarry during 26
years in prison, but news of the struggle against apartheid kept
him from despair.
   ``I never had the feeling I was at the lowest,'' the 77-year-old
African National Congress leader said Wednesday. ``There were
moments I felt very much in high spirits ... every time there was a
movement, a strike'' on the outside.
   Sisulu and two ANC colleagues, Elias Motsoaledi and Ahmed
Kathrada, recalled prison life during an interview at a Soweto
church with American journalists.
   They and senior ANC leader Nelson Mandela were convicted of
planning anti-government sabotage and sentenced to life terms in
1964. Mandela remains in prison, but Sisulu, Motsoaledi, Kathrada
and two others sentenced with them were among eight long-term
political prisoners freed unconditionally Sunday.
   The ANC is the biggest group fighting white domination in South
Africa.
   After their convictions, the ANC leaders were sent to a
maximum-security prison on Robben Island, off Cape Town.
   ``At the early stages, they (guards) went out of their way, as
they openly stated to us, to crush us, to break our morale,'' said
Kathrada, 60. ``They tried to instill into our minds that we would
be forgotten factors in a few years time.''
   He recalled a jailer with a swastika tattoo who said: ``I've
come to fight a war.''
   ``We started off chopping stones, breaking big stones into small
stones and small stones into smaller stones,'' Kathrada said. ``In
1965, we started working at a lime quarry, with picks and shovels.
That continued for 10 years.''
   He and other prisoners of Indian descent, and those of mixed
race, initially were treated better than black prisoners, Kathrada
said. Sisulu and other blacks were forced to wear short pants even
in winter, were not provided with socks and were not given bread,
he told reporters.
   Sisulu said: ``We used to come back from work on very cold days
_ no hot water. We stripped naked outside, then passed through a
cold shower of sea water.''
   At one stage, Sisulu was deprived of solid food for three days
and Mandela for six because prison authorities decided they had not
worked hard enough.
   In May 1971, pro-independence guerrillas from Namibia were
transferred to Robben Island and clashed with guards, Kathrada said.
   ``We embarked on a hunger strike and they decided to punish us
further,'' he said. ``They came one night, many of them very drunk,
and they stripped us all naked. We faced the wall. This was a
simple question of wanting to humiliate and punish us.''
   An older prisoner, Govan Mbeki, almost suffered a heart attack,
Kathrada said, but the hunger strike continued.
   ``We were meeting the oppressor at close hand,'' he said. ``It
helped to keep us united. What kept our morale up was our
confidence in our beliefs ... confidence that we are going to
triumph sooner or later. Of that we had no doubt at any stage.''
   Pressure by prisoners eventually ended the discrimination
between racial groups and won other concessions, including
permission to study and engage in sports, Kathrada said. They were
allowed newspapers in 1980 and radio and television in 1986.
   He expressed gratitude to the International Red Cross and to
Helen Suzman, an opposition member of Parliament who is now
retired, for campaigning on behalf of the prisoners.
   Before the liberalization, Kathrada said, ``political prisoners
gave top priority to keeping themselves informed, in one way or
another _ begging, stealing, buying, bribing. ... We tried to
smuggle in things, too _ letters, visits, just about everything.''
   News often was months late. In 1976, prisoners who arrived in
August told them of the uprising by Soweto schoolchildren in June
that started nationwide unrest.
   Sisulu cited that uprising as one of the most dramatic events of
his imprisonment.
   ``It was inspiring to see the children taking a position, to say
`Thus far and no further _ we're tired of your oppression,''' he
said. ``It boosted our spirits.''
   Motsoaledi, 65, said he learned with shock that three friends of
his children were killed in the aftermath of the June 1976
uprising. He said three of his six children went into exile, like
thousands of other young blacks who supported the African National
Congress.
   Sisulu's family has been hit particularly hard by political
turmoil. His wife, Albertina, is under restrictions; one son is in
jail; another was detained for two years, and two children are in
exile.
</TEXT>
