<FIRST>r p AM-MississippiElection     10-18 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mississippi Election,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Savor Victory for Mississippi Congressional Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A maverick Democrat's victory in a
Mississippi congressional race gave the state's House delegation a
one-party look and saddled Republicans with their fifth loss in
seven special elections this year.
   State Sen. Gene Taylor's victory Tuesday over Republican Tom
Anderson gave the state its first all-Democrat House delegation in
17 years.
   ``Gene was just an excellent candidate for this time,'' state
Democratic Chairman Ed Cole said Wednesday. ``But the lesson to the
party is that if you've got a process that's open and fair, the
people will tell you who they want.''
   Taylor, 36, garnered 65 percent of the vote and carried 11 of
the 12 counties in the 5th District, which includes the Gulf Coast.
Anderson, a top aide to Republican U.S. Sen. Trent Lott, was making
his first bid for public office.
   Taylor won 82,855 votes to Anderson's 44,377 in unofficial
totals.
   Taylor, who is to be sworn in next week, will serve 14 months,
succeeding Republican freshman Rep. Larkin Smith, who was killed in
an Aug. 13 plane crash.
   National Democratic Party Chairman Ron Brown said Taylor's
election was ``yet another signal that the supposed Republican
realignment in the South does not exist.
   ``This is a district that the Republican Party wanted so
desperately that George Bush personally campaigned for Trent Lott's
handpicked candidate,'' Brown said.
   Democrats had accused Lott of forcing Smith's widow from the
race after she had made public her intention to run. She eventually
backed Anderson.
   ``I think realistically something very American happened,''
Taylor said. ``The citizens chose a candidate rather than the big
power brokers in Washington and the big money interests.''
   The seat had been in GOP hands since Lott won it in 1972. He was
elected to the Senate in 1988.
   Republicans were assessing the loss Wednesday.
   ``I think the long-term ramifications of it are neglible,'' said
Haley Barbour, Republican national committeeman for Mississippi.
   ``Voters vote for who they think is the best candidate. From a
party point of view, it's no surprise,'' he said from Washington.
   Rep. Guy Vander Jagt, R-Mich., chairman of the Republican
Congressional Campaign Committee, said the GOP's special election
losses this year showed that voters choose Democratic candidates
who ``reject the liberalism of the National Democratic Party.
   ``The candidate who best captures the local agenda is the one
who will win,'' he said.
</TEXT>
