<FIRST>r a AM-FormerPresidents     10-18 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Former Presidents,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gerald Ford: Nixon Pardon `Right Thing To Do'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BRANCH, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ford said Wednesday
his pardon of Richard Nixon was ``absolutely the right thing to
do,'' although the Watergate scandal may have cost him the 1976
election.
   Questioned by 100 schoolchildren about the pardon, Ford said it
was the only way to end national divisions. He said the healing
process after Nixon's resignation as president will be the legacy
of Ford's brief administration.
   ``I was spending 25 percent of my time on the problems of one
man at a time when I should have been spending 100 percent of my
time on the problems of 240 million Americans,'' Ford said.
   ``The only way for me to get rid of the problems of one man was
to pardon Mr. Nixon,'' he said. ``It was absolutely the right
decision. I'm more convinced now than I was then it was the right
thing to do.''
   The Watergate scandal developed well before Ford was appointed
vice president, but he said it was costly to him.
   ``It was a tragedy,'' Ford said. ``I suspect that people voted
against me because of the existence of the Watergate scandal.''
   Ford was questioning by the Iowa children in a Quaker meeting
house on the grounds of the Herbert Hoover National Historic Site.
Earlier Wednesday, he spoke at a forum at the Herbert Hoover
Presidential Library on the role former presidents should play in
American government.
   Ford argued against a formal role for ex-presidents. Ford is one
of four living former presidents, who also include Nixon, Jimmy
Carter and Ronald Reagan.
   ``Frankly, I don't see the value in formalizing the role of
ex-presidents,'' Ford said. ``Let ex-presidents decide what
interest to pursue, what contributions to make on their own.''
   Ford said he spends his time lecturing on the college circuit,
campaigning for Republican candidates and pursuing business
opportunities.
   Carter and Ford sent President Bush a variety of recommendations
in November 1988, before Bush took office, but Ford said they were
largely ignored. The proposals were intended to help with Bush's
transition from vice president to president.
   ``President Bush made no comment on it and, as far as I know,
none of it has been implemented,'' Ford said. ``I felt an adverse
reaction from his own staff. I was somewhat disappointed.''
   Among the proposals from Ford and Carter were ways to solve the
nation's savings and loan crisis and ways to reduce the federal
deficit by cutting spending and raising taxes on beer, wine,
cigarettes and motor fuel.
</TEXT>
