<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1945EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Survivors     10-18 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Survivors,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Separate Neighbors Embrace; Tourists Sleep Under Tablecloths</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neighbors who had feared for each other's
lives embraced cheerfully Wednesday as they surveyed their ruined
homes, and tourists swapped stories about how they survived the
killer earthquake.
   Neil Hancock comforted Maryellen Sechser, his upstairs neighbor
in what had been a 21-unit apartment building in the Marina
District. The building toppled and caught fire after Tuesday's
quake, and three people were feared dead.
   ``She is the first one I've seen since last night,'' Hancock
said.
   The two stood among a crowd at Divisadero and Beach streets
watching firefighters hose water over the blackened remains of the
building.
   ``When I got here the whole building collapsed. I could see into
my apartment,'' Sechser said, fighting back tears. She watched
helplessly as the flames came up through the floor of her ruined
living room.
   The worst thing was not knowing if her neighbors, many of them
elderly, were all right, she said.
   ``(I thought) people were still in the building. I couldn't save
anyone, I couldn't save the animals, I couldn't save anything,''
Sechser said. ``I lost everything. What you see is all I've got.''
   Sechser went to the Red Cross shelter several blocks away hoping
to find neighbors but saw no one until she found Hancock, who also
had worried about neighbors.
   ``I was standing here all night,'' he said. ``I didn't know who
was dead and who was alive.''
   The destruction brought out hundreds of neighborhood residents
who crowded outside police lines to view the damage. Many took
pictures or continued to talk about where they had been when the
earth began to move.
   Balmy weather contributed to a festive atmosphere on some
streets.
   At the Embarcadero Hyatt Regency hotel, guests like Harley and
Marie Brown of Denver joked about the snoring that kept them awake
in the ballroom, where hundreds of other guests and stranded office
workers slept under tablecloths.
   ``It was just wall-to-wall people,'' Ms. Brown said. ``You could
hardly walk through without stepping on people. People were
laughing because the snoring would get louder and louder.''
   Survivors quickly snatched up local newspapers as souvenirs, and
people on the streets exchanged stories and shared airport
information.
   As Hyatt guests lined up for pay phones to change airline
reservations, others enjoyed an impromptu buffet of boxed cereal,
fruit salad and pastries by candlelight in the hotel's vast but
dimly-lit lobby.
   ``It was really rocking and rolling. It was pretty good,'' Juan
Richardson, a power company worker, said of the quake. ``A lot of
people from New York were wigging out.''
   Most visitors vowed to return to San Francisco despite the
disaster _ and some already were planning return trips.
   ``I was looking real forward to eating Oriental food last night,
and I'm still looking forward to coming back for that dinner,''
said Vernon Rowe of Pittsburg, Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
