<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Psychiatric     10-18 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Psychiatric,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Soviet Psychiatrists Condemn Readmission to World Body</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet psychiatrists living in exile
condemned the decision by the World World Psychiatric Association
on Wednesday to restore membership to the Soviet Union.
   Members voted overwhelmingly to reinstate the Soviet All-Union
Society of Psychiatrists after a six-year absence, but reserved the
right to suspend the membership if an investigation showed the
Soviets still used psychiatry for political purposes.
   The Soviets left the world organization in 1983 to avoid
expulsion because of allegations that dissidents were being
certified insane.
   Delegates of the official Soviet association admitted in Athens
that political abuse of psychiatry had occurred.
   An unofficial Soviet group, the Independent Psychiatric
Association, was admitted without conditions Wednesday. It was
established seven months ago by psychiatrists who oppose the
political use of their profession and is not recognized by the
Kremlin.
   No members of the independent organization attended the Athens
meeting. Sources said they were unable to get visas.
   Anatoly Koryagin, a psychiatrist who was held in a psychiatric
hospital for expressing dissident views and now lives in the West,
told a news conference after the meeting it would be difficult for
a review committee to investigate Soviet psychiatric hospitals.
   ``The Soviet psychiatrists will do their utmost to keep any
evidence of impropriety secret,'' he said.
   He said it would be ``almost impossible'' to get the two-thirds
majority needed to suspend Soviet membership. The resolution
adopted provides for an investigation during the next year, with
action to follow if necessary.
   Algirdas Stratkevicius, another emigre psychiatrist, said the
Soviets should have been given three years of probation before full
membership was restored, and said the World Psychiatric
Association's standards has been ``seriously lowered.''
   He and Koryagin held the news conference on behalf of the
Association Against the Political Use of Psychiatry, which is based
in Amsterdam and opposed restoration of the Soviet membership.
   Members passed the motion 291-45, with 19 abstentions. The
United States supported it.
   ``We wanted a compromise solution,'' said Melvin Sabshin,
medical director of the American Psychiatric Association. The
Americans had said they would oppose unconditional reinstatement
   A U.S. delegation visited the Soviet Union in February and found
that, despite improvements in the psychiatric system, patients
still did not enjoy the necessary legal safeguards.
</TEXT>
