<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 2016EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-RailWorkers     10-18 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rail Workers,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Gains More Power To Punish Rail Safety Violators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government can bar railroad workers who
violate rail safety rules from safety-sensitive positions under new
federal rules issued Wednesday.
   The Federal Railroad Administration has previously had no
authority to remove private railroad employees. It gained the
authority to assess civil penalties in July 1988.
   The new rule, to take effect in 30 days, follows the Rail Safety
Improvement Act of 1988.
   Employees who face suspension or permanent disqualification by
the agency will be notified and may face a hearing, the agency
said. Any disqualification order would be disseminated throughout
the rail industry.
   FRA Administrator Gil Carmichael said the new regulation should
lead to ``a new level of respect for the rail safety rules and
regulations.''
   ``Our only goal is to improve safety,'' he said, ``and if
enforcement action against individuals is the best way to deal with
a serious safety situation, we will act fairly, but firmly.''
   The orders apply to supervisors as well as employees who operate
trains, issue orders to trains, conduct training or inspect or
repair locomotives, cars, tracks or signals.
</TEXT>
