<FIRST>r a AM-Floods     10-18 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Floods,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain Floods Out Residents Of Mid Appalachians</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Flood Rescue, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of the ridge-bound valleys of southern West Virginia
and eastern Kentucky cleaned out mud and debris Wednesday left by
flooding from the remnants of Hurricane Jerry. And many of them
waited for more bad news.
   Forecasters predicted heavy showers that threatened to boost
water levels again. The National Weather Service issued a flood
watch through Thursday for 12 West Virginia counties and sections
of Virginia, with a flash flood watch for eastern Kentucky.
   West Virginia Gov. Gaston Caperton toured flood-ravaged sections
of his state, primarily in Logan and Mingo counties.
   The worst damage appeared to be in Matewan, where 150 homes were
evacuated. The Tug Fork River overflowed its banks by 6 feet
Tuesday night in low-lying areas of Matewan. Downstream at
Williamson, the river crested about 3 feet above flood stage.
   ``This is the 32nd time this has happened in my lifetime,''
Albert Collins Sr. said from a porch behind a downtown Matewan
store. ``It used to be that it just gave us something to do to come
down here and watch it.''
   Now, however, he believes something should be done about it.
   Donald Daugherty, a mail carrier from McCarr, Ky., across the
river from Matewan, agreed as he surveyed the damage.
   ``It's hard enough if you have to go through this once in a
lifetime, but this is over and over and over again.''
   John Perdue, an executive assistant to Caperton, said
preliminary survey work for a Matewan flood wall is being done. No
construction timetable has been set, he said. Williamson already
has a new flood wall.
   In Kentucky, damage assessment teams from the state Division of
Disaster and Emergency Services toured four counties believed to be
hardest hit in Tuesday's flood, which many officials said was the
worst to strike the region since 1984.
   Flooding was still occurring at Jackson, Booneville and
Heidelberg as the Kentucky River continued to rise, the National
Weather Service reported.
   Eighty percent of the roads and bridges in Letcher County were
damaged by the flood, said county Judge-Executive Reuben Watts, who
estimated the repair cost at $1.5 million.
   ``We've still got quite a few places where people can't get to
their homes and can't get out,'' said Mike Watts, the judge's son.
He estimated 75 homes suffered flood damage and between 75 to 100
bridges were washed out. Many of the structures were small, private
bridges.
   Water damaged the homes of 200 people in Clay County and
drinking water was being brought to residents in the Big Creek
area, said Joe Jones, assistant emergency services coordinator for
the county.
   Pike County, across the Tug Fork from Williamson, W.Va.,
declared an emergency after high water stranded hundreds of
residents and closed schools for two days. One of the hardest-hit
areas was Beefhide Hollow, where at least 25 families were forced
from their homes.
</TEXT>
