<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     10-18 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israelis Raid UN Food Center, Detain Refugee Camp Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers raided the main U.N. food
distribution center in the Gaza Strip and briefly detained relief
officers at three West Bank refugee camps Wednesday, Arabs and U.N.
officials reported.
   An officer with Israel's military government of the occupied
territories, who would not let his name be used, said the soldiers
were investigating reports that ``some employees of UNRWA are
either participating in the uprising themselves or aiding
activities of the uprising.''
   The army spokesman's office declined comment.
   An uprising among the 1.7 million Palestinian residents began 22
months ago in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel captured
from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 war.
   Israeli soldiers or civilians have killed 596 Palestinians and
40 Israelis have died. At least 130 Palestinians have been killed
by fellow Arabs, most on suspicion of collaborating Israel.
   Claire Grimes, spokeswoman for the U.N. Relief and Works Agency,
said documents were seized at the distribution center in the Gaza
Strip's Deir el-Balah refugee camp and three UNRWA staff members
were taken into custody.
   She said Christian Saunders of Britain and Declan Greenway of
Ireland were released after about an hour but the third, an Arab,
remained in Israeli hands.
   Ms. Grimes said the soldiers smashed the windows of a U.N. car
to get to the Arab staff member, who was locked inside. Palestinian
reporters identified him as Abdel Rahman Aiessa.
   In the West Bank, soldiers and paramilitary border police
briefly detained at least four staff members for questioning at
UNRWA offices in the Dheishe, Fawwar and Jalazoun refugee camps in
the West Bank, Ms. Grimes said.
   UNRWA sponsors aid programs for more than 375,000 Palestinian
refugees in the West Bank and 450,000 in Gaza.
   Brig. Gen. Amnon Strashnov, the army's chief prosecutor, told
the Israeli news agency Itim on Wednesday that 40,000 Palestinians
had been detained since the uprising began Dec. 8, 1987.
   He said 9,000 were held under ``administrative detention''
rules, allowing imprisonment for up to a year without charge or
trial, and about 600 had been detained more than once under those
provisions.
   Strashnov said 9,600 Palestinians currently were in custody,
including nearly 1,900 administrative detainees. Of the others, he
said, 2,799 had been convicted and sentenced, and the rest were in
the legal process.
   The prosecutor said 86 soldiers had been tried in military
courts for misconduct related to the uprising and 500-600 more had
been investigated. He did not give figures for convictions or
reprimands.
   A military court sentenced Ossman Marahia, 23, a Palestinian
from east Jerusalem, to 27 years in jail after he pleaded guilty
Wednesday to committing dozens of firebombings and arsons over five
years. The court was told a bus driver was slightly injured in one
incident.
</TEXT>
