<DOCNO> AP891018-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1850EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Geology     10-18 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Geology,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worst Damage Isn't Always Closest To Quake Epicenter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Among the lessons demonstrated by the
catastrophic Bay Area earthquake is that the most lethal damage
isn't always closest to the epicenter, experts said Wednesday.
   The Oakland freeway that collapsed, killing an estimated 250
people, was 50 miles from the center of the quake. By contrast,
some places just a few miles from the epicenter were hardly scathed.
   Soft waterfront soils, construction practices, land-use patterns
and changes in seismic waves as they move away from an epicenter
can conspire to create hopscotch patterns of earthquake damage,
experts said.
   The collapse of Interstate 880, the Nimitz Freeway, was the most
deadly disaster caused by the jolt, which measured 6.9 on the
Richter scale. Directly across the bay, there was extensive damage
in some sections of San Francisco.
   Far fewer casualties were reported in extensively damaged Santa
Cruz, just 10 miles south of the epicenter. In San Jose, 18 miles
north of the epicenter, damage was relatively mild.
   ``That seems to mainly be a function of ground conditions:
either artificially filled ground or not very stable natural
deposits around the margins of the bay,'' said geologist Douglas
Hamilton, president of Earth Sciences Associates, a Palo Alto
consulting firm.
   The Nimitz Freeway apparently rests on soft fill and bay mud,
and ``that was probably a factor,'' said Bob Streitz, a supervising
geologist at the California Division of Mines and Geology in
Sacramento.
   Hamilton said San Jose may have escaped catastrophic damage
because much of the city sits on stream deposits somewhat firmer
than bayfront mud and fill.
   In general, the intensity of ground shaking is strongest near
the epicenter, which explains why many buildings and roads
collapsed in Santa Cruz, Watsonville, Los Gatos and Hollister.
   Ronald Scott, a civil engineering professor at the California
Institute of Technology in Pasadena, said bedrock tends to shake at
high frequencies _ short, sharp jolts _ while soft fill and mud
produce ``more of a rolling effect that goes on longer. The motion
may be magnified on top of such deposits.''
   That was illustrated by catastrophic earthquakes centered on
Mexico's Pacific coast in 1985. The worst damage was in Mexico
City, which rests on soft sediments of an old lakebed 250 miles
from the epicenter.
   The change in seismic waves as they spread from a fault, along
with softer soils, give the waves longer vibration periods, Scott
said. That can make them more damaging to large structures, such as
I-880 or the Bay Bridge, than to small ones.
   ``The farther you go, there is some tendency for larger
structures to be affected,'' he said.
   Another reason for the concentration of deaths far from the
epicenter of Tuesday's quake is simply that the San
Francisco-Oakland area is more heavily populated.
   ``Santa Cruz experienced the kind of damage it did because it
was in the earthquake epicentral area,'' Scott said. ``But there
isn't a big Nimitz Freeway running through Santa Cruz. The biggest
concentration of large structures is around San Francisco.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1855EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Krenz-Profile     10-18 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Krenz-Profile,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youngest Politburo Member Takes Over From Mentor Honecker</HEAD>
<HEAD>With East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FRA4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egon Krenz, East Germany's new Communist Party
leader, grew to political maturity under the tutelage of his
hard-line predecessor, Erich Honecker.
   Convivial and articulate, Krenz's outgoing nature offers a
personal contrast to the aging, ailing Honecker. But politically he
adhers to the same orthodox brand of party doctrine as his ousted,
77-year-old mentor.
   The state news agency ADN announced Wednesday that the
52-year-old Krenz succeeded Honecker as head of the party, the
government and the military. Honecker came under increasing fire at
home as opposition mounted and a refugee exodus continued.
   Career politician Krenz is by far the youngest official on the
21-member Politburo dominated by aging Communists, many of them in
their 70s. But he has a reputation for following Honecker's hard
line.
   A burly, bushy-haired man, Krenz long has been plagued by rumors
he was an alcoholic, although there has been virtually nothing to
substantiate that.
   He is known for his spontaneous visits to local bars and
restaurants that give his bodyguards the jitters. Communist Party
sources say he enjoys striking up conversations with patrons.
   Krenz was born the son of a tailor in Kolberg, a coastal town in
what is now northwestern Poland, on March 19, 1937.
   He joined East Germany's communist youth organization in 1953,
while he was still in high school and the East German nation was
four years old.
   Krenz studied to become a teacher, but joined the East German
army and rose to the rank of lieutenant before being discharged in
1959.
   After studying in Moscow from 1964 to 1967, Krenz returned to
party work, beginning with the youth organization.
   He has been a member of the Communist Party's Central Committee
since 1973 and joined the ruling Politburo 10 years later.
   In recent years, he has been in charge of official youth
organizations and internal security matters, while many
acknowledged he was being groomed to take over from Honecker.
   Krenz lives in a heavily guarded compound reserved for
high-ranking Communist Party officials at Lake Wandlitz, about nine
miles north of Berlin.
   He has long mirrored Honecker's line on various issues _
repeating, for example, the long-held assertion that the
``imperialist'' West poses a threat to communist East Germany.
   In a profile on Oct. 8, West Germany's Bild am Sonntag newspaper
said Krenz is married and has two children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
