<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1953EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-EmergencyLanding     10-18 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emergency Landing,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Jet Makes Emergency Landing At Monte Vista</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTE VISTA, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Northwest Airlines jet with 104
people aboard made an emergency landing at a small, unattended
airport Wednesday after losing electrical power, sliding off a
short runway and into the mud, officials said.
   The DC-9 filled with smoke after landing, and the captain had to
use an ax stored above an emergency exit to release cabin pressure
and allow the doors open, a passenger said.
   One of the 99 passengers was treated for shock and minor
injuries at a hospital in Alamosa nearly 20 miles from this
southern Colorado city and released, hospital officials said. The
pilot suffered minor cuts and bruises.
   The plane, which had been flying from Minneapolis to Phoenix,
went dark about 11 p.m., said passenger Judy Sciola, 49, of Edina,
Minn.
   ``We started shaking a little bit,'' she said. ``We circled and
circled. Then we hit the runway. There was a lot of scraping and
flames. I'm sure the tires exploded.''
   ``I could hear the landing gear go down,'' Sciola said. ``The
pressure was just awful. The little baby next to me was just
screaming.''
   The plane slid about 1,000 feet off the end of the runway at
Monte Vista Municipal Airport at 12:20 a.m., said Bob Johnson,
regional director of the National Transportation Safety Board in
Denver.
   ``The crew seemed as confused as the passengers were. They
couldn't get a door open,'' Sciola said. ``Then it got even more
frightening because we thought we were going to blow up.''
   The only apparent damage to the jet was flat tires, Johnson said.
   ``Compliment that captain,'' said passenger Todd Curtis of
Thatcher, Ariz. Passengers said they could smell the tires burning
during the landing, but said there was no panic on the jet even
though the captain was unable to talk them over the intercom.
   When the plane landed, the crew had difficulty opening the doors
because the cabin pressure was wrong, Tina Borgmann, 24, of Waseca,
Minn., told WCCO radio in Minneapolis.
   The plane filled up with smoke, and ``the captain came running
back to try to get the doors open.'' she said. ``The captain had to
take an ax to the door. He finally got the doors to open. The
slides came out and all (aboard the aircraft) went down the
slides.''
   The airport was unattended, and the pilot apparently called the
Rio Grande County sheriff's office from a pay phone there, Johnson
said.
   Northwest did not release the captain's name, saying its policy
was that it not release names of pilots involved in accidents
unless a death was involved.
   The jet's left generator apparently failed in flight and the
pilot tried unsuccessfully to start an auxiliary power unit, the
NTSB official said. The right generator failed soon after, and the
plane was left with battery backup power, which would have lasted
about 25 minutes.
   Airline officials said the cause of the malfunction was not
immediately known. Investigators from the NTSB, the Federal
Aviation Administration and the Northwest went to Monte Vista.
   The passengers and crew spent the night in Alamosa, and were to
take another plane to Phoenix, Northwest spokesman Kevin Whalen
said in Minneapolis.
   The Monte Vista airport has a runway 6,000 feet long and 60 feet
wide, Johnson said.
   ``Under ideal conditions that would be acceptable, but in an
emergency situation, it's marginal,'' he said.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
