<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-18 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Falls in Chicago, Rain Drenches Numerous States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Unseasonably cool temperatures produced light snow in Chicago
and parts of Vermont, Maine and Michigan, and remnants of Hurricane
Jerry kept some rivers rising in Kentucky and rain falling in
numerous states Wednesday.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from northern Florida across
Georgia and the Carolinas, and from Virginia to New York state and
into New England.
   Rain also fell in portions of Texas, Louisiana, Arkansas,
Colorado, Kansas and Nebraska.
   West Virginia Gov. Gaston Caperton toured his state's
flood-ravaged southern region, promising to make available
low-interest aid to residents hit by two days of high water.
   ``The remains of Hurricane Jerry dumped several inches of rain
... Monday night and Tuesday,'' said Peter Parke, a National
Weather Service meteorologist in Charleston, W.Va.
   ``The ground is still sopping wet from these rains.
Additionally, the Appalachian woods are settling into their winter
dormancy and cannot absorb much rainfall anymore,'' he said.
   Flooding damaged homes in southern West Virginia and Kentucky,
where the Kentucky River continued to rise.
   Houlton, Maine, had an inch of snow at daybreak. Besides Maine,
snow slickened roads in parts of Wisconsin, Michigan, Vermont,
Illinois and New York state.
   Overnight temperatures were unseasonably cool over much of the
Plains and the Mississippi Valley.
   The morning low dipped to 9 degrees in Bismark, N.D., breaking
the city's record of 10 degrees for the date set in 1972.
   Key West, Fla., reached 89 degrees in the early afternoon,
passing its record high of 88 for Oct. 18 set in 1952.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 34
degrees at Houlton and Presque Island, Maine, and Marquette, Mich.,
to 96 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
</TEXT>
