<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 2027EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-JetEngines-Sting     10-18 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jet Engines-Sting,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Air Force Policemen Plead Guilty in Jet Engine Sting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERN ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Hill Air Force Base security policemen
pleaded guilty Wednesday to federal charges in the theft of three
F-16 jet engines they sold to undercover federal agents.
   Airman 1st Class Brian David Roth of Chesterland, Ohio, pleaded
guilty to five of 22 counts in an indictment charging theft of the
engines and other military equipment from the northern Utah base.
Senior Airman Danny Joe Stroud of Newton, Kan., pleaded guilty to
one count of stealing the engines.
   The pleas were entered as part of an agreement in which another
count charging Stroud with the theft of $64,000 worth of computers
and the remaining 17 charges against Roth will be dropped when U.S.
District Judge David Sam sentences the men Dec. 12.
   Prosecutors said the airmen agreed to sell the Pratt &amp; Whitney
F100-PW-200 engines to FBI agents posing as operators of a mock
military surplus store as part of Operation Punchout, a three-year
undercover operation that netted an assortment of government
munitions and equipment.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Bruce Lubeck said Roth, 22, began
selling stolen equipment in October 1987, and that in July 1988
sold $40,000 worth of aviation instruments from a disabled F-4 jet
fighter.
   In December of that year, Roth sold the undercover agents a
portable radio valued at about $6,000 and six jackets and two
bayonets worth $500, Lubeck said.
   He said Roth sold the agents 11 night vision devices valued at
$40,000 last March, and began discussing the theft of the F-16
engines at that time.
   Lubeck said Stroud, 24, drove the trailer and engines off the
base during the July Fourth holiday weekend while Roth monitored
base radio traffic to ensure the operation would go undetected.
   The engines, which with a trailer and tow tractor were valued at
$8 million, were turned over to the agents and stored in a
warehouse by the FBI. The purchase price was to be $300,000,
authorities have said.
   Stroud and Roth were arrested July 10.
   The penalty for each of the theft counts is up to 10 years in
prison and a $250,000 fine.
   Federal grand juries have returned about 20 indictments since
Operation Punchout began, said U.S. Attorney Dee Benson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
