<FIRST>r i AM-Panama     10-18 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Says Political Prisoners Tortured in Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIA VICTORIA GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the opposition Christian
Democrats said Wednesday the party vice president was tortured in
prison and other party members were mistreated while under arrest
by the government controlled by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Party President Ricardo Arias Calderon said Raul Ossa ``was
submitted to cruel physical and psychological torture'' after being
arrested Oct. 3. Ossa was held for six days in La Chorrera jail in
the western part of the city.
   Military rebels tried unsuccessfully on Oct. 3 to oust Noriega,
who as head of the Defense Forces also controls the government.
   Arias Calderon said Ossa ``could see five members of the party
manacled to a water pipe and was told he also would be so they
would be the first to fall when the gringo invaders took the
barracks.''
   ``On more than one occasion they put a gun to his temple,'' he
said. ``For 11 hours he was blindfolded with gauze, left standing
up, interrogated and beaten hard in the stomach.''
   Guards took turns to keep Ossa from sleeping, Arias Calderon
reported.
   The party said it was creating a special human rights commission
to be headed by Ossa that will denounce violations of its members'
rights, assist victims and relatives, and educate the public.
   Arias Calderon said the Oct. 3 rebels ``were interrogated about
a supposed link between the Christian Democratic Party and an
American invasion.''
   The U.S. government has been using economic and political
pressure trying to force Noriega out after he was indicted on U.S.
drug trafficking charges in February 1988.
   Noriega denies the charges and says the campaign against him is
part of a U.S. effort to avoid giving up the Panama Canal at the
end of 1999 under the 1977 canal treaties.
   Arias Calderon said the Christian Democrats' publicity director
was arrested on Sept. 28, accused of attacking the state, but has
not been mistreated.
   Five other party members were jailed on Oct. 2 for carrying
posters bearing slogans including those demanding Arias Calderon's
freedom when he was briefly under arrest.
   Arias Calderon said an arrest warrant is out for party official
Ramon Aizpurua, now abroad, on charges of financing an armed
movement aimed at overthrowing the government.

</TEXT>
