<FIRST>r w AM-US-Korea     10-18 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Korea,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korean President Completes Washington Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korean President Roh Tae Woo completed
an official Washington visit Wednesday defending his government's
performance on democracy, human rights and opening of its markets
to imports.
   The president, his wife and members of his cabinet later flew to
Los Angeles for a meeting Wednesday night with former President
Reagan and a Thursday address.
   In Wednesday speeches to members of Congress and later to the
National Press Club, the Roh sought to assure his listeners that
democracy revived under his 1{-year-old administration is in South
Korea to stay _ ``an unstoppable force which no one can divert,''
he said.
   Roh said that since 1985 South Korea has lowered trade barriers
faster than most countries, and all trade issues with the United
States eventually will be ``resolved to mutual satisfaction.''
   Answering questions at the press club, Roh said it was unfair to
accuse Korea of backsliding on trade liberalization, and specific
issues would be solved ``one by one.''
   Roh also predicted South Korea and China eventually will have
normal relations. Contacts rapidly expanded from the time of the
1988 Seoul Olympics until slowed by China's crackdown last June on
pro-democracy demonstrators, he said, but ``I am sure they will
pick up again, and sure that we will have normal relations with
China.''
   Seeking the offensive against human rights critics who say his
government is reverting to repression, Roh said in his speech to
Congress, ``I will confront squarely every challenge to our young
democracy, whether from within or without.''
   He said ``regrettably, certain radicals have resorted to force
and committed unlawful acts to pursue their aims under the guise of
democratic reform ... here are also the tiny band of extremists who
parade anti-American slogans and perpetrate attacks on U.S.
facilities.''
   That was the closest he came to mentioning the invasion and
vandalism of the U.S. ambassador's residence in Seoul last week by
six young militants.
</TEXT>
