<HEAD>Protestant Shot to Death at Door, IRA Claims Responsibility</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men shot to death a
Protestant in front of his family in an outlying village late
Wednesday, and the IRA claimed responsibility.
   The victim, who was not immediately identified, was killed at
his home in Magheralin, a village 17 miles southwest of Belfast,
when he answered a knock at the door, city police headquarters said
in a statement.
   Police said the victim's wife and teen-age daughter witnessed
the killing.
   The gunmen used a stolen car, which was later found burned out
five miles from the scene of the attack, police said. However, they
gave few other details.
   The mainly Roman Catholic Irish Republican Army claimed
responsibility in a message to Belfast news organizations.
   It said the victim was a key figure among Protestant
paramilitary groups. The statement said he had been involved in
attacks on Catholic targets.
   The IRA is fighting British rule in Northern Ireland. It wants
to unite the predominantly Protestant province with the 95 percent
Catholic Republic of Ireland.
