<FIRST>r a AM-BodiesFound     10-18 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bodies Found,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search Continues After Bodies Found in Shallow Graves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHILLICOTHE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators used a backhoe Wednesday
at a farm where three bodies were found in shallow graves, but said
little about their search for others.
   Residents began calling in leads after the badly decomposed
bodies were found Monday night and removed Tuesday from a barn,
said Greg Coon, a spokesman for a law enforcement task force.
   ``We get good leads and bad leads,'' Coon said.
   Investigators used the backhoe to dig around a well between the
barn and a farmhouse. Two other sites in the area were searched
Wednesday, but investigators would not say where they were.
   The search began last week after the Oct. 9 arrests of an
elderly couple on charges of conspiracy to steal in an alleged
cattle swindle.
   Ray Copeland, 75, and Faye Copeland, 68, remained in jail
Wednesday on bonds of $25,000 each. No other charges have been
filed against them.
   The bodies, all male, were found in separate, shallow graves on
a farm 12 miles south of the Copelands' home in Mooresville, about
90 miles northeast of Kansas City.
   The bodies have not been identified.
   Neil Bryan, who owns the barn where the bodies were discovered,
said Copeland worked for him doing odd jobs over the last 20 years.
John Hovey, who said he rented the farm from Bryan, said Copeland
had warned him and his four children to stay out of the barn.
   ``It stunk in the barn. I thought an animal had crawled in there
and died,'' Hovey said.
   Bryan is not a suspect, authorities said.
   Livingston County Sheriff Leland O'Dell has been secretive about
what investigators are seeking. The Major Case Squad, a task force
formed Friday, said in its first statement that investigators were
trying to locate an unspecified number of transients who had stayed
with the Copelands.
   The Copeland farm has already been searched.
 
