<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Politics     10-18 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Politics,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Says Israel Won't Compromise on PLO Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Wednesday
his government will never compromise on its opposition to talks
with the PLO or on its refusal to trade land for peace, two main
points of disagreement between Israel and the United States.
   ``This is our land from the dawn of history, and it will be so
always. We will not be pushed or pressured,'' he told a convention
of fundamentalist Christians.
   Still, Israeli leaders appeared to be trying to dampen a
smoldering conflict with the United States following Shamir's
remarks Tuesday that Israel would rather face conflict with
Washington than accept a U.S.-backed plan that could lead to talks
with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens telephoned Secretary of State James
A. Baker III and they spoke for 45 minutes on Baker's efforts to
restart the Middle East peace process, Israel radio said. It gave
no details and Arens' spokesman declined comment.
   On Tuesday night, Shamir called President Bush about Shamir's
planned mid-November visit to Washington.
   ``They talked about the peace initiative and how they can
advance it,'' Shamir's office said. ``Both think it is very
important to meet in order to get a better understanding between
the United States and Israel about the peace initiative.''
   Israel radio said the issue of Shamir's statements Tuesday did
not come up.
   Before calling Bush, Shamir told members of his right-wing Likud
bloc, ``We must accept the assumption that we may be entering a
tense period with the United States.''
   ``This time the battle is hard. It's a miracle that, thus far,
we have held our own against the world, where no element supports
our position.''
   Later he told a Likud rally in Ramle that ``the stone-throwers,
the firebombers have not succeeded in driving us into the arms of
the PLO. It is not possible that when they fail to do this, others
by diplomatic means ... would try to bring us to meetings with the
PLO.''
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutweiller called Shamir's
statements ``unhelpful'' and said the United States ``is not
looking for a fight with Israel.''
   But Shamir made it clear in his speech to the Christian
convention Wednesday night that Israel will not budge in opposing
direct or indirect talks with the PLO or withdrawal from the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   He accused the PLO of striving toward ``the creation of a
Palestinian state in place of Israel. ... Let me make it very
clear. There will be no second Arab state in the land of Israel.''
   The biblical names of Judea and Samaria embrace what is now the
West Bank.
   The United States advocates trading land for peace. Baker
proposed consultations among Israel, Egypt and the United States
aimed at convening a meeting between Israel and Palestinians.
   Shamir's Likud bloc sees the Israeli-Palestinian meeting as
bringing the PLO into talks through the back door.
</TEXT>
