<HEAD>Former Island Senator Charged With Hurricane Looting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHRISTIANSTED, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A local police captain
who was a former senator was charged Wednesday with looting in the
aftermath of Hurricane Hugo, court records showed.
   Adelbert Bryan, 49, was released on $5,000 bond by Federal
Magistrate Jeffrey Resnick after being charged with grand larceny
and possession of stolen property, according to U.S. District Court
records.
   Also charged was prominent restaurant owner Michael Harris of
the Ritz Cafe.
   Widespread looting occurred in Christiansted after the hurricane
devastated St. Croix on Sept. 17. U.S. officials had to send about
1,100 troops from the mainland to help restore order on St. Croix,
one of the islands hardest hit in the Caribbean by Hugo.
   ``We have filed significant cases where people who knew better _
or who should have known better _ took items that had little or
nothing to do with survival,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney David
Nissman.
   The FBI said Bryan, who as one of the island's 15 senators
unsuccessfully ran against Gov. Alexander Farrelly in 1986, was
seen by several witnesses, including police officers, in a truck
loaded with plywood taken from a wrecked shopping center.
