<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru a0816 10-18 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0816,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas, Government of El Salvador Fail in Bid for Truce</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with talks recessed, new agreement
to meet. Picks up graf 6 pvs, `Oscar Santamaria ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas and the rightist
government of El Salvador failed at an extra day of peace talks
Wednesday to reach a truce in their 10-year-old civil war.
   Salvadoran Bishop Gregorio Rosa Chavez, an observer at the
talks, said the the Farabundo Marti National Liberation front and
the government delegates could not agree on details for a
cease-fire. But he said they agreed to continue trying at a meeting
Nov. 20-21 in Caracas, Venezuela.
   ``The two sides have agreed to continue negotiating an end to
hostilities, with both undertaking to include all specific proposal
each sides presents in the agenda at the next round,'' he said.
   Rosa Chavez said the only agreement reached at the three-day
meeting in the town of Moravia, just north of San Jose, was that a
mechanism should be set up to verify future accords are honored.
   The talks, which began Monday with a two-day schedule, had been
extended to Wednesday. But Rosa Chavez said the two sides recessed
the talks after it became apparent there was no way out of the
deadlock.
   Oscar Santamaria, who heads the government delegation, said the
guerrillas had created an ``obstacle to advancement'' by expanding
their proposal.
   The rebels ``divert the discussion from the main theme to other
elements and that number of points make it impossible to go into
the theme of an end to hostilities,'' Santamaria said.
   The guerrillas have proposed a cease-fire, a purge of the armed
forces, respect for human rights and democratic freedoms to lay the
groundwork for their formation of a legal political party.
   President Alfredo Cristiani's government has proposed an
immediate end to fighting and disbanding of rebel forces as a first
step.
   Salvador Samayoa, a rebel representative, accused the government
of inflexibility in the talks.
   ``Substantial agreements appear to be far away. The government
is not prepared to negotiate,'' Samayoa said.
   The first round of talks since Cristiani took office June 1 was
held in September in Mexico City.
   About 70,000 people have been killed in the war, the majority of
them civilians.
</TEXT>
