<DOCNO> AP891018-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 2149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ComebackKid     10-18 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Comeback Kid,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Fights Against The Odds, Writes Note To Mom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two days after a doctor asked
Jennifer Keough's parents to donate the teen-ager's organs after a
car accident, the girl scratched out a message.
   ``I wat to tak to my mom.''
   Barbara Keough had never read a sweeter message.
   ``She's still on the respirator. But that's OK. She's coming
back to me,'' Mrs. Keough said, moments after her 15-year-old
daughter waved and wrote notes to her in the girl's room at
Memorial Hospital.
   It was surprising enough that Jennifer survived Saturday night's
crash after police said she was already dead. But it was even
better news that she began moving her toes and fingers on Monday.
   At 4:55 p.m. Tuesday, intensive care nurse Ron Brezicki called
Mrs. Keough at home with more news.
   ``She did what? She wrote? Holy Cow!'' Mrs. Keough gasped,
clenching the telephone. Her friends turned.
   Screaming, hugging and hand-slapping erupted in the small
apartment.
   Minutes before he called, Brezicki noticed Jennifer stirring,
apparently pointing. He asked if she would be able to write if he
brought her paper and pencil.
   Brezicki asked Jennifer where she lived, what year it was, the
name of the president. Each time she wrote down a correct answer,
except she wrote ``Regan.'' She was reminded there had been an
election, and then she wrote ``Bush.''
   Jennifer, a student at Hollywood Hills High School, also asked
why she was in the hospital and then repeatedly asked about her
friend Jane Valaziotis, 17, who was driving when the car was hit by
another.
   Miss Valaziotis was in stable condition with a broken jaw and
bruises.
   On Saturday, Jennifer's eyes were fixed and dilated when she was
brought to the emergency room, the first sign of possible brain
damage, said Dr. Francisco Pons, who saw her at the hospital.
Another doctor helping to work on the girl asked the teen-ager's
parents to consider donating organs.
   ``Things were looking so bad, we didn't want to give the mother
any hope,'' Pons said, adding that it appeared at the time that the
girl would either die or be brain dead.
   However, Pons said the girl had a strong pulse and pretty good
blood pressure, and he wasn't going to give up on her.
   On Wednesday, Jennifer's condition was upgraded from serious to
stable condition, hospital spokeswoman Linda Hamlin said.
   When he learned of the girl's progress, Pons was visibly shocked.
   ``That's a miracle,'' he said. ``Sometimes there are happy
endings here.''
</TEXT>
