10-18 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Israel-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deal in Works for Tel Aviv-Moscow Flights</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material and editing throughout. CORRECTS to say government
approval would involve separate deal, ADDS Soviet Jewish influx expected.
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Israeli and Soviet national airlines have
reached preliminary agreement toward initiating the first direct
flights between Tel Aviv and Moscow, a spokesman for the Israeli
airline El Al said Wednesday.
   The mass-circulation Yediot Ahronot daily said an agreement was
reached in Moscow this week between El Al's director, Rafi Har-Lev,
and top officials of Aeroflot, the Soviet airline. No starting date
for the flights was given.
   El Al spokesman Nachman Kleiman, reached by telephone, confirmed
that Har-Lev reached a preliminary deal in Moscow. But he said a
separate air agreement would also have to be reached between the
governments of the two countries.
   ``The negotiations still have to be finalized, a few more
details concluded,'' said Kleiman.
   Direct Moscow-Tel Aviv flights would help in an expected influx
of thousands of Soviet immigrants over the next few years, Israel's
consular representative in Moscow, Arieh Levine, said on Israel
television.
   Relations between Israel and East bloc nations have been
improving over the last three years. In 1987, Israel and the Soviet
Union resumed low-level diplomatic ties. Moscow broke diplomatic
ties during the 1967 Middle East War.
</TEXT>
