<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru a0838 10-18 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0838,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes in Bogota's Main Plaza Near Congress, 1 Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, CORRECTING time element in 5th graf pvs, Tuesday's
fragmentation ... and TRIMMING</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A terrorist was killed on Wednesday when
a grenade he was carrying exploded near Congress hours after a
guerrilla amnesty bill was introduced which excludes pardons for
drug traffickers.
   Police said four people were wounded in the midday blast at
Bolivar Plaza in the heart of this capital, about 50 yards from the
Congress building.
   Security forces suspect that scores of bombings in the last two
months were performed by hirelings of the drug traffickers, who are
trying to force Colombia to stop extraditing people wanted as
traffickers in the United States.
   The blast occurred on the first full day of a nationwide strike
by judges, who demanded added protection from attacks mounted by
drug traffickers.
   The fragmentation grenade apparently exploded by accident
Wednesday, witnesses told the Colombian radio networks RCN and
Caracol.
   People at the scene told RCN the man killed was walking rapidly
toward the Congress building when the grenade exploded.
   RCN quoted police as saying the man was also carrying a
submachine gun.
   Nearby is the presidential palace, which serves as the official
residence of President Virgilio Barco.
   It was Barco who rejected appeals by drug traffickers to be
included in the bill that would grant amnesty to leftist guerrillas
of the April 19 Movement.
   The amnesty is part of a negotiated settlement with the rebels,
who take their name from the date of a 1970 presidential election
opponents say was fraudulent.
   The 72-hour judges' strike was declared at noon Tuesday, hours
after a federal judge was shot and killed in Medellin. He was the
42nd judge to be murdered in Colombia in 12 years.
   Drug traffickers, in a telephone call to a Medellin radio
station, said they killed the judge to retaliate for the
extradition of four Colombians to the United States to face charges
related to drug trafficking.
   Also Tuesday, gunmen killed a Medellin radio station news
director. No one claimed responsibility for the slaying, the eighth
news media employee killed since drugrunners started a major
terrorist campaign in mid-August.
   The judges' strike, which crippled Colombia's courts, was
declared by the National Association of Court Workers with 14,000
members, including judges.
   The union president, Federal Judge Helmut Romero, said in a
broadcast interview Wednesday he met the day before with Justice
Minister Roberto Salazar.
   Romero said he was told the government doesn't have money to
fund a special program created two months ago to protect judges.
   Judges who were working had no bulletproof vests, even though
the U.S. Justice Department said two weeks ago it delivered vests
as part of a $19 million program to help protect the judges.
   A union administrator, Yolanda Parra, told The Associated Press
the Justice Ministry had received only 15 vests and even those had
not been turned over to judges yet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
