<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--MusiciansStrike     10-18 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Musicians Strike,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Musicians Union Places City Opera on `Unfair List'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Federation of Musicians has placed
City Opera on an ``unfair list,'' barring union members nationwide
from playing for the company until a contract dispute is resolved.
   Steve Sprague, assistant to the president of the union, said the
move Tuesday was an attempt to get both sides back to the
bargaining table.
   The union's Local 802 began a strike of City Opera on Sept. 13,
opening night of the fall season. The season was canceled Oct. 12
after negotiations broke down.
   The opera was to begin a national tour in January or February.
   ``We don't know at this juncture if the opera is going to be
touring,'' Sprague said.
   The union has 200,000 members across the United States and
Canada. Any union member who plays the City Opera while it is on
the unfair list will be subject to ``internal discipline,'' Sprague
said.
   Spokesmen for the opera did not immediately return telephone
calls.
</TEXT>
