<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 2305EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--SchoolBusExplosion     10-18 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--School Bus Explosion,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical Explosion on School Bus Sends 40 to Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A student mixing chemicals while riding in a
school bus caused an explosion Wednesday that sent 39 children and
the bus driver to hospitals, but no serious injuries were reported,
officials said.
   The children were on their way home from Oriole Park Elementary
School when one boy mixed potassium permanganate, an oxidizing and
bleaching agent that can be used as a disinfectant, with another
chemical, said Martha Tully, a spokeswoman at Resurrection Medical
Center.
   The reaction caused the bottle to explode, releasing fumes
throughout the bus.
   The bus stopped, and ambulances took the children and the bus
driver to various hospitals as a precautionary measure, hospital
officials said. The children ranged in age from 5 to 13.
   The children were released as their parents arrived to pick them
up.
   Some of the children had complained of nausea, stomach aches and
a slight burning sensation, Ms. Tully said.
</TEXT>
