<FIRST>u w AM-SFQuake-FederalResponse 1stLd-Writethru   10-18 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Federal Response, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0745,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Disaster Officials Move Quickly to Aid California</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 14-17: ``Vice President,'' with Quayle report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal disaster officials, stung by criticism
they responded lackadaisically to Hurricane Hugo, moved quickly
Wednesday to speed services to earthquake victims in California.
   Less than 17 hours after an earthquake devastated the San
Francisco Bay area, President Bush declared seven counties federal
disaster areas, clearing the way for them to receive federal
assistance.
   Bush paid a surprise, morale-boosting visit to the headquarters
of the Federal Emergency Management Agency where some workers had
been up all night coordinating the disaster response.
   ``It's important that this emergency machinery operate with
total efficiency,'' Bush told reporters after he received a
30-minute briefing on how 25 federal agencies planned to deal with
the disaster.
   The president defended FEMA, whose response to Hugo was
criticized by members of Congress. Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C.,
said FEMA was a ``bunch of bureaucratic jackasses.''
   ``I thought the response to Hugo was very good,'' Bush told
reporters. ``You can never avoid all criticism.''
   One difference between Hugo, which resulted in disaster
declarations in the U.S. Virgin Islands, Puerto Rico, South
Carolina and North Carolina, and the earthquake was planning,
according to Grant Peterson, FEMA's associate director.
   As recently as last August, the agency, along with state and
local officials, staged a dress rehearsal for an earthquake in
northern California.
   ``We were ready, we practiced for this event, we came on line
very quickly,'' he said.
   But he acknowledged the earthquake came at a bad time for FEMA,
a month after the devastation wreaked by Hugo.
   ``We do have the resources, but we are stressed,'' he said.
Peterson said the agency intends to use some of the $1.1 billion
appropriated by Congress for Hugo to cover earthquake-related
losses.
   Lawmakers will have to replenish the disaster pool when money
runs shorts, as it is expected to do, Peterson said.
   Asked how much will to needed for the earthquake, Peterson said,
``I don't know the cost of this disaster and no one else does.''
   Vice President Dan Quayle said he discussed the importance of
preparation with President Bush by telephone from Air Force Two on
his way back to Washington from inspecting the damage in San
Francisco.
   ``It could have been much worse if we had not had that
preparation,'' Quayle told reporters at Andrews Air Force Base near
Washington.
   ``I do believe it's under control and we are making progress,''
Quayle said.
   He said he also told the president about the importance of
volunteers who swarmed to help the injured and homeless.
   Shortly after the earthquake struck, FEMA personnel set up an
office in San Francisco's Presidio area to supervise federal relief
efforts.
   Other federal disaster offices will open soon to handle requests
from the public. Federal assistance can include temporary housing,
grants of up to $10,000 a family and low-cost loans to cover
uninsured private and business property losses. Red Cross officials
said hundreds of people stayed in federal shelters overnight.
   Local governments can receive money to pay part of the cost of
debris removal and for the replacement of damaged public property.
   California Gov. George Deukmajian activated the National Guard
and Defense Secretary Dick Cheney ordered military hospitals to
treat civilian casualties.
   Among the other federal relief efforts:
   _The Environmental Protection Agency took steps to contain oil
spillage in Richmond, Calif. EPA spokesman Jim Makris said no
environmental contamination had been found and workers at nuclear
plants were confident reactors had not been damaged.
   _The FBI was on call to help identify bodies.
   _The U.S. Geological Survey sent teams to determine the exact
nature of the quake.
   _The Department of Health and Human Services put a team on
stand-by alert even though health facilities were thought to be
sufficient.
   _The Department of Agriculture freed up federal food stored in
warehouses for the school lunch program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
