<FIRST>a w PM-WalterMears ADV19   10-18 0867</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walter Mears, ADV19,0887</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs Oct 19 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gramm-Rudman Cuts Unlikely to Cause Lasting Spending Reductions</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   So the budget ax has fallen on the government
in an act of self-punishment required by law _ but it is more
likely to bounce than to inflict real and lasting cuts in spending.
   That's the way it has worked before under the system of
deadlines and scaled-down deficit ceilings that is supposed to lead
to a balanced budget in 1993. A combination of cuts, revenue
increases and adroit bookkeeping got the numbers within deficit
limits in Senate and House budget bills required by mid-month. But
Congress couldn't settle on a final version in time to meet the
deadline.
   As a result, President Bush ordered sequestration, the fancy
name for $16.1 billion in automatic spending cuts under the
Gramm-Rudman act Congress passed in 1985 as a way to try to force
itself and the administration to deal with the deficit. Congress is
trying to agree on a budget bill that will squeeze the projected
deficit under the limit and supplant the automatic cuts.
   Since the Gramm-Rudman system was enacted, the annual deficit
ceilings it sets have been eased and some costly programs,
including part of the savings and loan bailout, have been designed
to avoid even those limits. One sponsor of the plan, Sen. Ernest F.
Hollings, D-S.C., thinks it has become a sham.
   But the rebuttal is that it beats nothing.
   ``If that law were not in place, federal spending would be
higher today and deficits would be higher today,'' said Sen. Warren
Rudman, R-N.H. His coauthor, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Tex., said
complaints about the measure are like ``the drunk criticizing the
wrench because he can't fix the faucet.''
   That less-than-elegant image is apt for a system devised to
substitute for the political discipline neither Democrats nor
Republicans, neither Congress nor the administration, were imposing
on themselves.
   President Bush, like Ronald Reagan before him, forbids new
taxes. The administration ruled out sharp cuts in defense spending.
Democrats are equally determined to protect domestic program
budgets, notably for the entitlement programs that pay benefits to
individual Americans.
   That adds up to the standoff that led to the Gramm-Rudman
measure, to squeeze down the deficits with progressively lower
ceilings. The target for the government year that began Oct. 1 is a
deficit no higher than $110 billion. It gets a lot tougher next
year, when the target is $64 billion, if it sticks.
   There already is talk of change.
   One way out would be to alter the scorekeeping system so as to
exclude from the deficit arithmetic a growing surplus in the Social
Security trust fund, $68 billion this year. That covers more than
half the deficit in the government's operating budget.
   The amendment now favored by Democratic congressional leaders
would stop counting that surplus, which means operating deficits
would be far higher, and at the same time raise the annual deficit
limits and set 1997 as the target year for a balanced budget.
   But first the government has to cope with the current situation.
The automatic cuts were supposed to be a sort of doomsday mechanism
that would prod the two branches of government into cooperating to
reduce deficits. But this is the third time the sequester sanction
has been imposed, even with the gimmicks that have been used to get
budgets under the Gramm-Rudman limits.
   ``Has the Congress cheated? Has the president, in the best
spirit of bipartisanship, worked with the Congress to cheat?''
Gramm asked. ``The answer is yes.
   ``But are we better off with Gramm-Rudman than we would be
without it? I think the answer is yes, clearly yes,'' he said
Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
   Richard G. Darman, the budget director, says Congress has made
past sequester orders into phonies by rescinding them and putting
all the money back. He's talking about spending cuts that would
stick, even after Congress and the administration settle on a
permanent budget measure. Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman
of the Ways and Means Committee, agrees, saying that spending cuts
should be permanent and painful.
   At the White House, Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said
automatic cuts aren't all bad. ``There would be sizeable cuts and
they would be real,'' he said. ``There wouldn't be any accounting
changes. they'd be real money that wouldn't be spent.''
   But the Gramm-Rudman formula would hit programs the
administration doesn't want cut along with some it would like
reduced. Social Security, aid to the needy and other major federal
spending items are exempt from the cuts, and some other
expenditures, including Medicare, can't be cut by more than 2
percent. What's left is a 4.3 percent cut in defense spending and a
5.3 percent reduction in other domestic programs.
   That gives everybody a stake in a settlement that undoes most if
not all of the automatic cuts. Until next time.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thurs Oct 19 and Thereafter</NOTE>
