<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv20   10-18 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 20,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, Oct. 20, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Minnesota bishops have pledged to
develop a covenant to formalize good relations, encourage ties
between parishes and possibly help intermarried families.
   The agreement was announced recently by Archbishop John Roach of
the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of St. Paul and Minneapolis, Bishop
Lowell Erdahl of the St. Paul Area Synod of the Evangelical
Lutheran Church in America, and Bishop David Olson of the
Minneapolis Area Synod.
   The bishops said they hope a committee of 12 can develop the
covenant in a year. The archdiocese has about 640,000 members, the
synods about 356,000.
   Catholic-Lutheran covenants have been signed in Chicago and
Milwaukee.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evangelist Billy Graham has been given a star
on the Hollywood Walk of Fame in recognition of his 40 years in the
ministry.
   Graham has preached to more than 100 million people in 85
countries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishop William Frey said he has submitted his
resignation as head of the Episcopal Diocese of Colorado to become
president of a church seminary.
   ``Even though it seems the right thing to do, it is not an easy
thing to do,'' Frey said in a letter to the diocese.
   If Frey's resignation is accepted by the Standing Committee and
a majority of bishops, it will take effect next spring as Frey
marks his 18th year in the Colorado diocese.
   The board of trustees of the Trinity Episcopal School for
Ministry in Ambridge, Pa., recently named the 59-year-old Frey as
the successor for the Rev. John Rodgers.
</TEXT>
