<FIRST>r f PM-MarketsRdp Bjt   10-18 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets Rdp, Bjt,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Markets Appear to Stabilize</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will be updated with morning trading.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock markets around the world appeared to be
stabilizing heading into today's trading after a Friday the 13th
shock that caused the second-biggest point drop ever in the Dow
Jones 30-stock industrial average.
   The Dow Jones average lost a moderate 19 points Tuesday after
weathering a late-morning scare that briefly sent it down more than
60 points.
   Tuesday's action was relatively calm after the average plummeted
190 points Friday and then bounced back 88 points Monday.
   Stocks lost little ground Tuesday in spite of continued
uncertainty surrounding a proposed buyout of UAL Corp. and a
government report showing a bigger-than-expected trade deficit in
August. The Federal Reserve helped by adding a modest amount of
reserves to the banking system.
   The Dow average closed with a loss of 18.65 points at 2,638.73,
with 224.07 million shares traded on the New York Stock Exchange,
scarcely more than half Monday's volume.
   In morning trading today in Tokyo, the key Nikkei index rose
moderately.
   Still, traders said the markets were not fully back to normal.
   ``The markets moving as they are here, very emotionally, all
around the world _ it's very difficult really to put any logic
behind the movements,'' said Chung Lew, chief stock trader at the
securities firm Kleinwort Benson Inc. in New York.
   UAL, which made speculators rich on the way up, made a lot of
them poor on the way back down. The stock fell $24.87{ to close at
$198 a share _ two-thirds of its recent peak of $294 a share.
   Traders said the drop in UAL helped drag down the overall
market, which had been pumped up partly by speculation that a
seemingly endless round of debt-financed takeovers would ratchet
stock prices higher.
   The employee-management group that wants to buy the parent of
United Airlines was still trying to put together a deal to replace
the $300-a-share buyout proposal that fell apart last week, sending
the market into its Friday the 13th swoon.
   Most traders said the big trade deficit, while bad news, had
relatively little effect on the market. The Commerce Department
said the August deficit rose about 31 percent to $10.77 billion
from a revised July deficit of $8.24 billion.
   The dollar spiked downward but quickly recovered after the trade
report in a surprising show of strength that helped soothe
investors in the stock market. Bonds gave up some early gains to
finish mixed.
   The Federal Reserve pumped $1.5 billion into the banking system
to make sure banks had enough reserves to make emergency loans to
any traders who lost big in the market's gyrations. It had injected
$2 billion in reserves Monday.
   By adding reserves the Federal Reserve is cheering up investors
who say the central bank has endangered the economy by being too
stingy with the money supply. But the Fed has acted very cautiously
and there has been no decisive downward move in the federal funds
rate, which it influences. This rate is the interest charged when a
bank loans money overnight to another bank to enable it to meet
reserve requirements.
   At times it appeared Tuesday that the stock market was being
pulled around by the stock-index futures market in Chicago, where
rises and falls tend to be exaggerated because it takes less money
to bet on the direction of the market. The swings in Chicago were
transmitted to the stock market in New York through computerized
program trading that exploited price discrepancies between them.
</TEXT>
