<FIRST>r f PM-BankersTrust     10-18 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bankers Trust,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takes Big Hit on Third World Loans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bankers Trust New York Corp., one of the largest
U.S. banks, said it set aside an additional $1.6 billion to cover
possibly bad Third World loans, drastically reducing its exposure
to risky debts.
   The move Tuesday by the nation's eighth-largest banking company
will result in a third-quarter loss of $1.42 billion, as well as a
still-undetermined loss for all of 1989. A detailed earnings report
is scheduled to be released Monday.
   Bankers Trust's decision mirrors action taken recently by a
handful of other big banks, which also reported big quarterly
losses.
   Bankers Trust and the others attributed their protective moves
to intensifying political and economic problems in debtor nations,
such as Argentina and Brazil, as well as a growing sentiment in
Washington toward forgiving some past debts.
   ``Recent events, including the outcome of Mexican debt
negotiations and the periodic suspensions of timely payments of
interest by other countries ... had the effect of reducing the
value of LDC loans,'' Chairman Charles S. Sanford Jr. said in a
statement.
   ``While reduction of interest and principal can allow time for
adjustment, only sound economic policies on the part of debtor
countries can provide a solution.''
   The $1.6 billion special provision brings Bankers Trust's
allowance for credit losses to $2.9 billion, or around 85 percent
of its medium- to long-term outstanding Third World loans.
   That's the second-largest percentage, behind J.P. Morgan &amp; Co.,
which said in September it had bolstered reserves cover all
medium-to long-term loans.
   The average percentage of protection among most banks that have
loaned money to Third World countries is 58 percent.
   Analysts say that many of the major banks that have begun facing
up to the likelihood of huge losses of loans to developing
countries, known as LDC loans, are unlikely to resume large-scale
lending to those nations for many years.
   Bankers Trust said in its statement that it would ``continue to
apply its merchant banking skills in ways that are useful to the
public and private sectors'' of Third World countries. However, it
made no mention of lending more money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
