<DOCNO> AP891018-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0132EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Markets-Volatility Bjt   10-18 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets-Volatility, Bjt,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Market Whipsawed Amid Program Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shortly after 10 a.m. Monday, a stock futures
contract tracking 20 big corporations shot higher in Chicago.
   Boom.
   A wave of computer-generated program trading orders to buy
stocks kicked in and the broader stock market stampeded upward. In
a stunning 15-minute reversal, the Dow Jones industrials average
moved from 63 points down to 6 points up.
   The gyrations from the market's Friday the 13th plunge showed
that big swings in the Chicago futures market can translate into
equally large movements in the stocks in New York via computerized
program trading, which was widely criticized for worsening the 1987
stock market crash.
   ``They kept pushing as the day went on,'' Donald Selkin, head of
stock-index futures research at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.,
said Tuesday. ``The programs I'd say we're a good part of the
advance.''
   The practice of moving millions of shares of stock with
lightning speed was voluntarily limited by stock exchanges and
brokerage houses in the wake of the Oct. 19, 1987, crash, but
gradually has been revived this year.
   After Friday's 190-point decline, some analysts speculated that
the New York Stock Exchange over the weekend encouraged firms to
avoid using computerized ``sell'' programs that could spur a
disastrous plunge, but to step in with buy orders if possible that
could propel the market higher. The exchange declined to comment on
the matter Tuesday.
   Program trading is a strategy involving the stock-index futures
market in Chicago and stock trading in New York. Stock-index
futures are contracts to buy or sell baskets of stocks at specified
prices by a specified date.
   In one form called index arbitrage, the strategy employs
computers to buy and sell huge blocks of stocks and index futures
in an attempt to profit from minute differences in prices on the
two markets. The practice can cause rapid price swings and is
believed by some to have accelerated the 1987 market collapse.
   But defenders complain that the strategy is used as a scapegoat
for sometime-normal market fluctuations.
   ``There's always fish in a tidal wave because there's always
fish in the water,'' said R. Steven Wunsch, vice president of
financial futures at Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co., one of Wall Street's
heaviest program trading firms.
   ``Buyers and sellers in an outright fashion move markets,'' he
said. ``Those who are buying and selling simultaneously don't cause
volatility. Taken all together it's a non-influence.''
   Wunsch instead blamed market volatility on an overdependence on
intermediate dealers whose job is to bring together buyers and
sellers.
   A presidential task force known as the Brady Commission that
invesigated the 1987 crash concluded that index arbitagers were
active at times of big price swings but didn't cause the crash.
   After the crash, some firms reduced their program trading levels
because of intense criticism by politicians and others _ Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. abandoned the practice altogether _ but there
has been a revival this year, officials said.
   The sharp price swings Friday and Monday intensified debate over
index arbitrage. NYSE Chairman John J. Phelan Jr. said program
trading accounted for 24 million of 100 million shares traded in
the final 1{ hours of trading Friday.
   ``We would say that it was abundant, but we wouldn't say it was
something that precipitated the market decline,'' he said.
   When the markets opened Monday, stock-index futures were trading
at a discount to the underlying stocks. Stock prices sank in the
first half-hour of trading. Buying of Major Market Index futures of
the 20 stocks soon pulled the futures market higher, and buy
programs kicked in. A similar action triggered buying on ``Terrible
Tuesday,'' Oct. 20, 1987.
   Some players said Wall Street's major brokerages should step in
with programs to help stem a decline.
   ``I think they should be in there all the time taking the market
up,'' said John J. Cramer, president of the New York money
management firm Cramer &amp; Co. ``Whenever the big sell programs come
in I think the powers that be ought to be in there taking it back
up.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0144EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Markets-WallStreetJobs     10-18 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets-Wall Street Jobs,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Since The Big Crash: Fewer Jobs But Better Pay on Wall Street</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Markets Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers on Wall Street are earning more money
than ever _ if they're still working.
   A federal report Tuesday said 15,000 securities industry
employees here have lost their jobs since the stock market crash of
October 1987. For those who survived, however, average pay was
nearly $79,000 last year.
   That was a 13 percent salary increase over 1987, and it came to
more than 2.5 times the average annual pay for all private
employees in New York City.
   The report, by the regional Bureau of Labor Statistics, said New
York's economy was not devastated by the 1987 crash, as some
feared. But employment has been essentially flat since the crash,
after a decade of growth.
   ``The post-crash record has clearly not been the disaster widely
touted by the forecasts and in the headlines in the early months
following Black Monday,'' the report said. ``But it does close out
a period of unprecedented private sector job expansion, marking a
distinct break with the past.''
   Samuel Ehrenhalt, regional commissioner of labor statistics,
said the stock market's more recent gyrations were part of an
ongoing restructuring in the securities industry.
   ``The stock market crash two years ago marked the end of the
resurgence of the '80s and the beginning of a transition that's
still taking shape,'' said Ehrenhalt. ``What you're seeing now is a
continuation of structural changes on Wall Street. That process
hasn't reached its end point.''
   At the same time, Wall Street's rising salaries indicated ``a
good deal of vitality,'' Ehrenhalt said. Average annual pay in the
securities industry in the city has risen from $19,317 in 1975 to
$78,625 last year.
   The figures indicated that securities workers laid off since the
crash were the least productive and lowest paid, Ehrenhalt said.
   The securities industry in New York now employs 146,000 people,
down from a peak of 163,000 in December 1987. Hiring momentum
carried it to its peak two months after the crash of Oct. 19, 1987.
   Before the crash, Wall Street employment had increased by an
average of 12,000 jobs a year since the early 1980s.
   The banking industry also lost jobs as a result of the 1987
market crash, with employment falling by 9,500 in the past two
years, the agency said. Banking jobs had been declining before the
crash, but far more slowly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CommoditiesReform Bjt   10-18 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Reform, Bjt,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exchange Heads Warn About Reforms' Effects on Competitiveness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top officials of the nation's four largest
futures exchanges told a Senate committee that some proposed market
reforms could drive their business overseas.
   At the same hearing Tuesday, the head of the agency that
oversees the futures markets said the proposed legislation gives
the markets more power than they want.
   Wendy L. Gramm, chairwoman of the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission, said her agency neither needs nor wants authority to
conduct undercover operations like the one that resulted in 46
indictments this summer in Chicago's freewheeling commodities
trading pits.
   ``I believe the current situation with the FBI having the
authority is sufficient,'' Ms. Gramm told the Senate Agriculture,
Nutrition and Forestry Committee, which is considering legislation
to reform the futures markets and reauthorize financing for the
CFTC, which oversees them.
   Ms. Gramm also said:
   _She believed that 17 of the indicted Chicago traders still were
working in the pits, including some handling customer orders. She
expressed concern about it but said the regulatory agency had to
balance that against the rights of the accused. ``They're indicted.
They haven't been tried and convicted.''
   _Temporary trading halts, known as ``circuit breakers,'' and
other market safeguards implemented since the 1987 stock market
crash ``appeared to work as designed'' during Friday's stock market
plunge. She also said she was satisfied with inter-market
communication during the stock slide.
   _There was no need to give the CFTC power to order crooked
brokers to pay restitution to customers they have cheated. ``A
majority of the commission believes current law provides sufficient
recourse for customers to obtain reimbursement of losses when funds
are available,'' she said.
   At the same hearing, officials of the Chicago Board of Trade,
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, the New York Mercantile Exchange
and the New York-based Commodity Exchange warned senators that
tougher record-keeping standards and service fees mandated by the
bill could make them uncompetitive with foreign markets.
   In addition to undercover probes and broker restitution, the
proposed Futures Trading Practices Act of 1989 would require
stricter record-keeping by market participants to ``independently,
precisely and completely'' record transaction times.
   At issue is the ``audit trail,'' an accurate record of any given
transaction that would allow investigators to determine if it
reflected what really happened and if the transaction followed the
rules.
   The General Accounting Office, the investigatory arm of the
Congress, has found that current record-keeping on most exchanges
is inadequate to prevent fraud because so much of it is orginated
by traders themselves _ often by hand.
   The bill also calls for financing stepped-up floor surveillance
through service fees, which several exchanges have criticized as a
secret tax.
   ``The worst outcome of this reauthorization process,'' said BOT
Chairman Karsten Mahlmann, would be to use the Chicago indictments
as an excuse ``for imposing audit trail standards utterly
incompatible with a liquid market or raising costs of access to our
customers by imposing new and unwarranted taxes on our markets.''
   He added that new fees ``could constitute a crushing burden and
competitive handicap'' against foreign markets that aren't as
restricted.
   The bill is sponsored by Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., the
committee chairman, and Sen. Richard G. Lugar of Indiana, the
panel's ranking Republican.
   Futures contracts are agreements to deliver a quantity of goods
at a specified price at a certain time in the future. They are used
by producers of such commodities as soybeans or gold to lock in a
favorable price, while speculators buy and sell those contracts in
pursuit of a profit.
   ``During this past year,'' said Leahy, ``regulation of the
futures industry has lurched from crisis to crisis.''
   In addition to the undercover FBI probe that resulted in the
Chicago indictments, a separate probe of futures exchanges in New
York was disclosed in May.
   In July, the CBOT issued an emergency order requiring traders to
slash their holdings in soybeans futures contracts. The order
touched off wild fluctuations in soybean prices.
   A bill also containing futures market reform was passed by the
House last month. Both bills seek to limit dual trading, the
controversial _ but legal _ practice that allows traders to conduct
transactions for their own accounts as well as those of their
customers.
   Ms. Gramm said a study by her agency found dual trading does not
have the impact on futures markets that its supporters have claimed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
