<DOCNO> AP891018-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0150EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AirlineData     10-18 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airline Data,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Airline Group Signs Contract For Data System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Air Transport Association
has announced an agreement for a computer-based system officials
said should increase airline profits and help passengers fly where
they want with less difficulty.
   The system to manage airline seat inventories is already used by
several U.S. airlines.
   IATA, which represents the world's scheduled airlines, will make
it available for a fee to both large and small carriers throughout
the world, officials said Tuesday.
   By keeping track of seat use and passenger demand, the system
developed by Control Data Corp. of Minneapolis allows airlines to
make the best use of available seats, both in terms of revenue and
service, said Gary E. Campbell of Control Data.
   He said the system enables a large or small airline to project
how many seats it can sell in various categories for each flight
and could help the company in making decisions about advertising
and the number and size of planes to use on its routes.
   For passengers, it will mean less of a chance of getting bumped
off of a flight and a better chance of getting a ticket for the
flight desired, Campbell said.
   The price an airline pays for the service will be determined by
the number of passengers it carries, and the system can be applied
either to selected flights or to all of the flights the airline
operates, said Geoffrey Bailey, who will manage the system for IATA
in Geneva.
   Information, including seats available for each flight, would be
constantly updated by the airlines that participate and made
available to travel agents throughout the world, he said.
   ``What this could lead to is a situation where you could go into
a travel agent and say, `I've got $50 and I want to fly from
Washington to Miami. What can you do for me?''' said Bailey. While
such a flight may not be immediately available, he said, the agent
might be able to find an airline willing to take the passenger.
   Bailey said such systems have increased an airline's overall
revenue by from 5 percent to 11 percent by reducing the number of
unused seats and helping it to set realistic fares for business and
personal travel.
   The price IATA paid for the license to lease the system to its
member airlines was not disclosed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
