<DOCNO> AP891018-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0150EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-US-JapanTrade     10-18 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Japan Trade,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Sees No Massive Trade Deficit Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills said
that new economic talks with Japan should produce a plan for
action, but no massive cut by next year in the U.S. trade deficit
with Japan.
   The two countries have agreed to make a final report next July
on their talks to remove ``structural impediment'' barriers to
trade between the United States and Japan.
   The talks began in Tokyo last month and are to continue, off and
on, until next summer.
   Even by then, Mrs. Hills cautioned Tuesday, ``it will be very
hard to say'' that the negotiators have achieved ``a massive
reduction in the deficit.''
   Mrs. Hills was asked at a news conference how she would cope
with growing sentiment in Congress for negotiated market shares, or
managed trade, if there is no easing of the U.S. deficit with
Japan. That hortfall has been running at more than $50 billion a
year.
   ``I am against managed trade,'' she said. ``I think you sell
yourself short when you decree that a group of bureaucrats can
decide you are entitled to 5 or 10 per cent of a market. In almost
every market where we agreed to a percentage, ... I feel
shortchanged. I think we could do better,'' she added.
   Echoing President Bush's declaration that the talks would be ``a
two-way street,'' the Japanese are pressing the United States to
improve its education and competitiveness and raise savings
deposits and investment.
   In Tokyo, she said, the Japanese side ``was impressed'' with
facts and figures produced by the United States to bolster
complaints against traditional Japanese systems of distribution,
pricing, land use, business collusion and bidding, all of which the
United States says discriminate against foreign products.
   ``It is a win-win situation,'' not a question of dictating to
each other, she said, because there is little dispute about the
potential gains of eliminating the shortcomings that have been
identified in each country.
   Early action on the Japanese side, she said, could take the form
of tightening enforcement of laws already on the books. At the
current enforcement level, there is little incentive not to engage
in business collusion, she said, and the Japanese Fair Trade
Commission needs more funds.
   The commission last fined a business in the 1970s and took no
action at all last year, she said, in contrast to the U.S. Justice
Department, which in 1988 filed 200 criminal actions and fined U.S.
businesses $30 million.
</TEXT>
