<DOCNO> AP891018-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0208EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-DirtBricks Bjt   10-18 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dirt Bricks, Bjt,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Pitches Dirt-Cheap Solution to Global Housing Crunch</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Terra Block'' is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company virtually unknown in North America may
hold the remedy to the Soviet Union's severe housing shortage by
literally building from the ground up.
   Terra Block Worldwide, which was dirt-poor five years ago, has
hit the motherlode in the Soviet Union with its simple hydraulic
compressor that converts regular soil into sturdy adobe-like
construction bricks.
   The Orlando-based company received Soviet orders for 2,000 of
its $75,000 Terrablock Duplex Machines following a visit to Moscow
earlier this year by company founder Robert Gross.
   ``We're getting inquiries from the Soviet Union nearly every
day,'' said Gross, a retired National Aeronautics and Space
Administration engineer. ``We can't make the machines quickly
enough.''
   Gross said Terra Block now must divert nearly all its focus
toward the Soviet Union, where the era of perestroika has eased
trade restrictions with the West.
   ``The Soviets face an incredible housing crunch. Sometimes there
are three families sharing a flat no bigger than a studio
apartment,'' said Gross, 57, who spends nearly half the year
traveling abroad. ``This is something that Gorbachev has set as a
priority. We just happened to be the right company at the right
place at the right political time.''
   Gross said the machine was inspired by a trip to Arizona in the
1970s, when he studied homes constructed of hand-made adobe.
Properly built adobe structures offer a natural insulation and are
extremely durable, such as the 900-year-old Taos Pueblo in New
Mexico.
   But the weeks needed to dry the adobe bricks in the sun made
large-scale modern projects impractical.
   Gross then began work on a prototype compression machine that
used computerized hydraulic rams to squeeze dirt into building
blocks. The production-model Terrablock Duplex churns out up to 600
30-pound blocks an hour using less than a gallon of diesel fuel.
   The bricks, formed under nearly 500,000 pounds-per-square-inch
pressure, are stacked without mortar and covered with a
plaster-based coating. The structures have passed all international
seismic and stress tests, said Gross.
   Terra Block spokesman Steve Buntell said the bricks can be used
for buildings up to two stories high.
   Several other brick-making machines are in use in the Third
World, but Buntell said they require additives such as concrete and
operate more slowly.
   In 1985, the company sold just one machine, to the west African
nation of Gabon. Today there are about 50 machines in use, mostly
in Africa and Asia. Four machines have been sold in the United
States, including one to the Hare Krishna sect for its proposed
headquarters in Tennessee.
   ``We haven't found any soil yet that won't work,'' said Gross,
nicknamed ``Dr. Dirt'' by co-workers. ``The sandier the soil, the
more pressure needed. But we've made blocks from soil in Saudi
Arabia that was almost all sand. Even in winter we can dig below
the frozen surface to useable dirt.''
   The $150 million Terrablock deal with the Soviet Union offers an
insight into the nation's changing economic policies, he said.
While the state-run construction ministry acts as a liaison,
individual community-based cooperatives can put in orders for a
machine if they come up with hard currency, such as dollars.
   When an order is placed, the money is transferred directly into
Terra Block's account in an Amsterdam-based bank, said Gross.
   Carl McMillian, a Soviet trade expert at Carlton University in
Ottawa, said the Soviet government is becoming more aggressive in
seeking needed goods, including housing.
   ``If they want it bad enough then there's a way to come up with
the hard cash,'' he said.
   Last year, the Soviets imported $26.4 billion worth of Western
goods and exported $22.9 billion in goods to the West, said
McMillian.
   Terra Block's plans call for about 100 machines to be shipped to
the Soviet Union by the end of the year.
   ``The deal with the Soviets was a breakthrough for us,'' said
Buntell. ``It really gave a push to the dream of becoming the
world's largest home builder.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0249 </DOCNO>
