<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   10-18 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Officials Say Airline Rebuilding Faster Than Expected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines says it is
rebuilding faster than it had projected last spring and should
emerge larger than expected from bankruptcy reorganization, but two
of its unions questioned the carrier's long-term stability.
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp., and
Phil Bakes, Eastern's president, said a combination of lower labor
costs and a level of public acceptance that is enabling the airline
to fill ``a very healthy percentage '' of its seats have helped the
airline rebuild.
   ``We are well along on our road of rebuilding the airline,''
Lorenzo told a news conference Tuesday.
   Lorenzo also said the company was continuing to discuss an
amended plan of reorganization with its creditors and expected to
file it shortly. He said he remained committed to paying creditors
``100 cents on the dollar.''
   But spokesmen for two of the unions that have been on strike
against the Miami-based airline since March 4 said Eastern
continues to face serious competitive problems.
   Eastern filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of
the federal bankruptcy laws shortly after being hit by the strike
by its Machinists union, pilots and flight attendants.
   The company said it would have 85 percent to 90 percent of
pre-strike operations when it emerges from bankruptcy protection
early next year. Its earlier target was to emerge at 60 percent to
65 percent of pre-strike operations.
   The airline expects to surpass its earlier goal of having about
820 daily flights in December, and should have 1,000 flights a day
by late spring, compared with 1,050 before the strike.
   Those figures exclude its Northeast shuttle service that Eastern
sold to developer Donald Trump for $365 million earlier this year.
   But Wally Haber, senior general chairman District 100
Machinists, which represents all Eastern Machinists members, said
he had doubts about whether Eastern will be able to meet its new
goals for flights.
   ``We know they are extremely short of aircraft mechanics,'' he
said. ``We just don't think they can get the Machinists to support
the type of flight levels they are talking about.''
   The Air Line Pilots Association, meanwhile, said that although
Eastern presnted itself ``all gussied up in new clothes and fresh
makeup'' at the news conference, the airline ``still is facing a
doubtful future as a survivor in the highly competitive airline
market.''
   Among Eastern's continuing problems, the pilots group said, are
financial shortfalls, chronic shortages and other problems in
maintenance and pilot training, vulnerability to an economic
downturn and an aging fleet.
   Bakes declined to comment on how much money Eastern was losing
but said he expects the airline to be profitable in 1990.
   Bakes said Eastern will operate a fleet of 188 planes next
spring, compared with the 157 it projected initially.
   The company also said it had a work force of 17,300, compared
with 31,200 before the strike. Eastern has hired replacement pilots
and some have crossed picket lines.
   Eastern expects to surpass its projection of 750 daily flights
by November and fly 775 to 80 cities. It expects to fly 835 daily
flights in December, up from an earlier projection of 820.
   Eastern now is flying about 700 flights a day.
   Eastern said it intends to maintain a strong international
presence, providing service to South and Central America, Mexico
and the Caribbean.
   Atlanta has been restored as Eastern's major hub, the company
said, and Eastern should again be Miami's largest carrier this
winter.
</TEXT>
