<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-18 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls In Europe, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in early European trading today,
pushed lower by news of the San Francisco earthquake and the
higher-than-expected U.S. trade deficit, dealers said.
   Gold rose in moderate trading, boosted by the weaker dollar and
higher oil prices which dealers said were lifted by concern that
the earthquake could affect the U.S. West Coast oil industry.
   Foreign exchange dealers said they expected the earthquake to
have little further impact on the dollar beyond its minor early
drop.
   Traders said the market was waiting for further developments on
the New York Stock Exchange following Tuesday's news that the U.S.
trade deficit in August was $10.8 billion, about $1.7 billion worse
than expected, and will closely follow the movement of the Dow
Jones stock index.
   ``The dollar is hanging on the Dow Jones,'' said Jens-Uwe
Fischer, senior trader at Manufacturers Hanover bank in Frankfurt.
``As long as the Dow remains steady, I think we'll see a slightly
firmer dollar.''
   Other traders expected the dollar's near-term movement to be
lower, but agreed that its fate was largely tied to the New York
market.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.15 yen to a closing 142.10 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at a lower rate of 141.40 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's
prices, included: 1.8470 West German marks, down from 1.8520;
1.6215 Swiss francs, down from 1.6227; 6.2810 French francs, down
from 6.2960; 2.0970 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0867; 1,361.50
Italian lire, down from 1,365.00; 1.1725 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1755.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5905 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.5835 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $368 a troy ounce, up
from late Tuesday's $367.75. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $368.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $368, up from $367.50 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.72 to close at a bid $368.38.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.12 a troy
ounce, unuchanged from late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
