<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-18 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Gain, Dollar Slips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index gained
moderately in calm trading today, nearly regaining its level before
the Wall Street plunge, while the dollar inched down against the
Japanese yen.
   The dollar closed at 142.10 yen, down 0.15 yen from Tuesday's
142.25-yen close. It opened at 142.55 yen and ranged between 142.05
yen and 142.63 yen.
   The dollar had gained 1.50 yen Tuesday after its 3.25-yen plunge
the previous day.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 111.48 points, or 0.32
percent, to 35,107.56. On Tuesday, it had gained 527.39 points, the
second-largest one-day gain this year after a 793.96 point advance
on March 28.
   Together, the gains of Tuesday and today nearly erased Monday's
647.33-point loss _ this year's largest one-day decline _ which
followed a big tumble on Wall Street on Friday.
   ``The market was calm and strong as players were reassured by
stability in foreign exchange rates despite America's worsened
trade deficit,'' said Masayoshi Yano, a Nikko Securities dealer.
   The deficit, reported by the U.S. Commerce Department on
Tuesday, rose to $10.77 billion in August, up from a revised $8.24
billion in July.
   Cautious investors stayed away from issues sensitive to interest
and foreign currency rates, Yano said.
   He said Japanese stock trading was not affected by news of a
severe earthquake, with heavy casualties, in the San Francisco area.
   ``If the New York market falls in reaction to the earthquake, it
may have some effects in Tokyo tomorrow,'' Yano added.
   Trading was fairly active, with first section volume estimated
at 800 million shares, up from Tuesday's 650 million.
   Currency dealings were calm and ``boring,'' said Mitsuhiko
Kinugasa, a senior trader with Daiwa Bank.
   ``Many participants were curious why the dollar remained so
strong above the 142-yen level even after the report of a large
(U.S.) trade deficit, but the basic trend here is to maintain the
dollar's stability,'' he said.
   Considering such factors as the trade deficit and Friday's stock
plunge, however, the dollar will turn downward sooner or later, he
said.
</TEXT>
