<HEAD>Stocks Advance in London</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: updates throughout with later trading, details.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices cast aside recent gloom to post solid
gains today.
   At midday, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index
was 17.9 points, or 0.8 percent, higher at 2,153.4 points.
   Volume was a healthy 239.9 million shares compared with 360.2
million shares at the same time Tuesday.
   Insurance stocks, which some equity analysts forecast might be
heavily hit by the earthquake disaster in San Francisco, were
showing only narrow losses.
   Buyers were tempted to return by an upward trend in the
Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index futures contract,
dealers said.
   In late morning, the contract was trading at a 12-point premium
to the underlying market, against a recent trend to trade at a
discount.
   Despite the swing into positive territory, dealers said the
market remained edgy in case Wall Street opened weakly.
   ``If so, London will be dragged lower,'' one dealer said.
   Dealers said the market remained nervous because it could be
swung so violently by shifts in sentiment. ``The market could crack
at any moment,'' said one London dealer. ``There isn't enough
institutional interest to help the market steady.''
