   Stocks turned higher, reversing course after a
brief, initial selloff today, as trading activity slowed from a
recently brisk pace.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, down about 12
points in the first 30 minutes of trading, posted a gain of 3.69 at
2,642.42 by 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Advancing issues had overtaken declining ones on the New York
Stock Exchange where 638 stocks were up in price, 541 were down and
545 were unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 60.49 million
shares after ninety minutes of trading.
   The NYSE composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.54 to 189.43.
   Activity on Wall Street seemed more subdued compared with the
volatile trading that prevailed for the past three sessions,
starting with Friday when the Dow Jones industrial average plunged
190 points.
   Despite worries about the negative impact California's
catastrophic earthquake might have on some companies, insurance and
technology stocks were holding up well.
   Travelers rose \ to 40[ and there were scattered gains for other
insurers.
   Among some heavily trading over-the-counter technology stocks,
Apple added { to 47} and Microsoft rose 1] to 80.
   Pacific Gas &amp; Electric fell ] to 19|.
   The turbulence in the stock market lately had been intensified
by confusion surrounding a proposed buyout of UAL. A tumble in
shares of the parent of United Airlines helped trigger Friday's
megadrop.
   The slide in UAL slowed as the stock lost 3 to 195. The selling
apparently was in reaction to word that Los Angeles financier
Marvin Davis has withdrawn his backup $300-a-share, all-cash bid
for United Airlines' parent.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph led the Big Board's list of
actively traded shares, falling [ to 42[.
   Meanwhile, new evidence of weakening economic activity led to
speculation that a significant slowdown might be a serious drag on
corporate profits.
   Before the market opened, the Commerce Department said housing
construction fell 5.2 percent in September to the lowest level
since the 1982 recession.
