<HEAD>Grain Futures Open Mixed; Soviet Soybean Talk Persists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade with the
main support stemming from persistent rumors that the Soviet Union
is shopping for soybeans.
   Talk of Soviet interest in U.S. soybeans and soybean meal helped
lift soybean and soybean meal futures sharply on Tuesday.
   Corn futures opened slightly higher but quickly turned mixed.
   Wheat futures were slightly lower in a follow-through from
yesterday's modest decline. An Agriculture Department announcement
that Egypt had bought 225,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at
subsidized prices was initially perceived as bullish but traders
later said the amount was less than expected.
   Forecasts for more harvest-hampering rain today and tomorrow in
the Midwest were seen as slightly bullish for the corn and soybean
markets, although clearing skies and warmer conditions are expected
by the weekend.
   In early trading, wheat futures were { cent to 1{ cents lower
with the contract for December delivery at $4.08 a bushel; corn
futures were { cent lower to { cent higher with December at $2.38}
a bushel; oats were { cent higher across the board with December at
$1.44\ a bushel; soybeans were { cent to 4\ cents higher November
at $5.57 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .22 cent lower to .28 cent higher with October
at 73.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent lower to .07
cent higher with October at 83.15 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent
to .57 cent higher with October at 48.57 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were unchanged to .25 cent lower with February at 52.30
cents a pound.
   All livestock and meat futures settled higher on Tuesday with
pork bellies up sharply.
