<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1159EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Chemicals     10-18 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Chemicals,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monsanto Up 9 Percent, Dow Down 7 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Chemical Co. said Wednesday that third-quarter earnings fell
7 percent on lower demand for polyethylene, while Monsanto Co. said
its profits rose 9 percent with strong showings by its chemical and
Nutrasweet divisions.
   Dow, based in Midland, Mich., reported net income of $589
million, or $3.29 a share, for the three months ended Sept. 30,
down from $632 million, or $3.36 a share, in the 1988 third quarter.
   Sales for the period reached $4.25 billion, up 2 percent from
$4.15 billion a year earlier, the company said.
   For the first nine months of 1989, Dow reported net income of
$2.06 billion, or $11.41 a share, on sales of $13.34 billion, up
from $1.76 billion, or $9.38 a share, on sales of $12.38 billion in
the same period last year.
   Demand for polyethylene used in items from plastic wrap to milk
jugs was short and prices were higher in the quarter so prices
fell, Dow spokeswoman Sarah Opperman said.
   Dow's third-quarter revenue from plastics fell 4 percent, while
revenue from chemicals grew 5 percent and consumer specialties such
as Seldane antihistamine grew more than 11 percent, the company
said.
   St. Louis-based Monsanto, a diversified company that also owns
Searle pharmaceuticals, reported net income of $126 million, or
$1.88 per share, on sales of $2.06 billion. That compared with
earnings of $116 million, or $1.67 a share, on sales of $2.02
billion for the same 1988 period.
   Monsanto's chemicals division reported operating income of $117
million, up from $96 million in the 1988 third quarter. NutraSweet
showed operating income of $39 million, up from $27 million a year
ago.
   Monsanto's crop chemicals and animals sciences agricultural
divisions reported operating income of $57 million, down from $78
million in the 1988 quarter. The drop was attributed to drought
conditions in Europe and the western United States.
   For the first three quarters of 1989, Monsanto reported earnings
of $589 million, or $8.66 per share, on sales of $6.67 billion.
That compared with earnings of $546 million, or $7.57 per share, on
sales of $6.41 billion in the first nine months of 1988.
</TEXT>
