<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1200EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Pepperell-CluettPeabody     10-18 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pepperell-Cluett Peabody,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cluett Deal Viewed as Step Toward Completing Farley-Pepperell Acquisition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textile industry analysts were trying to
determine whether the proposed $600 million sale of three Cluett,
Peabody &amp; Co. manufacturing divisions to a French company would
significantly cut debt from Farley Inc.'s acquisition of West
Point-Pepperell Inc.
   Cluett, the makers of Arrow shirts, Gold Toe socks and
Schoeneman suits, is a division of Georgia-based Pepperell, which
was acquired by Chicago-based Farley in a $3 billion debt-financed
deal earlier this year.
   Bidermann Industries USA, a subsidiary of the Paris-based
Bidermann Group, a fashion and apparel firm, is acquiring the major
Cluett manufacturing divisions under an agreement announced Monday.
   Farley has for months been expected to sell Cluett to pare the
debt from the Pepperell deal. Farley reportedly sought up to $800
million for the Cluett divisions, although some analysts have
placed their value as low as $450 million.
   ``He (Farley) almost certainly got less than he wanted,'' said
Don Hogsett, business editor of Home Textiles Today, a trade
publication. ``The question remains how does he pare down his debt.
Will he have to sell more?''
   Farley spokesman Jack Albertine was traveling Tuesday and could
not be reached for comment. Messages left through his secretary in
Chicago were not returned.
   Roy Bowen, executive vice president of the Georgia Textile
Manufacturing Association, said it was difficult to predict what
Farley might do next to secure cash for the Pepperell deal.
   ``A lot has happened in the debt markets since he acquired West
Point,'' he said.
   Bowen said the Bidermann deal should not have much effect on
Pepperell's operations because Cluett is in the apparel sector
rather than in Pepperell's main textile business.
   ``This doesn't detract at all from West Point's standing as a
major textile company,'' he said.
   Applauding the deal was the Amalgamated Clothing &amp; Textile
Workers Union, which itself made a bid for Cluett during the summer.
   ``We're very pleased,'' said Garry Ferraris, an ACTWU vice
president in Knoxville, Tenn. ``It (Bidermann) looks like a company
that's on a solid financial slate and putting up enough cash so it
won't be so leveraged.''
   The sale to Bidermann, subject to regulatory approval, is
expected to be completed by the end of November.
</TEXT>
