<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1200EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Quake-OilPrices 1stLd-Writethru f0042 10-18 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0042,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Oil Companies Report Some Delays In Quake Aftermath</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede PM-LONDON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with major U.S. oil companies reporting
Northern California slowdowns from quake. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Chevron Corp. said today that the devastating Northern
California earthquake forced it to shut two major oil pipelines
that distribute gasoline, jet oil and other products throughout the
area.
   Exxon Corp. and Texaco Inc., meanwhile, reported minor problems,
including power outages, but said their facilities were continuing
to operate at near normal capacity.
   Chevron spokesman Hal Holt said the hundreds of miles of
pipeline flowing from its Richmond, Calif., refinery northeast of
San Francisco to various distribution terminals in and around the
Bay area were closed as a precautionary measure and would reopen
after inspection.
   He said no shortages were expected and the Santa Fe and Bay Area
pipelines could resume normal operations later in the day.
   ``They will be visually inspected. There are no reports of
leakage along those lines,'' Holt said today from Chevron's East
Bay offices in Richmond.
   The quake was not affecting oil futures prices in early New York
Mercantile Exchange activity, traders said. Just before midday, the
November contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade
of U.S. crude, was trading at $20.74 a barrel, down 1 cent from
Tuesday.
   Gasoline for November delivery was down 0.19 cent to 55.84 cents
a gallon to 55.84 cents a gallon and domestic heating oil was down
0.50 cent at 61.05 cents a gallon.
   Holt said the quake also jolted Chevron's 315,000 barrel-a-day
refinery but the plant returned to normal operations early today
after some equipment automatically shut down due to vibrations. He
said the refinery, which makes gasoline, jet oil, heating oil and
other products, has been producing about 280,000 barrels a day.
   Power outages also have closed Chevron's loading racks, keeping
trucks from filling their tanks for distribution. Holt also said
power outages were preventing some service stations from pumping
gasoline.
   The quake shook Exxon's 132,000 barrel-a-day Benicia, Calif.,
refinery but that the facility had cut back production only
slightly ``just as a cushion to see if there will be any
aftershocks,'' said Henry Beathard, Exxon spokesman in Houston. The
refinery is located about 40 miles east of San Francisco.
   Texaco's refinery in Richmond, Calif., received minor damage but
was continuing to operate, said company spokeswoman Sharon Stakes.
   ``We will be able to continue distribution if roads are
accessible,'' Stakes said.
   In London markets, open-market prices of North Sea Brent Blend
crude oil were slightly higher at midday Wednesday on speculation
that the earthquake might disrupt supplies of crude oil and
petroleum products in California.
   Brent Blend prices were 15 cents to 20 cents a barrel above
their levels late Tuesday in Europe, and above their levels earlier
today in Tokyo.
   London-based officials of U.S. companies which operate
facilities in San Francisco said they were unable to obtain
information about possible damage because telephone lines to the
area were jammed.
   At about midday London time, Brent Blend for delivery in
November stood at $19.80 a barrel, up 20 cents from late Tuesday.
Brent Blend for December delivery was up 15 cents at $19.10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
