<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Brokerages     10-18 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Brokerages,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shearson Posts Quarterly Profit Following Year-ago Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings Inc., reversing
a loss from a year ago, on Wednesday reported a $66 million profit
in the third quarter from sharply higher revenue.
   For the three months ended Sept. 30, Shearson netted $64 a
share, compared with a loss of $3 million, or 11 cents a share, in
the 1988 period, when the brokerage company had $25 million in
pre-tax expenses from the acquisition of E.F. Hutton &amp; Co.
   Quarterly revenue jumped 25 percent to $3.3 billion from $2.6
million last year.
   Shearson said higher commissions and revenue from market making
and principal transactions more than offset lower investment
banking revenue and an increase in expenses.
   Expenses totaled $3.2 billion in the third quarter, up 21
percent from $2.6 billion last year, the company said. During the
quarter, Shearson said it began relocating employees to a new
office facility in New York, which should ultimately help control
costs.
   Shearson's earnings for the first nine months of 1989 were off 3
percent, totaling $106 million, or 98 cents a share, from $110
million, or $1.05, last year. Revenue jumped 26 percent to $9.6
billion from $7.6 billion.
   However, expenses also rose 26 percent to $9.4 billion from $7.5
billion, the company said.
   Results for the nine-month period of last year included $144
million in pre-tax merger-related expenses.
   Shearson is a subsidiary of financial giant American Express Co.
</TEXT>
