<FIRST>u f BC-Trinova     10-18 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Trinova,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trinova Announces Layoff of 1,500 Employees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAUMEE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trinova Corp. announced a major
restructuring Wednesday that includes reducing or closing around
three dozen facilities and laying off 1,500 employees over the next
three years.
   The company, which supplies equipment to the aerospace and
transportation industries, said it lost $29.7 million, or 87 cents
a share, in the third quarter as a result of a $38.5 million
provision taken for the restructing.
   That compared with a profit of $19.64 million, or 57 cents a
share, in 1988. Sales in the latest quarter rose 8 percent to $456
million from $422 million.
   ``The summer slowdown in automotive production seriously
affected our automotive plastics operations,'' President Darryl
Allen said in a statement.
   ``Lower U.S. defense sales and inefficiencies in the Aeroquip
operations also contributed to weaker results in power and motion
control.''
   As part of its restructuring, which is primarily related to its
Aeroquip Corp. subsidiary, Trinova said it will downsize or close
40 of its 170 facilities.
   That would result in layoffs of around 1,500 employees, all
technical and administrative workers, in the next three years, or 8
percent of its approximately 19,000 work force.
   The company also said it will take several steps to reduce
costs, such as improving production and reconfigurating the factory
floor.
   ``I am confident that these actions will improve the performance
of Trinova's companies ... and accelerate our earnings growth,''
Allen said.
   Trinova, formerly known as Libbey-Owens Ford Co., also operates
the subsidiary Vickers Inc.
</TEXT>
