<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1416EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CrayonCompany Adv23   10-18 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Crayon Company, Adv 23,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday Oct. 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>Not Just For the Kiddies Anymore</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY STREFF BUZBEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINFIELD, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's a child's delight _ rows of bright
red, yellow and green crayons that pop out of molding machines,
roll along conveyor belts and slip into little boxes that have
become a fixture in any toy store.
   But Binney &amp; Smith is making more than Crayola crayons at its
plant in this small Kansas town south of Wichita. The 85-year-old
company has branched into art products designed to appeal to
everyone from toddlers to professionals, as part of a larger
diversification plan by parent company Hallmark Cards Inc.
   The Kansas City-based cardmaker bought Binney &amp; Smith for $200
million five years ago, shortly after Irvine O. Hockaday Jr. became
Hallmark's president and chief executive officer. Hockaday has
since steered Hallmark into markets ranging from real estate to
Spanish-language television, but he still thinks his first buy was
a good one.
   ``It's hard to match the criteria we set,'' Hockaday said. ``But
Binney &amp; Smith is incomparable as far as people recognizing the
Crayola name and having good feelings about it. We thought that
feeling could be widened to different age groups, and we were
right.''
   Binney &amp; Smith plants in Winfield and at the subsidiary's
headquarters in Easton, Pa., now turn out about 9 million crayons a
day in 72 colors.
   But with marketing help from Hallmark, they also make new and
higher-priced lines of washable felt-tip markers and paints for
youngsters, and more precise erasable colored mechanical pencils
for older children. They also produce the company's Liquitex brand
of acrylic paints used by art students and professional artists.
   Last year, Binney &amp; Smith even began selling coloring books.
   ``Our crayon market has always been as stable as any market can
be,'' said Jim Wilson, manager of the Winfield plant. But parents
were looking for other products for their children.
   ``We knew mothers would love this,'' Wilson said of the felt-tip
markers printed with ``erasable'' in large letters. ``They were
telling us they wanted it to keep markers off the furniture and
walls.''
   In addition, the company is selling its products in new places,
from hotels to airlines, and planning more products targeted toward
teen-agers and the growing adult crafts market.
   ``The teen-age and young-adult market is enormous,'' Hockaday
said. ``We feel we can migrate the feelings that a young person has
toward Crayola into other products as they move into the pre-teen
years and then beyond.''
   So far, the theory seems to be working. Hallmark doesn't reveal
financial figures because it is privately owned, but Hockaday said
Binney &amp; Smith and its 1,300 employees have done slightly better
than Hallmark forecast five years ago. Its revenues and profits
have been growing by double digits in the last few years, he said.
   Hallmark itself, which had sales of $2.3 billion in 1988, still
specializes in greeting-cards and the related products in dealers'
stores.
   Its lines of greeting cards, including the Hallmark line and the
mass-market Ambassador line sold in grocery and drug stores,
account for 44 percent of all U.S. card sales.
   But officials decided they needed to diversify for the future of
the company owned by descendants of founder Joyce Hall and some
employees.
   ``We don't see any serious clouds on the horizon of our core
business, but theoretically, technology could eat into the
greeting-card business a bit in the future,'' Hockaday said. ``And
theoretically, rapidly increasing postal rates if they occurred
could slow our sales.''
   In 1987 and 1988, Hallmark bought 10 Spanish-language television
stations and a Spanish-language TV network based in Los Angeles.
   The company had some experience making greeting cards for
Hispanic customers but felt the market had been mostly overlooked
by advertisers in the past, Hockaday said.
   ``The Hispanic market is growing faster than any other market
segment that I'm aware of,'' Hockaday said. ``We think it's one of
those unique, niche, growth opportunities.''
   Future acquisitions are under consideration, Hockaday said, but
Hallmark officials view the market as ``overheated'' right now and
are acting cautiously.
   Meanwhile at the Winfield plant, crayons now share floor space
with washable markers. But it's still crayons that most fascinate
the local schoolchildren who regularly tour the plant, said plant
manager Wilson.
   ``Their appeal is enduring,'' he said. ``That's our greatest
strength.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday Oct. 23</NOTE>
