<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     10-18 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Firms, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar turned mixed in active European
trading Wednesday as the disasterous California earthquake had
little impact on foreign exchange.
   Gold prices were higher.
   ``This was a directionless market, but there was high trading
volume,'' said a dealer at a European bank in Frankfurt. ``We all
watched the stock exchange, but it never helped to establish a
clear direction.''
   The earthquake, which rocked through northern California on
Tuesday, and Erich Honecker's removal as East Germany's leader had
little apparent impact on exchange markets, dealers said.
   Traders said the market was awaiting Thursday's release of the
U.S. consumer price index figures for September.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell to a closing 142.10 Japanese yen from
142.25 yen Tuesday. Later, in London, it dropped to 141.40 yen.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5880 from $1.5835 late
Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
1.8525 West German marks, up from 1.8520; 1.6255 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6227; 6.2990 French francs, up from 6.2960; 2.0818 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.0867; 1.1737 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1755; and 1,366.00 Italian lire, up from 1,365.00.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $368.25 a troy ounce
from $367.75 bid late Tuesday. In Zurich, gold rose to $368.50 an
ounce from $367.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.72 to close at $368.38 an
ounce.
   Silver fell in London to a late bid price of $5.11 a troy ounce
from $5.12 Tuesday.
</TEXT>
