<FIRST>r f BC-NewspaperSale     10-18 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Newspaper Sale,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Media General Puts 31 Weekly Newspapers Up for Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media General Inc. has put up for sale 31
weekly newspapers in Orange County and the San Gabriel Valley area,
saying the papers are too far from its base in Virginia.
   The Richmond, Va.-based firm announced the planned sale Tuesday,
adding that the decision was also prompted by a desire to
concentrate on its chain of daily newspapers.
   The papers it wants to sell constitute Golden West Publishing
Inc. and are to be sold as a unit.
   They include nine published by South Orange County News in
Mission Viejo and 22 run by Highlander Publications of the City of
Industry. All but one are distributed to community residents free
of charge.
   A statement issued by Media General said that ``management
demands for the West Coast operations are no longer prudent,'' and
that ``we prefer to concentrate our efforts on daily newspaper
operations.''
   Media General owns newspapers in Richmond and Tampa, Fla., and
television and cable systems elsewhere in the Southeast.
   Golden West chief executive Ron Redfern said the papers have a
combined circulation of 487,000 and gross annual revenues of about
$15 million.
   He would not disclose the asking price, but said that weekly
newspapers usually sell for one to two times their gross revenues.
   A number of companies had expressed interest, Redfern said, but
he declined not identify them.
   Golden West was formed in 1980 and 1981 with the purchase of
several small weekly newspaper chains. Redfern said the company
initially had planned to convert one or more of the papers to
dailies but later changed its plans.
   Media General successfully defended itself against a hostile
takeover attempt last year by Hollywood producer Burt Sugarman and
sold its only other West Coast operation, a paper mill in Pomona,
to Sugarman after his bid failed.
</TEXT>
