<FIRST>u f BC-Markets-Britain     10-18 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Markets-Britain,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Stocks Close Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rallied Wednesday to close sharply
higher after fears subsided over what effect the California
earthquake would have on Wall Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index jumped 34.6
points, or 1.6 percent, to close at 2,170.1, its high for the day.
   The key index had been under pressure most of the morning over
concerns that possible economic effects of the earthquake would
undermine prices on Wall Street and translate into sharper declines
for British stocks.
   But London's fortunes turned after dealers reappraised the
direct impact of the disaster and New York rebounded from its early
disaster-led losses.
   ``Wall Street didn't collapse, so there was no reason for London
to,'' a dealer with the London investment firm Hoare Govett Ltd.
noted.
   The Financial Times 30-share index finished 27.8 points higher
at 1,758.5 points. The Financial Times 500-share index closed at
1,202.54, up 20.8 points.
   Volume was 449.3 million shares traded, the lightest this week
and down from 643.4 million shares on Tuesday.
   British insurance stocks, which some equity analysts forecast
might be heavily hit by the earthquake disaster, helped underpin
London by staging only narrow losses in early dealings.
   Dealers said the market still has not shaken off its nervousness
after the sharp declines of recent sessions, which resulted from a
190-point drop in the Dow Jones industrial average on Friday.
   But technical factors, including modest gains in the British
pound, helped draw buying back into the market and at least reverse
losses posted a day earlier.
</TEXT>
