<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1442EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Drugs     10-18 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Drugs,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pfizer Earnings Flat; Schering-Plough, American Home Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Pharmaceuticals giant Pfizer Inc. said Wednesday its earnings
were flat in the third quarter, while Schering-Plough Corp. and
American Home Products Corp. said profits increased compared with
the same period last year.
   New York-based Pfizer said net income was about the same in the
three-month period as in 1988 because of new product launches and
larger research and development costs.
   Pfizer reported net income of $217.5 million, or $1.29 a share,
on sales of $1.44 billion for the quarter, compared with $216.8
million, or $1.29 a share, on sales of $1.38 billion in the same
1988 period.
   Pfizer said health care sales increased 3 percent and consumer
products sales rose 23 percent, while speciality chemicals sales
were flat and agricultural sales fell 5 percent.
   Pfizer attributed the flat earnings to the introduction of newly
approved drugs for angina, hypertension and cardiovascular disease,
and a coronary angioplasty catheter. Pfizer said its research and
development expenses increased 11 percent for the quarter.
   Fot the first nine months of 1989, Pfizer reported a 9 percent
earnings decline to $594 million, or $3.52 a share, from $650
million, or $3.86 a share. Sales rose 4 percent to $4.18 billion
from $4.02 billion.
   Schering-Plough said its earnings increased 20.8 percent despite
poor exchange rates and the sale of its European cosmetics
businesses.
   The Madison, N.J.-based pharmaceutical and health care company
said net earnings were $114 million, or $1.01 a share, up from
$94.4 million, or 84 cents a share, in same 1988 period.
   Third-quarter sales rose 3 percent to $743.7 million from $724.4
million, the company said. Quarterly sales of the company's
worldwide consumer products business declined 12 percent.
   For the first nine months of the year, Schering-Plough reported
a 21.3 percent profit rise to $360 million, or $3.20 a share, from
$297 million, or $2.65 a share. Sales were $2.38 billion, up from
$2.23 billion in the first nine months of 1988.
   American Home Products, based in New York, said third-quarter
earnings rose 11 percent to $266.2 million, or $1.80 a share, from
$240.7 million, or $1.65 a share. Sales rose 7 percent to $1.51
billion from $1.42 billion in the 1988 period.
   From January through September, American Home said earnings rose
11 perecnt to $766.7 million, or $5.21 a share, from $693.5
million, or $4.75 a share. Sales for the period increased to $4.43
billion from $4.20 billion in 1988.
</TEXT>
