<FIRST>r f AM-TrinovaLayoffs     10-18 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trinova Layoffs,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trinova Corp. Announces Layoff of 1,500 Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAUMEE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trinova Corp. announced Wednesday it would
lay off 1,500 employees in its second restructuring in as many
years.
   Thomas Ainsworth, a spokesman for the suburban Toledo-based
company, said 40 of the company's 170 plants would be closed or
reduced. Ainsworth declined comment on which plants would be
affected.
   Trinova, formerly known as Libbey-Owens Ford Co., operates
Aeroquip Corp. and Vickers Inc., which supply power and motion
control systems, components and plastic products to the aerosapce
and transportation industries.
   The layoffs will affect technical and administrative employees.
The company has 20,000 employees worldwide, including 230 at its
Maumee world headquarters.
   ``I am confident that these actions will improve the performance
of Trinova's companies, Aeroquip and Vickers, and accelerate our
earnings growth,'' said Darryl Allen, Trinova's president and chief
executive officer.
   Last October, the company announced it merged two subsidiaries
because they shared a variety of customers.
   ``The summer slowdown in automotive production seriously
affected our automotive plastics operations,'' Allen said. ``Lower
U.S. defense sales and inefficiencies in the Aeroquip operations
also contributed to weaker results in power and motion control.''
   Some anaylsts said they were surprised by the size of Trinova's
restructring, but that it would benefit the company in the long run.
   James McCann, an analyst with Drexel Burnham, said the move will
help the company become more competitive in the face of increasing
foreign competition.
   ``It doesn't mean it won't be painful in the short term for the
people who are involved, but the U.S. industry is becoming more
competitive, and Trinova has taken the bull by the horns,'' McCann
said.
   The restructuring resulted in a charge of $38.5 million, after
taxes, against Trinova's 1989 third-quarter earnings, producing a
loss of $29.7 million, or 87 cents a share.
   Trinova earned $19.4 million during the 1988 third quarter, or
57 cents a share.
   Sales in the third quarter increased 8 percent, to $456.2
million, up from 1988 third-quarter sales of $422 million.
   Sales for the first nine months increased 11.6 percent, to $1.44
billion, compared with sales in the first nine months of 1988 of
$1.29 billion.
   Earnings through the first nine months of the year were $13.1
million, or 38 cents a share, after deducting the restructuring
provision. In the same period in 1988, the company earned $61.6
million, or $1.79 a share.
</TEXT>
