<DOCNO> AP891018-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1500EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-AMR     10-18 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-AMR,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>AMR Reports Decline In Third Quarter Earnings, `Unhappy' Outlook</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AMR Corp. reported Wednesday its
third-quarter earnings fell nearly 9 percent, and Chairman Robert
L. Crandall said the fourth-quarter outlook for the parent of
American Airlines was ``unhappy.''
   Crandall attributed the poor showing, which had been expected,
to higher fuel costs and lower revenue per passenger mile.
   The announcement came two days after billionaire Donald Trump
withdrew his $7 billion buyout proposal for AMR as the company's
stock fell in the overall Wall Street plunge.
   AMR said it earned $137 million, or $2.16 per share, in the
three-month ended Sept. 30, compared to $150.3 million, or $2.50
per share, in the same period last year.
   Revenue increased to $2.73 billion from $2.33 billion in the
same period last year.
   For the nine months, AMR's earnings were $415.9 million, or
$6.59 per share, an increase over 1988's $360.1 million, or $5.99
per share. Revenue in the nine-month period rose to $7.89 billion
from $6.46 billion.
   Crandall said in a statement that revenue per passenger mile was
down slightly during the quarter, and fuel prices were up more than
11 percent from the third quarter of 1988. The two factors took a
toll on AMR's results.
   ``Unfortunately, we think these trends will continue and will
produce a very disappointing fourth quarter as well,'' Crandall
said. ``This unhappy outlook ... underscores the continuing
volatility of airline earnings and the importance of an adequate
capital base.''
   AMR never responded directly to Trump's proposal beyond saying
the company was opposed to highly leveraged deals and preferred to
remain independent.
   Analysts have suggested Trump was unable to get financing to
back his bid because of growing uncertainties over the future of
airline performance.
   Crandall told analysts last month profits through next year
would be squeezed by competition from a recovering Eastern
Airlines, higher labor costs, expansion of service and purchase of
new aircraft.
</TEXT>
