<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1454EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-MarketsRdp 6thLd-Writethru   10-18 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets Rdp, 6th Ld-Writethru,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Open Lower; Some Cite San Fran Earthquake</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 17 grafs to UPDATE with stock prices, more market
sectors; picks up 14th graf, On Tuesday ....</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California earthquake registered only mildly
today on the nation's stock exchanges.
   Stocks of companies in San Francisco and Silicon Valley were
mixed, with some such as Apple Computer Inc. actually higher. Many
insurance stocks also rose, apparently on speculation that the
quake would provide an opportunity for the companies to raise rates.
   Building-materials suppliers and companies that supply disaster
recovery services for computer users also saw their stocks rise.
   Overall, the stock market wavered after a series of chaotic
sessions that began with Friday's 190-point plunge in the Dow Jones
30-stock industrial average.
   The Dow Jones average was up 0.41 points at 2,639.14 at 2:30
p.m. EDT on the New York Stock Exchange. It had fallen in the
opening moments but was up more than 10 points by midday. The
number of advancing issues slightly outpaced decliners on the Big
Board.
   Apple Computer Inc. was up 50 cents at $47.75 a share and Intel
Corp. was up 25 cents at $33.75 in over-the-counter trading. On the
New York Stock Exchange, the biotechnology company Genentech Inc.
was off 12{ cents at $19.75 and Hewlett-Packard Co. was up 12{
cents at $45.87{.
   Among local utilities, Pacific Gas and Electric was down 37{
cents a share at $19.62{, while Pacific Telesis Group, parent of
Pacific Bell, was off 12{ cents at $45.12{.
   Chevron Corp., which has headquarters in San Francisco, was off
12{ cents at $63.87{.
   Among insurers, stocks rebounded quickly after a selloff
triggered by the earthquake. Some analysts said the quake could
produce more than $1 billion in claims, but that the quake losses,
coupled with losses from Hurricane Hugo, could trigger a round of
rate increases that would help the industry's profitability.
   San Francisco-based Transamerica Corp. was off 25 cents at
$42.75, Aetna Life &amp; Casualty was up $1.12{ at $58.25, Chubb Corp.
was up 75 cents at $81.25 and Travelers Corp. was up 37{ cents at
$40.25.
   The strongest performers among insurance stocks were the
so-called reinsurers that absorb risk from the policy-writing
firms. On the NYSE, General Re Corp. was up $2.62{ at $86.37{ and
Marsh &amp; McLennan Cos. was up $3.25 a share at $76.
   Hardest hit was Everex Systems Inc., a maker of personal
computer equipment based in Fremont, Calif., on the east side of
San Francisco Bay. It was off 30 percent, falling $3.50 a share to
$8.12{ in over-the-counter dealings.
   Two companies that bail mainframe computer installations out of
disasters were higher: Comdisco rose $1.25 to $30.75 on the NYSE
and Sungard Data Systems Inc. climbed $2 to $21.50.
   Among the construction companies that gained from the quake were
Fluor Corp., up $1 to $33.62{; Morrison Knudsen, up $2.25 to $44;
and Foster Wheeler, up 62{ cents to $18.50. Building-materials
suppliers included Georgia-Pacific, up $1.75 to $58.50, and
Louisiana-Pacific, up $1.25 to $41.
   Volume on the floor of the New York Stock Exchange came to
124.47 million shares as of 2 p.m. EDT.
   Overseas, the Tuesday evening quake was blamed for declines on
the Australian and New Zealand markets, but stocks in Tokyo posted
moderate gains, with the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gaining
111.48 points, or 0.32 percent, to close at 35,107.56.
   In London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index
rose 34.6 points, or about 1.6 percent, to close at 2,170.1.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones average lost just under 19 points
Tuesday after weathering a late-morning scare that briefly sent it
down more than 60 points.
   Trading was relatively calm Tuesday after the Dow industrial
average plummeted 190 points Friday and then bounced back 88 points
Monday. The Dow Jones average fell 18.65 points to 2,638.73 Tuesday.
   Stocks lost little ground despite continued uncertainty
surrounding a proposed buyout of UAL Corp. and a government report
showing a bigger-than-expected trade deficit in August. The Federal
Reserve helped by adding a modest amount of reserves to the banking
system.
</TEXT>
