<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1525EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-SecuredCreditCard     10-18 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Secured Credit Card,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Announce New Secured Low Rate Credit Card</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers recovering from serious debt problems
don't have to wait years, or pay through the nose, before
re-entering the world of plastic.
   American National Bank of New York announced Wednesday it can
provide many of those with tainted credit histories with a new Visa
credit card carrying an annual 12.5 percent interest rate, around
six percentage points below the national average.
   But there's a catch: applicants must put a minimum $500 into a
one-year certificate of deposit at the bank to be used as
collateral, and enroll in a counseling program with a non-profit
credit counseling service. The largest such organization is the
Maryland-based National Foundation for Consumer Credit, which
oversees a network of 400 counseling offices nationwide.
   One of the biggest of those offices, the Budget &amp; Credit
Counseling Services Inc. of New York, which counsels about 10,000
families and individuals a year, helped arrange for the American
National Visa card.
   ``America operates on credit, which means that even people with
past credit problems need a credit card to function effectively,''
explained Luther R. Gatling, president of the New York credit
counseling service.
   ``To be without credit undermines an individual's self-esteem.
It makes normal activities like business travel impractical, and
general consumerism in this country impossible.''
   The new credit card is secured by the CD. The line of credit is
limited to the amount of the deposit minus $250 for desposits
between $500 and $2,500, or 90 percent of a deposit between $2,501
and $10,000.
</TEXT>
