<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     10-18 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0481</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market hovered at slightly higher
levels today, steadying after three hectic sessions.
   The California earthquake appeared to be doing little damage to
the market and many stocks actually benefited as investors bought
companies that could profit on account of the destruction in the
San Francisco Bay area.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks had a small gain
of 1.43 points, bringing it to 2,640.16, at 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by about 5 to 3 on
the New York Stock Exchange where 780 stocks were up in price, 667
were down and 466 were unchanged.
   The NYSE composite index of all its listed common stocks
increased 0.40 to 189.29.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 143.14 million
shares with 1 hour left to go.
   Activity on Wall Street seemed more subdued compared with the
chaotic trading that began with Friday's 190-point tumble in the
Dow Jones industrial average.
   Pacific Gas &amp; Electric fell ] to 19| but the San Francisco-based
utility said recovering from the quake wouldn't put a significant
financial strain on the company.
   Chevron, which has its headquarters in San Francisco, rose } to
64} as more than 1.2 million shares changed hands.
   Several insurance stocks rose on speculation that heavy
quake-related claims, coming after losses from Hurricane Hugo,
could lead insurers to raise premium rates, enhancing the
industry's profitability.
   Some contruction stocks surged in anticipaton of greater demand
for cement and other building materials on account of the quake.
   Technology stocks appeared to shrug off initial concerns in the
market about problems at Silicon Valley facilities. Apple Computer
rose { to 47}, Intel was up { at 34 and Microsoft firmed 1~ to 80{.
   Other active blue chips included American Telephone &amp; Telegraph,
up \ at 42{, International Business Machines, down ] to 101~,
McDonalds, down | to 30. Philip Morris, which reported its
third-quarter earnings climbed 20.5 percent, helped by the
inclusion of results from Kraft, wasup [ at 43] on volume of more
than 2.2 million shares.
   AMR, parent of American Airlines, headed the Big Board's actives
list, and more than 2.4 million shares had traded by 3 p.m. It
gained 1{ to 74} despite news that its third-quarter earnings fell
nearly 9 percent.
   AMR had taken a dive earlier this week on word that Donald Trump
had withdrawn his $7 billion bid for the airline holding company.
   The third most heavily traded issue was UAL, which lost 6\ to
191}.
   The recent turbulence in the stock market had been intensified
by confusion surrounding a proposed buyout of UAL. A tremendous
plunge in shares of the parent of United Airlines helped trigger
Friday's megadrop.
</TEXT>
