<DOCNO> AP891018-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1530EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Airlines-Takeovers     10-18 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airlines-Takeovers,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Approves Legislation Blocking Certain Takeovers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee voted Wednesday to give the
Transportation Department authority to block major airline
takeovers, after backers of the bill said travelers want assurances
a purchaser's heavy debt would not jeopardize safety.
   Under the legislation, the Transportation Department would be
obligated to block the purchase of 15 percent of an airline's
voting stock if the deal would jeopardize safety, lead to a breakup
of the company, hinder its ability to compete, or leave the carrier
in the hands of a foreign interest.
   ``This bill does not prevent airline takeovers or significantly
interfere with an owner's property rights. It merely gives DOT the
opportunity to review those transactions that might harm the public
interest,'' said Rep. John Paul Hammerschmidt, R-Ark.
   ``Air travelers expect assurances that the heavy debt load
incurred during an acquisition will not lead to a deterioration of
safety,'' Hammerschmidt told the House Public Works and
Transportation Committee before it approved the bill by a vote of
23-5.
   Opponents claimed the bill could be the first step toward
congressional regulation of debt-financed takeovers, while
Hammerschmidt said the legisalation is similar to procedures used
by the Justice Department to review mergers under antitrust laws.
   ``The government doesn't have a role in determining individual
transactions and second-guessing the market place,'' countered Rep.
Arlan Stangeland, R-Minn., calling the bill an impediment to the
economics of the airline industry.
   The committee defeated an amendment by Rep. Peter DeFazio,
D-Ore., which would have barred a takeover if it would result in a
major reduction of wages, benefits or workers.
   With the bill restricting a buyer from selling off a big part of
an airline's assets, DeFazio told the committee: ``You're now
leaving the employees naked in this bill to take all the cuts.''
   The House bill, similar to legislation approved by the Senate
Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee, had been rushed
through Congress because of concerns about Donald Trump's attempts
to takeover AMR Corp. of Fort Worth, Texas, parent company of
American Airlines.
   Trump, a New York billionaire, withdrew his $7.5 billion bid on
Monday, hours before the House aviation subcommittee passed the
legislation, but said he may make another bid for the country's
largest airline.
   Members of the House committee said they were approving the bill
in the face of a possible veto by President Bush. Deputy
Transportation Secretary Elaine L. Chao said Monday the the
administration strongly opposes the bill and that DOT has
sufficient authority to act when an acquisition raises concerns
about an airline's fitness.
   As a result of mergers and acquisitions in the years since
deregulation, the number of major carriers has dropped from 22 to
eight, which now control 90 percent of domestic traffic, said Rep.
James L. Oberstar, D-Minn., chairman of the aviation subcommittee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
