<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-UnitedTechnologies     10-18 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-United Technologies,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>UTC Reports 3 Percent Increase In 3rd Quarter Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Technologies Corp. said its
third-quarter income rose 3 percent on the strenghth of increased
sales for jet engines, air conditioning systems and elevators.
   UTC said it earned $196.7 million, or $1.46 per share, up from
$190.1 million, or $1.45 per share, in the same period a year
earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose to $4.75 billion from $4.47 billion
last year.
   UTC subsidiaries _ Pratt &amp; Whitney jet engines, Otis, Carrier
air contioners and Sikorsky helicopters _ all reported increased
revenue during the period, UTC Chairman Robert F. Daniell said.
   For the first nine months, UTC earned $517.7 million, or $3.91
per share, compared to $508.5 million, or $3.89 a share, for the
same period in 1988.
   Revenue during the first three quarters totaled $14.49 billion,
compared to $13.25 billion a year earlier.
   Pratt &amp; Whitney received $9.5 billion in commercial jet engine
orders during the first nine months of the year, a 90 percent
increase over the $5 billion in commercial jet engine orders
received in all of 1988, Daniell said.
   ``The continued strong demand for Pratt &amp; Whitney's
new-trechnology commercial engines will pay off for years to
come,'' Danielle said.
   UTC's other subsidiaries include Norden and Hamilton Standard.
Norden produces radar and other defense systems, while Hamilton
Standard manufactures components used in space shuttles and
astronaut space suits.
</TEXT>
