<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1618EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Banks     10-18 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sovran Says Earnings Up 12 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sovran Financial Corp., which plans to merge with Citizens &amp;
Southern Corp. to create the nation's 14th-largest banking company,
on Wednesday reported a 12 percent rise in its third-quarter profit
over a year ago.
   Net income for the three months ended Sept. 30 totaled $69.2
million, or $1.15 a share, compared with earnings of $61.9 million,
or $1.04 a share, a year ago.
   For the first nine months, its earnings were $196.6 million, or
$3.28 a share, up 12 percent from a profit of $175.0 million, or
$2.94 a share, in 1988.
   Chairman Albert B. Gornto Jr. attributed the improved results to
higher revenue, both net interest and non-interest.
   Norfolk, Va.-based Sovran last month announced an agreement with
Atlanta-based C&amp;S to combine operations in a stock swap under a new
holding company to be called Avantor Financial Corp.
   The merger would create the nation's 14th-largest bank holding
company with $47 billion in assets, $34 billion in deposits and 976
branches in eight states in the Southeast.
   The transaction is pending approval of regulatory authorities
and is expected to be completed in the first quarter of 1990.
</TEXT>
