<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-18 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Rally With Soyoil, Poor Harvest Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices rose for the third
consecutive day Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid
speculation that the Soviet Union was looking to buy a large
quantity of U.S. soybean oil.
   Grain futures closed mixed.
   Expectations that the Soviets would purchase 50,000 to 75,000
metric tons of soybean oil at subsidized prices supplanted the
rumors of Soviet interest in soybeans and soybean meal that
supported the market Tuesday.
   Forecasts for foul weather in the Midwest on Thursday and Friday
also supported the soybean market, said Joel Karlin, an analyst
with Research Department Inc., a Chicago-based brokers' advisory
service.
   ``We are supposed to get quite a bit of rain and cold
temperatures, and that could limit harvesting of soybeans in the
eastern Corn Belt,'' he said.
   At the close, wheat futures were 3\ cents lower to 4 cents
higher with the contract for delivery in December at $4.06\ a
bushel; corn futures were } cent lower to { cent higher with
December at $2.38\ a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1{ cents higher
with December at $1.44\ a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents to 4}
cents higher with November at $5.60 a bushel.
</TEXT>
