<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 2052EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f BC-EECForecast     10-18 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC Forecast,0154</SECOND>
<HEAD>Predict 3.5 Pct 1989 Growth Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic growth in the 12-nation
European Economic Community will reach 3.5 percent this year, up
from the 3.25 percent forecast in June, its executive body said
Wednesday.
   In its annual economic report, the European Commission projected
economic growth next year at 3 percent, after adjustment for
inflation.
   It said the inflation rate was likely to run 4.8 percent in
1989, up from the 3.6 percent recorded last year. It said, though,
the rate should slow to 4.5 percent in 1990.
   Henning Christophersen, who handles the commission's budget
affairs, said unemployment might fall below 9 percent as some 1.5
million jobs are created next year.
   But he said unemployment remained well above levels earlier in
the decade, and that there would have to be ``a continuing
improvement of the economy before the unemployment situation
becomes acceptable.''
</TEXT>
