<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1933EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CreditFraud     10-18 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Credit Fraud,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accuse Boiler-Room Operator of Bilking Credit Card Holders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OCALA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators have seized records and shut a
``boiler room'' operation of a telemarketing firm suspected of
bilking thousands of credit card holders in a huge and highly
organized fraud case.
   The company, American Tele-Digital, called on credit card
holders outside Florida and asked them to buy a service that
notifies all credit card companies if the cards are lost or stolen,
investigators said.
   ``Last year, we dealt with about half-a-dozen fraud schemes, and
this one is the most organized and probably the largest we've
seen,'' said Richard Cataldo, a security agent for American Express
Co.
   Officials raided and closed American Tele-Digital, seized
records and subpoenaed employees, Chief Assistant State Attorney
Ric Ridgway said Tuesday.
   American Tele-Digital was set up as a telephone ``boiler room''
where sales people telephoned credit card holders and fraudulently
obtained their card numbers before billing fees to their accounts
without permission, said Jennifer Fanzlaw of the Marion County
Sheriff's Department.
   Employees called credit card holders and claimed they worked for
the company authorized to insure their cards, Ms. Fanzlaw said.
   ``The company then advised they needed their credit card number
to verify they were the current holder, or if they wanted to cancel
the protection,'' Ms. Fanzlaw said.
   With the numbers, the company was able to bill fees to
customers' accounts without their permission, Ms. Fanzlaw said,
adding: ``That is where the scam came in.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
