<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1952EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Mesa-StatesWest     10-18 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mesa-StatesWest,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Terms of StatesWest Offer for Mesa Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARMINGTON, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mesa Airlines Inc. said Wednesday that
StatesWest Airlines Inc. had offered $15.3 million in cash and
securities for all the common stock in Mesa that the Phoenix-based
airline doesn't already own.
   The offer values the entire company at $16.5 million.
   Gary Risley, Mesa's vice president for corporate affairs, said
StatesWest is offering $10 _ $7 a share in cash plus StatesWest
securities with a value of $3 per share _ for each Mesa share.
   The offer was made in a letter to Mesa from StatesWest Chairman
Rudy Miller. StatesWest had asked Mesa's board of directors to keep
the terms confidential, but Mesa announced the terms Wednesday.
   Risley said Mesa has 1.65 million shares of stock. StatesWest
acquired 7.25 percent of the stock in May, and Miller said Tuesday
he had purchased ``a little stock in the last couple of days,'' but
declined to say how much.
   Risley said Tuesday the StatesWest proposal would be referred to
Mesa's board for consideration along with recommendations from
Mesa's financial and legal advisers.
   ``We believe that the terms we have proposed are fair and
generous and in the best interest of the Mesa shareholders,''
Miller said Tuesday in announcing the proposal.
   ``Because we are making this offer on a friendly basis, we are
first submitting it to the board of directors for its review and
consideration,'' Miller said.
   ``We hope to have the opportunity to discuss the proposal with
Mesa's board of directors in the near future,'' he said.
   Last week, Mesa officials said they had no interest in a
friendly takeover proposal by StatesWest, and later in the week
Mesa announced it was examining the possibility of buying Air
Midwest of Wichita, Kan.
   StatesWest serves cities in Arizona, southern California and
Nevada.
   Mesa serves cities in New Mexico, Colorado, Wyoming, Texas and
Arizona. A recently acquired Mesa subsidiary, Milwaukee-based
Skyway Airlines, serves cities in Iowa, Indiana, Illinois, Michigan
and Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
