<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1958EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Dun&amp;Bradstreet     10-18 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Dun &amp; Bradstreet,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rose 15.2 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp. announced Wednesday its
third quarter earnings rose 15.2 percent despite a drop in revenue.
   The business information company said it earned $155.3 million,
or 83 cents per share, up from $134.8 million, or 72 cents per
share, in the third quarter of 1988.
   Revenue declined to $1.04 billion from $1.07 billion.
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet said sales were hurt by several factors,
including the strength of the dollar in overseas transactions and
the absence of revenue from its Official Airlines Guides business.
Dun &amp; Bradstreet sold OAG last year.
   Without those factors, the company said its revenue would have
increased 6 percent.
   For the first nine months of the year, Dun &amp; Bradstreet said it
earned nearly $449 million, or $2.40 per share, up 19.4 percent
from $375.9 million, or $2.01 per share, a year earlier.
   Revenue for the nine-month period increased 0.8 percent to $3.16
billion from $3.13 billion a year earlier. Without the same factors
that affected the third-quarter figure, revenue would have
increased 8 percent, the company said.
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet's segments include Moody's Investor Service,
Nielsen Marketing Research and its Donnelly yellow pages publishing
business.
</TEXT>
