<DOCNO> AP891018-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 2005EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Viacom     10-18 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Viacom,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Loss Narrows in 3rd Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Viacom Inc., a communications and entertainment
concern, said Wednesday its loss for the third quarter narrowed to
$21.7 million as earnings from operations climbed 42 percent and
revenues rose 11 percent.
   The company, which has interests in broadcasting and cable
television and owns MTV Networks Inc. and Showtime Networks Inc.,
said its loss for the three months ended Sept. 30 amounted to 41
cents per share and contrasted with a loss of $56.9 million, or
$1.07 per share, in 1988.
   Third-quarter revenue rose to $345.5 million from $311.6 million
a year earlier.
   Earnings from operations climbed to $47.4 million in the quarter
from $33.3 million a year earlier.
   The company blamed its quarterly loss primarily on interest
expenses.
   The company recently announced a restructuring of its bank debt
and said the new 10-year $1.5 billion unsecured financing agreement
will give it significant interest rate savings and increased
operating flexibility.
   Viacom said its networks segment, which includes basic cable
service from MTV and pay-TV service from Showtime, posted 17
percent higher revenue for the quarter while earnings from
operations more than doubled to $30.4 million.
   The announcement comes a day after Viacom said it agreed to sell
a 50 percent interest in Showtime Networks, the second largest
pay-TV service, for $225 million to the cable giant
Tele-Communications Inc. of Denver.
   For the quarter, earnings from operations were up 24 percent in
entertainment, up 2 percent in cable television and off 10 percent
in broadcasting.
   For the first nine months, Viacom said it earned $142.7 million,
or $2.67 a share, in contrast to a loss of $162.7 million, or $3.05
a share, a year earlier.
   The latest figures include a pre-tax gain of $313.1 million from
the sale of the cable systems on Long Island, N.Y., and in
Cleveland.
   Nine-month revenue rose 16 percent to $1.05 billion from $903.1
million in 1988.
   Viacom is 83-percent owned by National Amusements Inc., a
Dedham, Mass.-based theater chain controlled by Sumner Redstone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
