<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Manville     10-18 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Manville,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manville Reports Drop In Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manville Corp. reported Wednesday that its
third-quarter profit fell 24 percent over a year ago due to
weakness in construction and industrial markets.
   For the three months ended Sept. 30 Manville netted $40.39
million, or 30 cents a share, compared with net income of $53.49
million, or 44 cents, a year ago. Sales were fairly flat, totaling
$549.82 million, vs. $545.86 million in 1988.
   ``We continued to experience strong performances from our
worldwide forest products business,'' said Tom Stephens, Manville
president and chief executive officer. ``However, weaknesses were
seen in our construction and industrial markets resulting in a
fall-off in profitability in our fiber glass and specialty products
segments.''
   Manville also said that its emergence from Chapter 11 federal
bankruptcy reorganization during last year's fourth quarter
continued to impact earnings due partly to increased interest
expenses.
   For the first nine months of this year, Manville's earnings were
$144.14 million, or 91 cents per share, on sales of $1.62 billion.
That compared with a profit of $15.36 million, or 98 cents a share,
and sales of $1.54 billion, last year.
   Manville's primary businesses include wood and paper products,
packaging, fiber glass and industrial insulation products, roofing
systems and filtration and minerals.
</TEXT>
