<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 2010EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Phones 1stLd-Writethru   10-18 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Phones, 1st Ld-Writethru,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ameritech Earnings Up 2.8 Percent While BellSouth Has $$$ Percent
Drop</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede CHICAGO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE with BellSouth results.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Ameritech Corp., the telephone company serving the Midwest, said
Wednesday its third-quarter profits rose 2.8 percent while
BellSouth, another regional phone company, said its earnings dipped
3.6 percent as the firm refinanced long-term debt.
   Ameritech reported earnings of $289.1 million, or $1.06 per
share, for the three months ended Sept. 30, compared with $281.1
million, or $1.03 per share, for the same period a year ago.
   Third-quarter revenue increased 1.9 percent to $2.55 billion
from $2.51 billion, the Chicago-based company said in a prepared
statement.
   ``Increased calling volumes from our regulated business and
continued growth from our unregulated businesses were offset
somewhat by refunds and rate reductions imposed by regulators upon
our Bell operating companies,'' Chairman William L. Weiss said in
the statement.
   Expenses rose 2.6 percent, including one-time, pre-tax charges
of $40 million in signing bonuses related to three-year contract
settlements with the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers and the Communications Workers of America. The CWA
settlement ended an 18-day strike.
   BellSouth reported third-quarter earnings of $404.4 million, or
84 cents per share, down from $419.6 million, or 89 cents per
share, in the same quarter of 1988.
   Revenue rose to $3.55 billion from $3.46 billion a year earlier.
   The Atlanta-based company attributed the earnings decline to
restructuring of $481 million in long-term debt. While the move
resulted in an earnings decline, the company said it would
ultimately save $250 million by refinancing.
   For the first nine months, Ameritech reported its earnings fell
2.3 percent to $906.5 million, or $3.37 per share, from $927.7
million, or $3.40 per share. Revenue for the period rose to $7.6
billion from $7.4 billion.
   The company said the decline in year-to-date earnings reflected
a gain of $42.1 million in last year's second quarter from the sale
of Ameritech's interest in Cantel, a Canadian cellular company, and
its third-quarter 1988 sale of Applied Data Research Inc., a
software subsidiary.
   BellSouth said it earned $1.27 billion, or $2.67 per share, up
2.1 percent from $1.25 billion, or $2.61 per share, for the same
period in 1988.
   BellSouth provides phone service in nine states: Alabama,
Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, Louisiana, Mississippi, North Carolina,
South Carolina and Tennessee.
   Ameritech owns Bell companies serving Illinois, Indiana,
Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
