<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-18 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended weaker Wednesday against key
foreign currencies after a mixed performance overseas, with the
disastrous California earthquake registering only a slight
influence on foreign exchange markets.
   Gold prices rose. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
for current delivery settled at $368.70 a troy ounce, up $1.30 from
Tuesday. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid for
gold of $367.70 an ounce, also $1.30 higher.
   Currency dealers said the dollar sank in overnight trading on
news of the catastrophic earthquake in northern California, but it
regained some ground on the strength of the U.S. stock market.
   Some company stocks, particularly those involved in insurance
and construction, benefited on the belief that business might pick
up during cleanup of the destruction in the San Francisco Bay area.
   Robert Ryan, senior currency trader for the Bank of New York,
said an unconfirmed report that the Federal Reserve moved to buy
dollars early in trading also helped support the dollar. However,
most dealers dismissed those rumors.
   Traders said the market was awaiting Thursday's release of
consumer price index figures for September, hoping they would shed
more light on the direction of the economy and inflation.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell to a closing 142.10 Japanese yen from
142.25 yen Tuesday. It traded at 141.40 yen in London and New York,
compared with 142.70 in New York Tuesday. The dollar was lower
against the British pound. Sterling bought $1.5880 in London, up
from $1.5835 late Tuesday. In New York, the pound was worth
$1.5922, up from $1.57575.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with Tuesday's
quotes included: 1.8485 West German marks, down from 1.8672; 1.6243
Swiss francs, down from 1.6365; 6.2810 French francs, down from
6.3475; 1.17335 Canadian dollars, down from 1.17555; and lira
1,362.00 Italian lire, down from 1,400.00.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Tuesday: 1.8525 West
German marks, up from 1.8520; 1.6255 Swiss francs, up from 1.6227;
6.2990 French francs, up from 6.2960; 2.0818 Dutch guilders, down
from 2.0867; 1.1737 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1755; and
1,366.00 Italian lire, up from 1,365.00.
   Gold gained in London to $368.25 an ounce from $367.75 bid late
Tuesday. In Zurich, gold rose to $368.50 an ounce from $367.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.72 to close at $368.38 an
ounce.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex silver bullion for
current delivery closed at $5.105 a troy ounce, higher than
Tuesday's bid of $5.102. Silver fell in London to $5.11 an ounce
from $5.12.
</TEXT>
