<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   10-18 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices posted modest gains Wednesday as
the market regained its composure after several jumpy sessions.
   Contrary to initial fears, the Northern California earthquake
didn't do much damage to the market. Some companies' stocks
benefited as investors bought on the hunch that business might boom
during the cleanup of the destruction in the San Francisco Bay area.
   Blue chips overcame a late flurry of selling and the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials finished with a gain of 4.92 at 2,643.65.
The key market measure now stands 74.39 points above the level
reached in Friday's 190-point plunge.
   Activity on Wall Street was subdued compared to the wild trading
that began Friday with the worst selloff since the crash of 1987,
which occurred exactly two years ago Thursday.
   Computer-guided maneuvers, which had tugged stock prices up and
down during the three previous sessions, weren't much of a factor
in Wednesday's trading.
   ``I think the market is showing signs of having stabilized.
Volume has moderated and we did not see the violent swings,'' said
Gordon L. Smith, a managing director at Alex. Brown &amp; Sons Inc. in
Baltimore.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board eased to 166.90 million
shares from Tuesday's higher-than-normal 224.07 million shares and
Monday's enormous 416.29 million.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by less than 5 to 4
in nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks,
with 822 up, 668 down and 461 unchanged.
   Despite some early selling on worries about the extent of
liabilities, insurance group stocks generally rose amid speculation
that heavy quake-related claims _ on top of losses from Hurricane
Hugo _ could lead insurers to raise premium rates, enhancing the
industry's profitability.
   There also was speculation that the big temblor Tuesday could
boost demand for earthquake insurance coverage.
   Insurance broker Marsh &amp; McLennan moved up 3 to 75~, General Re
rose 2} to 86{, Aetna Life &amp; Casualty added 2] to 59{ and American
International Group gained 3\ to 102|.
   Among other beneficiaries of the quake-related buying were
stocks of companies in construction, engineering and building
materials. Morrison Knudson rose 2] to 44[, Fluor rose } to 33] and
Georgia Pacific climbed 1\ to 58.
   Meanwhile, Pacific Gas &amp; Electric fell ] to 19| but the San
Francisco-based utility said recovering from the quake wouldn't put
a significant financial strain on the company.
   Chevron, which has its headquarters in San Francisco, rose 1 to
65.
   Other active blue chips included American Telephone &amp; Telegraph,
up \ at 42{, General Electric, down [ to 56] and International
Business Machines, down { to 101}.
   Philip Morris, which reported its third-quarter earnings climbed
20.5 percent, rose [ to 43] on volume of nearly 2.6 million shares,
making it the Big Board's second most heavily traded stock.
   AMR, parent of American Airlines, headed the actives' list, and
more than 2.8 million shares changed hands. It gained } to 74
despite news that its third-quarter earnings fell nearly 9 percent.
   Recent turbulence in the stock market had been intensified by
uncertainty surrounding a proposed buyout of UAL, owner of United
Airlines. The slide in UAL moderated Wednesday as the stock lost 6\
to 191}.
   Retailer Dayton Hudson, a major operator in California, rose 1
to 61[. The company said it will purchase 7 million of its shares
at 62~ under terms of a previously announced ``Dutch auction'' that
expired midnight Oct. 17.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 188.76 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market gained $7.64 billion, or 0.23
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks went
up 0.43 to 189.32.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 0.88 to 390.22, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index finished 0.60 higher at 341.76.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
3.35 to 463.28. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 378.07, up 2.91.
</TEXT>
