<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-18 0709</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Turning Bearish As Copper Prices Dip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices slipped Wednesday to their lowest point
this month on New York's Commodity Exchange and some experts said
the market's 4-month-old rally may be weakening.
   On other commodity markets, precious metals advanced; energy
futures retreated; grains and soybeans were mixed; livestock and
meat futures were mixed; and stock-index futures rose.
   Copper futures settled .40 cent to 2.85 cents lower with the
contract for December delivery at $1.2645 a pound, its lowest close
since Sept. 29.
   Some technical analysts interpreted the break below $1.27 as an
indicator of further losses to come, while fundamental analysts
cited significant changes in supply-and-demand factors.
   Chief among them was a report that the Mexican government was
nearing agreements with labor on terms for reopening the Cananea
copper mining and processing center, which closed Aug. 21 due to
alleged financial mismanagment.
   The mine is capable of producing 160,000 tons of copper
annually, about 3 percent of the world's total copper output.
   ``People were expecting it to open in mid-November but now it
looks like it may open before then,'' said Fred Demler, metals
economist with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   The news came in the aftermath of labor leaders' acceptance in
Canada of a contract that could lead to the reopening of the
Highland Valley copper mine near Logan Lake, B.C., if the agreement
is ratified by the rank-and-file.
   A reopening of the 180,000-tons-per-year Highland Valley mine,
which was shut down by a strike on July 6, would leave the
Bouganville mine in Papua New Guinea as the only major copper mine
still out of commission.
   Meanwhile, a government report of a 5.2 percent drop in U.S.
housing starts last month provided new evidence of economic
weakness and prompted speculation that demand for copper may soften
even as the supply picture improves.
   Analyst James Steel of the commodities brokerage Refco Inc. said
copper's fundamentals appeared to be ``slowly turning'' bearish.
   But Demler said the market's long-term outlook remained bullish.
As for the market's current weakness, he said, ``it's just had a
little bit of a head cold, I guess.''
   In precious-metals trading on the Comex, gold settled $1.30
higher across the board with October at $368.70 a troy ounce;
silver was 0.2 cent to 0.4 cent higher with December at $5.16 a
troy ounce.
   Energy futures ended lower on the New York Mercantile Exchange
in technically inspired selling after gaining initially on supply
fears linked to the earthquake that rocked Northern California
Tuesday night.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 10 cents to 20 cents
lower with November at $20.56 a barrel; heating oil was .29 cent to
.54 cent lower with November at 60.60 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .57 cent to 1.26 cents lower with November at 54.58
cents a gallon.
   Soybean futures rose for the third straight day on the Chicago
Board of Trade amid speculation that the Soviet Union is looking to
buy a large quantity of U.S. soybean oil. Grain futures closed
mixed.
   Wheat settled 3\ cents lower to 3{ cents higher with December at
$4.06\ a bushel; corn was } cent lower to \ cent higher with
December at $2.38\ a bushel; oats were \ cent to 1{ cents higher
with December at $1.44\ a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents to 4}
cents higher with November at $5.59} a bushel.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, strong cash markets
supported the live cattle and hog markets, but pork bellies
weakened amid uncertainty about when the government plans to ship
bellies to Poland as part of a food-aid package.
   Live cattle settled .12 cent lower to .95 cent higher with
October at 74.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent lower
to .07 cent higher with October at 83 cents a pound; live hogs were
.13 cent lower to .72 cent higher with October at 48.72 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies were .45 cent to .80 cent lower with
February at 51.72 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures made modest gains on the Chicago Merc, where
the contract for December delivery of stocks tracked by the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled .65 point higher at 344.65.
</TEXT>
