<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 1820EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SFQuake-Economics     10-18 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Economics,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Problems for Exchange and ATMs, But No Long-Term Economic Problems
Seen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The vigorous economy of the San Francisco Bay
area should be little affected by the earthquake in the long run, a
top state official said Wednesday.
   ``We have a large, strong economy, and while the personal
tragedy for many families is great, the overall economic picture
for the Bay Area and the rest of the state is unclouded by this,''
said John Sullivan, the undersecretary of the state Department of
Business, Transportation and Housing.
   Sullivan, who stayed up all night assessing the situation, said
it was still too early to set a damage figure for the earthquake's
devastation. But he said, ``Overall the impact will be one the
state will recover from very quickly.''
   Insurers said the quake might have caused more than $1 billion
in damages in Northern California, just three weeks after Hurricane
Hugo resulted in an estimated $4 billion in damages in South
Carolina. However, only a fraction of the damages are covered by
insurance.
   Sullivan said he was optimistic about the insurance business.
   ``We don't have huge areas of just massive devastation, block
after block, fortunately,'' Sullivan said.
   While damage appeared extremely heavy in such cities as Santa
Cruz and Watsonville, Farmers Insurance Group Inc. spokesman
Jeffrey Beyer said he tended to agree with Sullivan that most
insurers would have no major problems.
   In a sign of investors' confidence in the state, California
municipal bond issues were down Wednesday, but only slightly and in
line with the overall decline in the market, said Mark Haslinger, a
senior vice president with Clayton Brown &amp; Associates in New York.
   Traders at the Pacific Stock Exchange's main floor in San
Francisco worked by candlelight and flashlight, taking orders that
were then executed in Los Angeles, at the exchange's other trading
floor.
   Volume was ``very, very low,'' said exchange spokesman Navin
Vyas.
   Security Pacific Bank spokesman Richard Warner said his bank had
contacted the state's top 10 banks about setting up a coalition to
provide disaster recovery loans.
   Warner said backup computers kicked into action Tuesday night at
Security Pacific. Other banks and businesses like the San
Francisco-based Charles Schwab &amp; Co. discount brokerage also
reported that emergency systems had taken over and they were
conducting business.
   At Amdahl Corp., a Silicon Valley manufacturer of mainframe
computers, the computer system crashed, then was brought back up _
albeit at one-third the usual speed _ in a backup mode late Tuesday
night.
   Advanced Micro Devices Inc., another big Sunnyvale-based
high-tech company, said it called off the graveyard shift but
normal operations resumed with the start of the day shift.
   Pacific Bell said its network of equipment sustained only minor
damage. But heavy use disrupted calls into and out of the Bay Area
all day long Wednesday.
   State officials worked with businesses and local authorities to
reroute business commuter traffic around the crippled Bay Bridge.
   Banks and savings and loans struggled to reopen branches and
automated teller machines closed by power outages, downed phone
lines and structural damage.
   Many workers at non-essential industries stayed home as advised
by government officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
