<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 2026EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-NYTimes     10-18 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-NY Times,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earnings Sharply Higher in 3rd Qtr Due to Cable System Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Times Co. said Wednesday its
earnings soared eightfold in the third quarter because of a onetime
gain on the sale of its cable television system.
   Excluding the gain, the company said income from continuing
operations fell 34.9 percent from the same period a year earlier.
   New York Times Co. said it earned $210.8 million, or $2.68 per
share, in the three months ended Sept. 30, compared with $26.7
million, or 33 cents a share, a year ago.
   But the company said that excluding the after-tax gain of $193.3
million on the sale of NYT Cable TV and the income from its
operations prior to the sale date, income from continuing
operations fell to $16.4 million from $25.2 million.
   The decline stemmed from dilution due to recent magazine
acquisitions, lower equity earnings from the forest products group
and a decline in ad linage at The New York Times.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 6.4 percent to $415.3 million from
$390.5 million a year ago.
   For the first nine months of 1989, The New York Times Co. said
it earned $285.6 million, or $3.63 a share, compared with $117.2
million, or $1.44 a share, last year. The latest figures included
the gain on the cable sale.
   Nine-month revenue rose 4 percent to $1.30 billion from $1.25
billion a year earlier.
   Income from continuing operations fell to $87.2 million from
$112.5 million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
