<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 2039EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-CommoditiesFine     10-18 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Commodities Fine,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Futures Firm Fined $500,000, Quits Merc</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   CHICAGO _ A commodities trading firm agreed to pay a $500,000
fine and withdraw from membership in the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange to settle charges of improper record-keeping and violating
margin requirements, exchange officials said Wednesday.
   The company, Capcom Futures Inc., withdrew from membership in
the Chicago Board of Trade last summer and a London-based
affiliate, Capcom Financial Services Ltd., was expelled from the
Board of Trade at the same time to settle rule violations similar
to those alleged by the Merc.
   The Merc said Capcom had neither admitted nor denied violating
exchange rules.
   Chicago-based Capcom Futures said in a statement that no
customers had been hurt by its actions and that the alleged
offenses were ``technical in nature and essentially involved
record-keeping matters.''
   The Merc said that on Oct. 6, 1988, in violation of exchange
margin requirements, Capcom accepted trades from a customer while
that customer had a debit balance in another trading account.
   On April 27, 1987, the Merc alleged, Capcom transferred nine
positions into a customer account from other, unaffiliated
customers accounts, a violation of exchange rules.
   The Merc also alleged that from April 1987 through October 1988,
Capcom failed to adequately document certain transactions among
Capcom and individuals and an entity directly or indirectly
controlled by shareholders of Capcom.
   Merc spokesoman Iris Poliski said a firm that withdraws from
exchange membership may re-apply for membership at any time.
   Withdrawal from exchange membership means a firm has voluntarily
left the exchange while expulsion means the firm has been ordered
out by the exchange, said Board of Trade spokesman Michael
O'Connell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
