<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Northrop     10-18 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Northrop,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northrop 3rd Qtr Earnings Off 23 percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northrop Corp. said Wednesday its
third-quarter profit fell 23 percent, due in part to a decline in
research and development work on such projects as the B-2 stealth
bomber.
   Northrop, the focus of repeated investigations and much
congressional criticism for its performance on various government
contracts in recent years, said it earned $21.5 million, or 46
cents per share, for the three months ending Sept. 30, compared
with a profit of $28.8 million, or 61 cents per share, in the same
period a year ago.
   Sales for the third quarter totaled $1.25 billion, down from
$1.36 billion a year earlier.
   The Los Angeles-based company said the B-2, which some in
Congress want to kill as too expensive, has passed the peak of its
development phase and is now in initial production at a low rate.
   The defense contractor, which lost $78.1 million in the second
quarter, also noted that it had made fewer deliveries of its F-A-18
fighters.
   Interest expense in the third quarter was $35 million, $18
million higher than in the same quarter last year. Debt at Sept. 30
was $1.22 billion, compared to $911 million a year earlier.
   Northrop stock closed down 25 cents at $21.12{ a share Wednesday
in composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange. That put the
company's stock's market value below $1 billion _ a very low level
for a company with yearly revenues in the $6 billion range.
</TEXT>
