<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 2045EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-GeneralDynamics     10-18 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-General Dynamics,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Contractor's Profit Flat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Dynamics Corp., the nation's
second-largest defense contractor, reported Wednesday its
third-quarter profit was virtually unchanged from the same quarter
last year.
   The St. Louis-based company said it earned $76.5 million, or
$1.83 a share, compared with $76.4 million, or $1.82 a share, in
1988's third quarter.
   Sales for the quarter, which ended Sept. 30, totaled $2.5
billion, up from with $2.3 billion in last year's third quarter.
   Sales and profits for the first nine months of the year also
were flat.
   A spokesman said that higher-than-expected costs in the joint
development competition for the Air Force's Advanced Tactical
Fighter and delays in F-16 deliveries kept profits from rising in
the most recent quarter.
   The company did get a boost from big profit jumps in its
submarine, general aviation and construction materials
subsidiaries, which account for about 25 percent of its sales.
   ``General aviation experienced its best quarter since Cessna
Aircraft became part of General Dynamics four years ago,'' said
Stanley Pace, chairman and chief executive officer.
   The company said profit for the first nine months of the year
totaled $210 million, or $5.03 per share, on sales of $7.4 billion.
In the first three quarters of 1988, General Dynamics reported
earnings of $209 million, or $4.97 per share, on sales of $7.1
billion.
   Pace said that because the government has changed its method of
buying jets, tanks, submarines and other equipment, General
Dynamics has incurred higher interest expenses.
   For the third quarter, the company's interest expense rose to
$21.5 million, compared with $12.4 million for the same period a
year ago.
   ``These changes have raised the investment and capital
requirements of the defense industry,'' Pace said. ``And while
their impact on the industry is being felt today, their full impact
will be realized over the next several years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
