<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 2107EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Campeau-Christmas     10-18 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Campeau-Christmas,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Campeau Corp. Takes Step To Ensure Supply of Christmas Merchandise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp., fighting its way out of a
financial crisis, is taking steps aimed at assuring uninterrupted
supplies of merchandise to its Allied and Federated department
store divisions for the Christmas shopping season.
   Toronto-based Campeau, whose U.S. retailing operations are based
here, plans to use $80 million backed by letters of credit from the
Canadian Bank of Commerce for security to reassure merchandise
supply firms, Campeau spokeswoman Carol Sanger said.
   She said the credit is intended to reassure suppliers, called
factors, that serve as middlemen by paying manufacturers for goods
and then collecting payments from stores after shipment. The money
would provide additional credit if needed to guarantee shipments,
she said.
   ``It is just a security blanket,'' Ms. Sanger said in an
interview this week. ``It would cover any additional exposure we
might have for the holiday period.''
   Campeau, weighed down by heavy debt it took on to buy Federated
and Allied, suffered a financial and credibility crisis last month
until it obtained a $250 million loan.
   As a condition of making the loan, Olympia &amp; York Developments
Ltd. of Toronto made Toronto businessman Robert Campeau relinquish
control of his retailing and development company.
   The agreement called for up to $150 million of the loan to be
channeled to Campeau's Federated Department Stores Inc. and the
remainder to its Allied Stores Corp. division.
   The money will allow the department store units to meet interest
payments now due on debt and to pay suppliers shipping merchandise
ahead of the critical Christmas season, the most lucrative
retailing time of the year.
   Stores owned by Campeau include the Cincinnati-based Lazarus
group; Bloomingdale's and Abraham &amp; Strauss in New York; Maas
Brothers-Jordan Marsh in Florida; Burdine's in Miami; and Rich's in
Atlanta.
</TEXT>
