<DOCNO> AP891018-0309 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 2332EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-JunkBondDelays     10-18 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Junk Bond Delays,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investment Bankers Delay Two Junk Bond Issues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two investment houses said Wednesday they were
postponing two junk bond issues totaling more than $1.2 billion
because of the upheaval in the market for the high-risk, high-yield
securities.
   One of the offerings, for $1.1 billion, was for the Grand Union
Co., a supermarket operator. The second, for $156 million, was for
Ethan Allen &amp; Co., the furniture store chain.
   An official at Salmon Brothers Inc. told The New York Times that
it had ended its ``road show'' for the Grand Union offering, in
which the investment house travels around the nation to drum up
buyers for the bonds.
   A Salomon spokesman told the newspaper that the investment firm
was waiting for the junk bond market to settle down before it would
again try to sell the issue.
   A group that bought Grand Union last spring needed to issue the
bonds to help pay for the purchase from British financier Sir James
Goldsmith. The buyout group included Salomon.
   Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. said it delayed the Ethan Allen junk bond
sale until market conditions were calmer.
   ``We had hoped to start this week,'' said James A. Mullin, a
managing director at the firm. ``Things are pretty tough.''
   Ethan Allen was sold last year to a group of its managers by the
conglomerate Interco Inc.
   The junk bond market has been unsettled since last month when
Campeau Corp., the Canadian company than owns many U.S. department
store chains, said it would have trouble making payments on its
large junk-bond debt.
   The market took another hit when stock prices plunged Friday on
the news that a group seeking to buy airline company UAL Corp.
could not find financing. Junk bonds are so named because they are
issued by companies that have a poor credit rating.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
